<1ST_LINE>u i AM-China-Capsize 1stLd-Writethru   07-22 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Capsize, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0679,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rescuers Continue Search For Survivors, Fifth Body Found</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New 10 grafs to UPDATE with newspaper reporting 10 bodies
recovered, official saying no accurate estimates of those on board;
picks up 5th graf, Among those ... Minor editing to TRIM</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newspaper said Saturday that rescuers have
pulled 10 bodies from a southwest China river after a boat
capsized, but authorities were still not sure how many more are
missing.
   The overseas edition of the official People's Daily said
Saturday that 10 bodies had been found and 148 people had been
rescued from the fast-moving waters of the Min River, a tributary
of the Yangtze in Sichuan province.
   The daily said 16 of the rescued had been hospitalized.
   The official Xinhua News Agency in a report late Friday said 152
people had been rescued after the boat hit a rock and sank.
   It was not known if any foreigners were on the boat.
   Xinhua reported Thursday that 250 people were on the boat, but
local officials said by telephone Friday the exact number of
passengers was not known because the boat made frequent stops.
   Another report in the Peasant Daily said the boat was carrying
its capacity of 324.
   Tang Langmin, an official of the Chongqing Shipping Co., owners
of the vessel, told The Associated Press that there are still no
accurate estimates of those on board.
   Tang said the cause of the accident is still not clear, although
earlier reports said the boat hit a rock.
   He said it is unlikely that there were any foreigners aboard
because the area is still closed to foreign visitors.
   Among those rescued were 16 crew members, China News Service
said. It said six people required hospitalization but did not give
details of their injuries.
   The report quoted Sichuan officials as saying rescue work was
difficult because the accident occurred in a remote area and the
river level was high.
   The boat sank in Qianwei County, about 116 miles south of the
provincial capital of Chengdu.
   Xinhua said an investigation was under way.
   Sichuan Gov. Zhang Haoru and Vice Gov. Ma Lin went to the scene,
said an official at the Foreign Affairs Office in nearby Leshan,
contacted by telephone.
</TEXT>
