<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Drought-OhioRiver     07-22 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Ohio River,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Barge Traffic Flowing More Freely on Ohio</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOUND CITY, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Recent rains in the nation's midsection
have raised the waters of the Ohio River enough to clear a logjam
of barge traffic that has existed for weeks, the Coast Guard said
Friday.
   The Ohio River, like the Mississippi and Missouri, had shrunk to
all-time lows earlier this month. At one point, 84 barge tows were
backed up on the Ohio near this Southern Illinois town a few miles
north of the the point where the Ohio meets the Mississippi.
   But by Friday evening, all backed-up barges had cleared the area
and all size restrictions on the tows were lifted, said Coast Guard
Ensign Rick Johnson.
   Upriver at Louisville, the Ohio averaged 5 billion gallons of
water a day during the first half of the month _ 84 percent below
normal, the U.S. Geological Survey said.
   The current flow rate wasn't available Friday, but during one
24-hour period this week the river rose 5 feet, Johnson said. The
river stage at Cairo was 6.1 feet Tuesday and 12.69 feet Friday, he
said.
   However, the Coast Guard continued to rout traffic one way at a
time through an auxiliary channel near Mound City while a dredge
scooped out silt from the main route.
   ``It still has a lot of work to do in the area,'' Johnson said.
   The question of whether barge traffic continues to flow freely
will be answered by the amount of rainfall, he added.
   ``I don't know how long it will stay this way,'' Johnson said.
``If we get a dry spell like we've been having, the river will go
right back down and we'll be back where we were.''
</TEXT>
