<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AsbestosSuit     07-22 0264</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Asbestos Suit,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Overturns Combination Of 35,000 Asbestos Suits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court has overturned a judge's
decision to combine 35,000 asbestos-related lawsuits against a
Chicago company after some of those who filed the suits objected.
   Last month, U.S. District Judge Robert L. Vining Jr.
consolidated 35,000 personal injury law suits pending against
Raymark Industries Inc. in response to a defense motion in an
asbestos-related injury claim of an Atlanta couple.
   That decision, which had created one of the largest personal
injury cases and the largest asbestos-related injury case ever, was
overturned by three judges of the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals.
   According to federal court records, more than 100 plaintiffs
objected to having their lawsuits against Raymark consolidated into
one complaint because none of them had been notified about legal
efforts that sought the class action. The plaintiffs also
complained that the evidence considered by the federal court was
not enough to justify such a major decision.
   In an order Wednesday, Judge Frank Johnson wrote that the
``District Court's order will delay resolution of their claims
indefinitely.''
   ``The court's order, which essentially moves their cases back to
square one, could hardly place petitioners in a more drastic
predicament,'' wrote Johnson.
   Raymark has been the target of 70,000 personal injury lawsuits
involving 82,000 people in the past 10 years. The suits claim that
people developed asbestos-related diseases after exposure to
insulation and other Raymark products at construction and
shipbuilding sites and factories.
   Half of the 70,000 cases already have been resolved by trial,
out-of-court settlement or dismissal.
</TEXT>
