<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Reagan-Nicaragua     07-22 0631</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Nicaragua,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White House Still Not Saying Whether It Will Seek Military Contra
Aid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House is pushing for a
``strong, meaningful, bipartisan package'' of aid to Nicaraguan
rebels, but is stopping short of saying whether the package should
include lethal military assistance.
   ``It is something that we're going to be discussing with the
congressional leadership next week,'' White House chief of staff
Kenneth M. Duberstein said Thursday as he briefed reporters after a
meeting of top presidential aides on foreign and domestic issues.
   He said Reagan, who winds up a weeklong vacation at his ranch
north of Santa Barbara on Sunday, will meet with Republican
congressional leaders on Tuesday.
   Duberstein said Thursday's 3{-hour meeting of 15 of Reagan's top
aides was designed to lay out ``a positive, energetic, active last
six months of his presidency to reinforce the themes of the first
7{ years.''
   Reagan's second term will end Jan. 20.
   ``The staff input today was to go forward on a strong,
meaningful bipartisan package on Contra aid, and it is something
that we will be talking to the leadership about next week,''
Duberstein said.
   The chief of staff did not reply directly, however, when asked
whether the administration would press for lethal as well as
humanitarian assistance.
   ``It is something that we are going to be working with the
Congress to make sure that we can get as much as possible to
support the peace efforts that we have under way,'' he said.
   It was not the first time the administration has struck a note
of reticence as it weighs new approaches for dealing with the
increasingly defiant leftist government of Nicaragua in the wake of
congressional action in February cutting off military aid to the
rebels.
   In a June 18 radio address, the president said the congressional
cutoff of aid was ``a dangerous gamble with our national security''
and added, ``We must work for a free Nicaragua ... but time is
growing short.'' He did not, however, spell out what steps should
be taken.
   On June 29, speaking in support of Republican senatorial
candidate Rep. Connie Mack III in Miami, he said, again without
being specific, ``Connie Mack and I stand with the Nicaraguan
resistance; we will not rest until we have won for them the full
support they need.''
   Then, on July 13, Reagan was asked whether he was going to
request military aid and responded, ``I'm trying to consider ...
whether I should answer that or not. It's almost like giving
something away while we're still at work.'' He never did answer.
   On July 15, the president ducked a question as to whether there
was now a consensus in Congress for lethal aid, saying, ``I'm not
in a position to estimate or make any count of that.''
   In a speech in Los Angeles on Tuesday, Lt. Gen. Colin L. Powell,
the president's national security adviser, said Congress and the
president need to ``come to agreement on a program of effective aid
for the Nicaraguan resistance as an adjunct to our diplomatic
strategy.''
   But Powell did not define ``effective,'' any more than Reagan
said what he meant by ``full support'' or Duberstein by
``meaningful'' assistance.
   Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole, R-Kan., has introduced a bill
that would provide for humanitarian assistance and put some lethal
aid in an escrow account to be released if the president certified
it was needed.
   ``We're going to take a look at the Dole package, which we have
generally supported, and talk with others on the hill as far as
getting cosponsors and making sure that it is something that we can
get through the Senate and that will provide for the needs that we
see,'' Duberstein said.
</TEXT>
