<1ST_LINE>r w PM-NuclearComponents     07-22 0507</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nuclear Components,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NRC, Nuclear Industry Focus on Substandard Materials in Power
Plants</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nuclear Regulatory Commission and U.S.
nuclear industry are undertaking stepped-up efforts to deal with
the use of substandard components in nuclear power plants,
according to NRC officials.
   They told a commission briefing Thursday that although the
problem is serious, it does not appear to pose immediate safety
hazards.
   ``We have a very serious issue before us,'' said NRC Chairman
Lando W. Zech Jr. ``We've just got to get our arms around it and
find out exactly how big the problem is.''
   At issue are components ranging from defective bolts and other
fasteners to used circuit breakers that were falsely labeled as new
and first discovered this spring at a California nuclear power
plant.
   Thomas Murley, the NRC's director of reactor regulation, said
his office has issued special information bulletins to nuclear
plant operators and was cooperating with the agency's office of
investigations.
   Possible changes in NRC regulations are being considered to help
deal with the components problem, he said, but ``it's too early to
tell where that will lead us.''
   Murley said he believes the ``great majority of deficiencies''
in plant equipment will be spotted through regular checks as part
of the NRC's quality assurance program.
   ``Still, we acknowledge that the quality assurance program is
not perfect,'' he said.
   Overall, Murley said, ``our conclusion is that we must continue
to deal with the problem, but there is no immediate safety issue.''
   Victor Stello, the NRC's executive director for operations,
said, ``I am persuaded that the (nuclear) industry now recognizes
that they do indeed have a serious problem.''
   The NRC announced earlier this month that it was investigating
five California companies for their alleged role in supplying used
circuit breakers falsely labeled as new equipment.
   After seizing documents during searches at the companies'
offices, the NRC sent notices July 8 to nuclear plants across the
country.
   The used circuit breakers, which serve the same function as
fuses in shutting off power to prevent short circuits or fires,
were first discovered at the Diablo Canyon nuclear power plant near
San Luis Obispo, Calif., when they failed tests there in April.
   In June, Stello told a House Energy and Commerce subcommittee
that more than half of the country's 109 nuclear reactors had some
substandard studs and bolts in safety-related locations.
   Stello testified that the problem stemmed from failure to test
crucial steel bolts that suppliers sold to reactor operators as
being resistant to bending under stress.
   Members of the subcommittee asserted that some of the suppliers
may have profited by deliberately marketing weak fasteners falsely
labeled as ``high tensile.''
   According to information supplied by the NRC to the House panel,
utilities operating 66 reactors in 31 states had reported the
presence of bad bolts. Eight to 10 percent of a small sample
surveyed by the utilities last fall at the agency's request were
below required specifications for tensile strength, hardness,
resistance to stretching or chemical composition.
</TEXT>
