<HEAD>On The Last Night: Still More Parties</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 3rd graf pvs bgng, `As the,' with 6 grafs to UPDATE with
Dukakis, Bentsen, attending party, comments, editing for transition</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The final night of the Democratic National
Convention had at least one thing in common with the first three.
Parties.
   The last night on the party circuit included a large ``Victory
'88'' party at the Georgia World Congress Center, next door to the
convention hall, and planned bashes by the Michael Dukakis-Lloyd
Bentsen and Jesse Jackson campaigns.
   Dukakis and Bentsen received thunderous applause from a crowd of
thousands _ delegates and others who attended or worked at the
convention _ when they walked across the street at the close of the
convention to the ``Victory '88'' party.
   ``This has been a great convention and it sets the stage for a
great Democratic victory in November of 1988,'' Dukakis told the
throng after thanking Atlanta Mayor Andrew Young and the city of
Atlanta for hosting the convention.
   Later, he warned his supporters not to ease up their support for
the ticket: ``We're going to need you all. This is going to be a
tough, tight, competitive race.''
   When he completed his five minutes of impromptu remarks, an
orchestra started playing Greek tunes and Dukakis danced two or
three steps, setting off wild cheers.
   Bentsen said the convention had produced ``the most enthusiastic
and united Democratic party that I have ever seen.''
   Earlier in the evening, when convention activities got under way
at The Omni, contributors to the Democratic Party of Georgia
mingled over drinks at a party next door at the Omni Hotel.
   At first, journalists were denied entrance. ``This is private _
you know, for muckety-mucks,'' said Democratic doorkeeper Scott
Sikes.
   But reporters later were admitted, and inside the reception room
were the backbone of any successful political endeavor _ the
non-famous loyalists who give money.
   The contributors watched on giant-screen TV as Georgia high
school bands marched in the convention hall, and they stood up,
drinks held aloft, as Lynda Carter sang the national anthem.
   Just down Marietta Street at the Metroplex rock nightclub,
ticket prices were cut from $10 to $6 for the final night of the
``Alternative '88'' convention. A scheduled appearance by comedian
Pat Paulsen was cancelled, but alternative conventioneers could
hear three rock bands and a political satirist-comic.
   Also planned was an ``Austin to Boston'' party hosted by the
Massachusetts and Texas delegations, which expected appearances by
Dukakis and Bentsen.
</TEXT>
