<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     07-22 0620</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Air Force Arguments in Radioactive Spill Detailed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Air Force has acknowledged that its
initial report on a 1986 radioactive spill at an Ohio military base
was incomplete, but is protesting a proposed fine as unwarranted,
Air Force documents show.
   The documents, released Thursday by the Nuclear Regulatory
Commission, were prepared by the Air Force in response to a
proposed fine of $102,500 by the NRC in connection with the
incident at Wright-Patterson Air Force Base near Dayton.
   The NRC said the proposed fine is for willful failure to report
the spill within 24 hours and for the internal exposure of an
individual to the radioactive powder.
   However, the Air Force argued that under the facts of the
incident, the requirements do not clearly mandate a report within
24 hours.
   ``Through a chain of errors, but without any intent to withhold
information or deceive, the subsequent report from the (Air Force)
was neither full nor complete,'' Gary Vest, deputy assistant
secretary of the Air Force, told the NRC. ``In addition, the
reporting regulation itself is ambiguous.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>FCC Says It Won't Tolerate Satellite TV Pirates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission says it
is ``putting the public on notice'' that it will no longer tolerate
pirates who market illegal descrambling devices for backyard
satellite dishes.
   ``We will put them out of business and, if we can, put them in
jail,'' FCC Chairman Dennis Patrick said at a news conference
Thursday.
   Patrick said the FCC is sending warning letters to 19 firms that
the FCC believes sell the technology that enables a dish owner to
decode the scrambled signals used by premium program services like
Home Box Office and Showtime.
   Using such illegal devices allows a dish owner to receive the
broadcasts without having to pay the fees charged by the
programmers or the cable firms authorized to retransmit their
signals.
   `` We're putting the public on notice that we will no longer
look the other way,'' Patrick said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>U.S. Welcomes Vietnamese Offer To Help Locate Missing Americans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States is welcoming Vietnam's offer
to work with U.S. officials to resolve the cases of Americans
missing from the Vietnam War.
   U.S. and Vietnamese officials will meet next week in Hanoi to
discuss joint efforts to search for those still listed as missing,
an administration spokesman said Thursday.
   U.S. officials also welcomed a statement by the Vietnamese
foreign minister, Nguyen Co Thach, that he would try to resolve by
the end of year 70 so-called discrepancy cases, among them,
Americans believed to have been captured by the Vietnamese.
   ``We are pleased to confirm that Vietnam has offered to work
jointly with the United States on concerted efforts to resolve the
issue of American military and civilian personnel still missing and
unaccounted for from the Vietnam war,'' said State Department
spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley.
