<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nicaraguan Envoy Rebuffed In Effort To Return To U.S.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nicaraguan Ambassador Carlos Tunnermann was
rebuffed by U.S. officials on a request to return to the United
States to resume his duties as Sandinista representative to the
Organization of American States.
   In rejecting Tunnerman's visa request, State Department deputy
spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said Thursday that he had abused his
privileges of residence in the United States and therefore is not
welcome in this country.
   Tunnermann and seven Nicaraguan colleagues were expelled from
the United States last week after Sandinista authorities ordered
home eight U.S. diplomats from Managua, including Ambassador
Richard Melton.
   Tunnermann, who served as both ambassador to the United States
and the OAS, denied the charges and said the administration had
exceeded its authority in expelling a diplomat accredited to the
OAS.
