<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--RepublicanVersion     07-22 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Republican Version,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Republicans Spend Week Sounding Themes That Will Return</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican ``truth squads'' spent the week trying
hard to rain on the Democrats' convention parade, but they also
began to spell out themes that will become grindingly familiar by
November.
   ``To the extent they have some staying power, I think you will
hear them again,'' said Rich Galen, a spokesman for the National
Republican Congressional Committee.
   Beginning last Friday with Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole,
the GOP flew in party officials each day to criticize the Michael
Dukakis-Lloyd Bentsen ticket.
   Dukakis sought all week to reach out to moderate and
conservative Democrats by picking Bentsen and insisting on a
platform that was deliberately brief.
   The Republicans, however, tried to link him with Jesse Jackson
and attacked ``deception'' in the platform. Their goal was to tag
Dukakis with a liberal label, or ``the `L' word'' as one described
it.
   ``You don't have to be a political genius to figure out that the
Republicans will want to make that point,'' Galen said. ``You don't
have to be a genius to point at that Mike Dukakis is a proud
liberal.
   ``You want to force him back to his home base,'' he said. ``The
overall strategy was to set that out as a framework.''
   In their final session on Thursday, however, a panel of GOP
officials broadened the assault, and claimed a ``Democratic sleaze
factor'' has effectively defused ethical questions which have long
swirled around the Reagan administration, most recently around
Attorney General Edwin Meese.
   They noted there's been almost no rhetoric about Meese during
the week, though Democrats had badly wanted to make him a campaign
issue.
   Rep. Guy Vander Jagt, R-Mich., said Democrats were embarrassed
by House Speaker Jim Wright's role in presiding over the convention
despite ethical questions which have been raised about him.
   ``I think they have felt uncomfortable talking about sleaze when
the camera right over the shoulder of the speaker focuses on Jim
Wright,'' said Vander Jagt.
   Mike McCurry, spokesman for the Democratic convention, said the
Democrats have steered away from highlighting Meese's problems
because ``we felt in was important to stay focused on delivering a
positive message about what Democrats would do.''
   The Republicans also worked hard to emphasize divisions on the
Dukakis-Bentsen ticket. Vander Jagt argued that Dukakis seemed like
a moderate during the primaries only because he was running against
Jesse Jackson.
   With the more conservative Bentsen at his side, Vander Jagt
said, voters will begin to view Dukakis as a liberal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
