<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--DNCMeeting     07-22 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--DNC Meeting,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Top Democratic Panel Adding More Jackson Backers</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Meeting convenes at 10:30 a.m. EDT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democratic National Committee is expanding
its membership and officers to make room for more Jesse Jackson
supporters, a key provision of the unity agreement between Jackson
and party nominee Michael Dukakis.
   The deal between Dukakis and Jackson, announced on Monday, ended
tensions between the two camps and cleared the way for the peaceful
and united Democratic National Convention that ended its four-day
run here Thursday night.
   The changes in the national party's structure are intended to
meet the presidential runner-up's demand that the DNC be more
reflective of the rank and file.
   DNC chairman Paul Kirk said he was backing the changes ``in
order to give real meaning to the politics of inclusion and
expansion ... building on the important efforts that Rev. Jackson
has made to expand the party's base.''
   The two most important changes up for DNC approval today would
add a fourth vice chairman and eight new at-large members to the
panel.
   The new vice chairman will be designated to head the party's
voter registration and mobilization efforts _ a focus of Jackson's
efforts for many years. The current three spots traditionally go to
a woman, a black and a Hispanic.
   The new at-large seats boost that group to 33, all of whom are
nominated by the chairman. Jackson convention manager Ron Brown
said this week that Jackson would get roughly half the new at-large
seats.
   All these changes have to be written into the party's charter,
requiring a two-thirds vote of the full committee.
</TEXT>
