<HEAD>Abu Nidal Denies Staging Attack On Greek Cruise Ship</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Abu Nidal's Palestinian terrorist group
denied accusations that it staged the attack on a Greek cruise ship
that left nine people dead and 98 wounded.
   A statement Thursday from Abu Nidal's Fatah-Revolutionary
Council said the man named by Greek police as the leader of the
July 11 terrorist raid on the liner City of Poros has been dead
since 1985.
   ``In light of the American allegations that charged our movement
with what happened to the Greek ship ... and what was attributed to
the Greek security minister, I assert that our group has no
connection with this incident,'' said the statement signed by Atef
Abu Bakr, official spokesman for the group.
   ``I also declare that Khadar Samir Mohammed, whose name has been
mentioned, gained the honor of martyrdom in 1985 and this was
officially reported at the time,'' the statement said. It did not
say where or how he died.
   Anastassios Sehiotis, Greek public order minister, said
Wednesday that Hejab Jaballa, whom he accused of leading the
attack, was actually Mohammed. Greek police said the fingerprints
of the two were identical.
   Abu Nidal, whose real name is Sabry al-Banna, has been blamed
for many terrorist attacks, including those on the Rome and Vienna
airports in December 1985 in which 22 people were killed and more
than 80 wounded.
