<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-88 0432EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Nicaragua     07-22 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua,0441</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sandinistas Say Bermudez's Election Jeopardizes Peace Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ruling Sandinistas say the
election of a guerrilla military leader to a key political role in
the rebel movement will jeopardize prospects for negotiating a
permanent peace.
   A Sandinista army officer, meanwhile, said 34 rebels were killed
during a series of attacks by guerrillas earlier this week.
   The election on Monday of Col. Enrique Bermudez to the political
directorate of the rebels' Nicaraguan Resistance umbrella
organization ``makes the possibility of negotiating peace even more
remote,'' the Sandinista National Liberation Front's newspaper
Barricada said in an editorial.
   Bermudez was elected by rebel delegates to a meeting in the
Dominican Republic. His election ``removes the civilian mask'' from
the U.S.-backed Contra movement, Barricada says.
   Bermudez, commander of the main rebel army known as the
Nicaraguan Democratic Force, was a colonel in the national guard of
the right-wing Somoza dynasty that ruled Nicaragua for 42 years
until it was overthrown by the leftist Sandinistas in July 1979.
   Barricada said Bermudez's election ``ratified the Somoza
leadership in the (rebel) movement.''
   Maj. Ramon Caldera, chief of the general staff for the Fifth
Military Region, said government troops under his command repelled
rebel attacks Tuesday that were intended to disrupt celebrations
marking the ninth anniversary of the Sandinista regime. He said 34
Contras were killed.
   Caldera also said the Contras were secretly supplied with
weapons in four airdrops in northeastern Nueva Guinea province
during the first 15 days of July.
   Caldera made his remarks at a ceremony marking the discharge of
12,000 government troops from active service. He gave no details on
the attacks in central Chontales province and northern Boaca
province and did not mention government casualties.
   A Defense Ministry statement said two rebels died Wednesday when
a Contra group attacked an army patrol in Buenos Aires, about 148
miles north of the capital. It said Contras kidnapped six civilians
in the northern part of the country on Sunday and Tuesday.
   The statement, which gave no details, also said six rebels
deserted to Sandinista forces this week.
   A cease-fire has been in effect since March 21 in the 7-year-old
war between the Sandinista government and the Contras. Each side
has accused the other of violating the truce.
   President Daniel Ortega on Tuesday announced a unilateral
government extension of the cease-fire to Aug. 30. It had been set
to expire at the end of this month.
   No talks are scheduled to reach a lasting peace agreement. The
last round broke off in June.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
