<DOCNO> AP880722-0048 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-88 0440EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ContraRift     07-22 0396</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Contra Rift,0407</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contras Insist Military Split Not a Crisis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contra leaders still may be able to negotiate with
seven field commanders who resigned to protest the growing power of
a hard-line military leader, a spokesman says.
   ``There is no crisis,'' Bosco Matamoros, spokesman for
Nicaraguan Resistance, the Contra umbrella group, said Thursday.
``We had a generational change within our forces.''
   The seven commanders abandoned their southern front commands
Tuesday after the election of Enrique Bermudez _ who was already
the rebel military chief _ to the Contra ruling body. In May,
Bermudez forced out five major northern front military officials
who had demanded his resignation.
   The seven commanders denounced the election of Bermudez in
Nicaragua as an attempt by ``the extreme right'' to gain control of
the Contra movement.
   ``The commanders have the right to express their opinion,''
Matamoros said. ``Our organization is composed of volunteers.''
   But the resignations may not be final, he added.
   ``We will talk to them and see if they will reconsider,'' said
Matamoros.
   He claimed the dissidents command only ``a few hundred'' troops.
But the seven commanders, some of whom were important enough to
participate directly in recent peace talks with the Sandinistas,
say they represent all 2,700 rebel fighters on Nicaragua's southern
front along the Costa Rican border.
   Like dissidents before them on the northern front based in
Honduras, the southern commanders attacked Bermudez for corruption,
inefficiency and his close links to the hated National Guard of
deposed dictator Anastasio Somoza Debayle. Bermudez was a colonel
in the guard before Somoza was overthrown by the Sandinistas in
1979.
   They also complained their troops are not receiving U.S.
humanitarian aid, unlike Bermudez's forces. From the beginning, the
southern front guerrillas have received but a fraction of the U.S.
aid given the larger, better known northern front Contra army.
   Matamoris said the newly elected seven-member directorate has
not issued any statements about the dissidents.
   The split is only the latest in a growing rift among Contra
leaders and military commanders. One issue is the peace talks with
the Sandinistas, which the dissidents accuse Bermudez of trying to
sabotage.
   Pedro Joaquin Chamorro, formerly the most liberal of the
directors and a spokesman for the dissidents, was dumped from the
ruling body during the Contra assembly meeting in the Dominican
Republic last weekend.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
