<HEAD>Highlights of Final Day's Developments at Convention</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are developments on the final
day of the Democratic National Convention:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>DUKAKIS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis starts campaigning today as the Democratic
Party's official nominee for president. Declaring ``the Reagan era
is over and a new era is about to begin,'' the son of Greek
immigrants accepted his party's nomination Thursday night.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>BENTSEN</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, winning the Democratic vice
presidential nomination by acclamation, acknowledged philosophical
differences with Dukakis but said the two agree ``on the basic
issues of justice and opportunity.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>JACKSON</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The convention crowd exploded in cheers as onetime rival Jesse
Jackson strode on stage to shake hands with Dukakis, the man he
failed to defeat, and with Bentsen, whose job he wanted as a
consolation prize.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>DEMOCRATIC STRATEGY</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Dukakis' aides say he will contest every state with Vice
President George Bush, who will get the Republican presidential
nomination at the GOP convention in New Orleans Aug. 15-18.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>BUSH</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Bush says the Democratic ticket will self-destruct because
Dukakis is a liberal and Bentsen is a conservative. ``I can't wait
for the debates _ Dukakis vs. Bentsen,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>POLL</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The convention appears to have helped Dukakis nationally. An ABC
poll taken Wednesday found the Democratic ticket with a 53 percent
to 41 percent lead over Bush, a significant jump from a 46-45
Republican lead in a poll taken Sunday.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>TV NETWORKS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The Omni may have been turned into a big television studio, but
viewers weren't turning on their sets. Low ratings this week caused
them to think about cutting back on prime-time coverage. Network
ratings have been about 10 percent lower than in 1984.
</TEXT>
