<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SiblingCustody Bjt   07-22 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sibling Custody, Bjt,0528</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brother Named Guardian of Five Orphaned Brothers and Sisters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATALINA ORTIZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAYWARD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At age 24, Frank Montenegro Jr. felt he
was just starting adulthood, working at his first teaching job in
San Diego.
   But he willingly surrendered his bachelor life and went to court
to become the father of five younger siblings, who faced being
split up and sent to foster homes after their parents died within
three months of each other.
   Montenegro says he was determined to keep the family together.
   ``All of a sudden, you go from raising yourself to taking care
of five others,'' he said.
   Montenegro, who left his job and moved back to Northern
California to become head of the grieving household, was named
legal guardian Wednesday of three brothers and two sisters.
   The only condition the judge attached to the decision was that
Montenegro post a $25,000 security bond to protect the family in
case of his death.
   ``Who won? Who won?'' asked 8-year-old Jaime Montenegro, tugging
at his brother's trousers after a brief hearing in Alameda County
Superior Court.
   ``We won,'' said Montengro, the oldest of a family of eight
children orphaned earlier this year through the deaths of their
parents.
   Genevieve Montenegro, 42, died in March from a blood clot after
giving birth to a daughter. In May, Frank Montenegro Sr., 46, died
when he lost control of his van and crashed on a freeway off-ramp
near the family's home in Hayward, across the bay from San
Francisco.
   The couple's five dependent children could have been declared
wards of the court and placed in foster homes, but Montengro went
to court seeking guardianship.
   ``It has to be that way,'' he said. ``You have to have a
family.''
   Montenegro shrugged his shoulders when asked if he had any
regrets about assuming responsibility _ on a teacher's salary _ for
Philip, 16; Jaime, 8; Joaquin, 6; Genevieve, 5; and 4-month-old
Nicole, who has Down's syndrome.
   ``There's obviously going to be problems but you have to raise
your family,'' he said.
   The new family man runs the household with the help of three
aunts. Two younger brothers on their own _ Peter, 22, and Manuel,
19 _ also help from time to time.
   The community also has helped the Montenegros, raising money to
help pay for the parents' funerals and medical expenses for a
two-day hospital stay for Nicole, who caught pneumonia in May. A
trust fund at a Hayward bank had reached more than $8,600 as of
Wednesday.
   Montenegro is teaching summer school at an Oakland church, but
the family's finances will improve this fall, when he begins a
$23,000-a-year job as a bilingual teacher at an elementary school
in Fremont.
   Montenegro, while relieved at Wednesday's ruling, knows the
family's problems aren't over. ``That's one step toward raising
them up. We're just starting down that road,'' he said.
   His lawyer, Adele Fenstermacher, who volunteered her services,
is confident the Montengros will succeed.
   ``If there's anyone capable of doing it,'' she said, ``it's
Frank.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880722-0052 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-88 0531EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Korea     07-22 0682</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea,0701</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Politicians Seek Unified Positive Response To North's Proposal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korean political leaders said
today they would try to respond positively to a North Korean call
for talks on a non-aggression pact between the two bitter rivals.
   Leaders of the south's four main political parties said they
would cooperate with each other to produce a united response by the
end of next week that could clear the way for talks.
   ``We will make efforts to seek an early realization of
inter-Korea parliamentary talks,'' said opposition leader Kim
Dae-jung.
   Communist North Korea sent an invitation Thursday to the South
Korean National Assembly for talks with the Supreme People's
Assembly in Pyongyang on a non-aggression pact drawn up by the
communist north.
   South Korean government and opposition leaders said preliminary
negotiations would be needed to work out the terms and details
before any agreement could be reached on parliamentary talks.
   Kim, opposition leaders Kim Young-sam and Kim Jong-pil and
government Democratic Justice Party chairman Yoon Gil-joong said
they would try to use the north's proposals to promote contacts to
ease tension on the divided peninsula.
   South Korean Defense Minister Oh Ja-bok warned senior commanders
today that the north had substantial military superiority over the
south and its forces were poised for a lightning attack.
   The North Korean proposal received modest coverage in the South
Korean media. Many observers said the proposal did not appear to be
a major new development.
   The rival Koreas have presented a series of proposals in recent
months to ease tension and establish peace on the divided
peninsula. But each side has tended to ignore the other's
proposals, insisting its plans be followed.
   Talks between parliamentary delegations on a non-aggression pact
collapsed in 1986 when North Korea pulled out to protest routine
U.S.-South Korean military exercises. Similar efforts in the early
1970s also failed to make any progress.
   A government spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
talks between the rival governments should be held at the same time
as the parliamentary talks. He said any decision on a pact by the
south would be taken by the Seoul administration.
   South Korean insistence on inter-government talks could block
the parliamentary talks, since North Korea has been refusing to
deal with the Seoul government. Both governments claim they are the
sole legitimate government of Korea.
   North Korea refused to accept letters earlier this month from
the Seoul government calling for political, economic and
humanitarian talks on easing relations. South Korean President Roh
Tae-woo called for a major peace effort, but the north refused to
accept the letter outlining the proposal.
   North Korea has been insisting for months it wants to deal
directly with the ``people'' in the south and has continued to
denounce the Seoul government as a U.S.-backed puppet regime. It
apparently sent a letter to the National Assembly for this reason.
   The South Korean government and the opposition-dominated
National Assembly agree any talks with the north must be under the
administration's direction. Any North Korean delegation at peace
talks would be under direct government control because the north's
assembly is a powerless, rubberstamp body.
   South Korean political parties all support peaceful
reunification, but also fear the north remains determined to extend
communist rule over the peninsula.
   Political leaders in Seoul expressed concern North Korea did not
respond to the National Assembly's call to take part in the 1988
Olympic Games in Seoul. The North Korean proposal was in response
to the assembly's call for Pyongyang not to boycott the Games.
   North Korea has been demanding to co-host the Olympics, but
international Olympic officials said the Games can only be awarded
to a single city.
   The Korean peninsula was divided by U.S. and Soviet forces that
ended the Japanese occupation at the end of World War II. Efforts
to reunite the peninsula failed and separate governments were
declared in 1948.
   The communist north invaded the south in 1950 to start the
Korean War. About 42,000 U.S. troops are based in the south under a
mutual defense treaty.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
