<DOCNO> AP880722-0056 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-88 0606EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CVN--Quotes     07-22 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Quotes,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>What the Politicians Were Saying</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   MICHAEL DUKAKIS, in his speech accepting the Democratic
nomination for president, rallying his party to battle Republican
Vice President George Bush: ``It's time to rekindle the American
spirit of invention and daring, to exchange voodoo economics for
can-do economics, to build the best America by bringing out the
best in every American.''
   
   LLOYD BENTSEN, in his speech accepting the vice-presidential
nomination, acknowledging that he and Dukakis differ on some
issues: ``We Democrats do not march in lockstep behind some narrow,
rigid ideology. ... We are not gray grains of oatmeal in a bland
porridge of privilege. ... Of course we have differences of
opinion. But on the basic issues of justice and opportunity, we
stand united.''
   
   BENTSEN, on how he will campaign against Bush: ``Mine will not
be a personal attack. He's a friend of mine, and our wives are
friends. We're talking about differences on issues and differences
on results.''
   
   JESSE JACKSON, after saying he didn't feel let down by losing
the nomination: ``Our work continues ... this quest for jobs and
peace and justice and fairness, expansion and inclusion, that
campaign isn't over with.''
   
   KITTY DUKAKIS, speaking at a restaurant for the homeless where
she ate lunch: ``I would be a very active first lady, involved in
this issue and other issues that I feel are important.''
   
   WILLIE BROWN, Jackson campaign chairman, said after meeting with
the Congressional Black Caucus: ``Jackson's people and Dukakis'
people are now one and the same.''
   
   Arkansas Gov. BILL CLINTON, reacting to the poor reception given
to his lengthy speech nominating Dukakis, said the speech ran
longer than expected because Dukakis campaign people kept rousing
the crowd to cheer: ``I'm not mad or anything. It's just one of
those weird deals.... My guess is that it's just a one-day story
and nothing to get in a deep funk about. It will be just a whiff on
the screen.''
   
   JERRY CALVERT, a delegate from Montana, complaining that the
careful convention choreography took away its spontaneity: ``The
whole focus has been subordinated to TV showmanship. This
convention is much less a deliberative body than a television
extravaganza. And that's bad.''
   
   Former President JIMMY CARTER, commenting on references to
Dukakis' fluency in Spanish and Carter's once addressing an
Organization of American States meeting in Spanish, laughed and
said: ``I don't think either the Latin contingent or the Americans
could understand what I said.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
