<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BadAd     07-22 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bad Ad,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Dismisses Murder-Solicitation Charge in Anniversary Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOLIET, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A murder-solicitation charge has been
dismissed against a woman whose arrest on charges of hiring a
gunman to kill her husband was published in a newspaper on the same
day as her happy anniversary message.
   The motion to drop the charge came after Mary Borunda's daughter
_ a key witness in the case _ refused to testify against her, said
Assistant State's Attorney Douglas DeBoer.
   ``I think my client is very pleased that this is over,'' Ms.
Borunda's attorney, Winston Block, said after Will County Circuit
Judge Bruce Falk approved a prosecution motion Thursday to drop the
charge against her.
   ``They appear to be a very happy couple,'' he added.
   The investigation began when the daughter, identified by Block
as Janet Taylor, went to police with information that led to the
charge against Ms. Borunda, DeBoer said earlier Thursday. The
daughter's refusal to testify left the state no alternative but to
dismiss the charge, he said.
   ``There were numerous allegations. ... Further investigation has
proven many of them _ as well as the case _ not to be founded,''
said Block.
   Block said he could not speculate about the basis for her
accusation.
   Ms. Borunda was arrested June 25, accused of paying a gunman
$1,000 and promising an additional $1,500 after her fifth husband
had been killed during a staged break-in, Police Detective Dan
Hulbert said.
   The account of her arrest was published in the local paper the
same day as her happy-anniversary message to her husband, who was
identified as the intended victim.
   ``Happy fourth anniversary 6-29-88 to my wonderful husband Joe
Borunda,'' read the ad in the Herald-News of Joliet. ``I'll love
you always. Your wife Mary.''
   Borunda, 59, told police he had several life insurance policies
worth well over $100,000, Hulbert said.
   But Borunda, who earlier posted $1,000 bond to secure his wife's
release, did not believe she intended him any harm, Block said.
   Neither Ms. Borunda or her husband appeared in court Thursday,
the attorney said.
</TEXT>
