<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     07-22 0540</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WATERLOO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This small town will finally honor one of
its most famous daughters, a barnyard belle whose profile is
well-known to generations of milk drinkers.
   Waterloo town fathers and the Seneca County Chamber of Commerce
planned today to unveil a sign on Route 96 reading simply:
``Waterloo, N.Y., Birthplace of Elsie the Cow _ 1932.'' A picture
of the famous bovine's face will also be revealed.
   Elsie, the symbol of Borden Dairy products since 1935, was born
on a farm in Waterloo in 1932, according to Dick Compo, chamber of
commerce president.
   Borden officials picked the jersey cow to be Elsie to satisfy
public demand for a real-life counterpart to a popular cartoon cow
in Borden advertisements.
   Elsie's advertised words soon became a popular Borden trademark.
   ``Dear Mom, I'm so excited I can barely chew,'' the celebrity
cow said. ``From now on I'm sending all my milk to Borden.''
   Compo said the sign was erected because ``Elsie is a community
asset.''
   Among those scheduled to attend today's unveiling was one of the
current Elsies, who is visiting the Seneca County Fair in Waterloo.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ARLINGTON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 19-year-old employee of the Arlington
Police Department who lacked the ``stable'' demeanor necessary for
the force has been retired.
   Rondo, a member of the department's four-horse mounted patrol
unit, ``just didn't have the right temperament,'' said Deputy
Police Chief Mike Johnston.
   Police work demands cool composure, but that wasn't Rondo's
style. So he will become the second horse to be retired from the
department and be returned to his owner. Another four-hoofed crime
stopper will replace him.
   Police also would like to replace Rondo with a darker-colored
horse to give the mounted patrol a more uniform look.
   ``We've had a few people approach us about donating horses to
the department,'' Johnston said. ``Right now, there's a glut of
horses because of the high cost of feeding them.''
   In three years of existence, Arlington's four mounted patrol
officers have become a familiar sight in shopping center parking
lots and some residential areas. They also spend their Friday and
Saturday nights riding herd over the city's teen-age cruisers,
Johnston said.
   ``They do their job,'' he said. ``They probably average three
arrests a month.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>IRVINE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese diners looking for a change from
teriyaki and sushi will get a chance to munch on enchurritos and
burritos at Japan's first Taco Bell. But they're in for a surprise
if they order ``tako.''
   In Spanish, a taco is meat, beans or other filling folded into a
flat, cornmeal flapjack called a tortilla. In Japanese, tako is
octopus, most often served boiled, sliced and dipped in a sauce of
fermented bean curd.
   The Mexican-style fast food chain announced Thursday it had
become the latest American company trying to break into Asia's
biggest consumer market. The Southern California-based chain says
its first restaurant will open Monday in the city of Nagoya.
   Taco Bell, which has 2,700 outlets in the United States and has
ventured overseas to Canada, Guam, Puerto Rico and Britain, sees
the Land of the Rising Sun as a $4.5-billion-a-year fast food
market and plans to open more franchised and company-owned stores
there.
</TEXT>
