<HEAD>Rain in the East</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Occasionally heavy rain fell across much of the East today,
triggering warnings of possible flooding in some areas.
   Showers and thunderstorms fell from Maine to the Carolinas,
southern Georgia, Alabama and Florida. Scattered showers dampened
northern Indiana and northern Ohio, as well as Southern California.
   On Thursday, more than 3 inches of rain fell in northern New
Castle County, Del., pushing the Christina River about a half foot
over flood stage at Cooches Bridge. However, the river dropped
below flood stage two hours later.
   Heavier rainfall in six hours overnight included more than 2{
inches at Wilmington, Del.; 2\ inches at Fayettville, N.J. and 1}
inches at Newark, N.J.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from New
England and New York to central Florida, as well as over the Gulf
Coast and the Mississippi Delta.
   High temperatures were forecast in the 70s in New England and
the Great Lakes region, and along the northern Pacific Coast and
the central California coast; the 80s from southern New York to
inland sections of the Carolinas, the Ohio and Tennessee valleys,
from northern Georgia to northern Mississippi and much of the
Mississippi Valley; 100 degrees in eastern Montana and Nevada; 115
degrees in the desert Southwest; and near 90 degrees to the 90s in
the rest of the nation.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 49
degrees at Craig, Colo., to 94 degrees at Phoenix.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 71 cloudy; Boston 63 foggy; Buffalo 65 partly
cloudy; Charleston, S.C. 81 fair; Cincinnati 65 fair; Cleveland 65
partly cloudy; Detroit 67 partly cloudy; Miami 81 fair; New York 72
rain; Philadelphia 74 rain; Pittsburgh 65 fair; Portland, Maine 62
rain.
   _Central: Bismarck 61 fair; Chicago 65 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
75 fair; Denver 64 fair; Des Moines 64 fair; Indianapolis 63 fair;
Kansas City 64 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 61 fair; Nashville 72
fair; New Orleans 75 partly cloudy; St. Louis 68 fair.
