<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ArtDispute     07-22 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Art Dispute,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thais Outraged Over Art Institute Proposal For Return Of Relic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thai officials predict their government will
reject a proposal that it lend sculptures to the Art Institute of
Chicago so Thailand can recover a historic temple relic it claims
was stolen.
   ``I am 90 percent certain of this,'' said Prince Subhadradis
Diskul, an expert in Thai art and archaeology who came to Chicago
to negotiate the return of the 900-year-old sculpture.
   The prince met with Art Institute officials Thursday, but left
without resolving the dispute that has sparked demonstrations in
Chicago and Bangkok.
   The relic at issue _ called a lintel, or crosspiece over a door
or window _ is titled ``Birth of Brahma With Reclining Vishnu On A
Makara.''
   The 2{-feet-long by 3-feet-wide lintel depicts the Hindu god
Vishnu reclining on water, and dates to Cambodia's Khmer dynasty
from 805-1250 A.D.
   It is the only important original piece missing from the 10-acre
Khmer temple of Phnom Rung in the northeastern Buri Ram province
near the Cambodian border.
   ``We will probably put a sign at the temple where the lintel
should be so tourists _ including Americans _ will know it was
taken, that we asked to give it back, and that they (the Art
Institute) would not,'' the prince added.
   Following a morning meeting, Art Institute officials proposed a
revolving-loan program that would bring to Chicago, for at least 10
years, ancient Thai sculptures of a comparable period and aesthetic
importance.
   ``The feeling of the people of Thailand is that it is stolen.
And they think that if it is stolen, we shouldn't have to send
anything in return,'' the prince said at a news conference.
   But the royal visitor, heading a delegation of Thai officials
and archeologists, promised to take the institute proposal back to
his government.
   Art Institute spokeswoman Eileen Harakal said the piece was
legally purchased by a dealer in Bangkok, who sold it to a New York
dealer, who finally sold it to the Alsdorf Foundation of Winnetka,
Ill.
   It was on loan to the Art Institute from 1967 until 1983, when
the foundation made it a gift, she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880722-0083 </DOCNO>
