<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DrugArraignment     07-22 0207</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drug Arraignment,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Colombians Plead Innocent to Drug Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four Colombians arrested in a drug raid in
which police seized 277 pounds of cocaine worth $66 million pleaded
innocent to charges of possessing a controlled substance for sale.
   Jorge Jimenez, 38, Johnny Castillo, 24, Juan Quintero, 23, and
Maria Martinez, 32, pleaded innocent to the charges during a
Municipal Court arraignment Thursday.
   The three men were ordered held on $2 million bail each while
Ms. Martinez's bail was set at $1 million pending an Aug. 2
preliminary hearing, said a court clerk.
   The four were arrested Tuesday during a police investigation
launched aftr officers received a tip that large amounts of cocaine
were being shipped out of a home in Chino, about 40 miles east of
Los Angeles.
   Narcotics detectives from the Los Angeles and Chino police
departments and the California Highway Patrol monitored the house
and followed a van when it left the residence.
   CHP officers pulled the van over, found 46 pounds of cocaine and
$13,000 inside and arrested Castillo and Quintero, police said.
   Jimenez and Ms. Martinez were arrested later at the Chino home
when police serving search warrants found 231 pounds of cocaine,
loaded handguns and $12,000.
</TEXT>
