<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Vietnam-Cambodia     07-22 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vietnam-Cambodia,0244</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietnam Moves Up Schedule For Cambodia Withdrawal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam's leader, Nguyen Van Linh, says
all Vietnamese troops will leave Cambodia by early 1990 at the
latest instead of the end of 1990 as previously announced.
   Linh made the statement in a meeting in Moscow on Thursday with
Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev, according to an official
Vietnam News Agency report monitored today in Bangkok.
   Soviet-supplied Vietnamese forces invaded Cambodia in late 1978,
installed a pro-Vietnamese government and are battling three major
guerrilla groups.
   The agency said Linh told Gorbachev that all Vietnamese troops
``will be withdrawn by the end of 1989 or early 1990 at the latest,
and that the schedule for the troop pullout will be updated if an
early solution is reached.''
   Vietnam says it is withdrawing 50,000 troops, or half its force
in Cambodia, this year. It says its military command was withdrawn
on June 30 and that the running of the war was turned over to the
Cambodian government.
   The Vietnamese report quoted Linh and Gorbachev as saying they
would strive to create favorable conditions for a settlement and
stated that China could contribute to a settlement. China arms the
guerrillas.
   They also stressed the importance of talks beginning Monday in
Bogor, Indonesia, that would for the first time bring together all
the warring factions in Cambodia. Vietnamese Foreign Minister
Nguyen Co Thach is scheduled to attend the talks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
