<DOCNO> AP880722-0089 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-88 0751EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-WarCrimes     07-22 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-War Crimes,0374</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Investigators in Soviet Union Probing War Crimes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British investigators say they will interview
witnesses to World War II atrocities in their search for evidence
against more than 100 Britons suspected of Nazi war crimes.
   Sir Thomas Hetherington, a member of a British inquiry team that
arrived this week, told reporters the team will focus on the
Ukraine and on the Baltic republics of Lithuania and Latvia, which
Nazi forces occupied after attacking the Soviet Union in June 1941.
   The investigators will question people who witnessed murder,
manslaughter and genocide under the Nazis, he said Thursday.
   British Home Secretary Douglas Hurd established the commission
in February to decide whether enough evidence could be gathered to
pursue criminal prosecution of British citizens or residents
accused of war crimes.
   If such evidence can be assembled, Hurd told Parliament, he will
ask the body to change British law to allow prosecution for crimes
committed outside the country.
   Canada has passed a similar law, and Australia is considering
one, Hetherington said. The United States can prosecute suspected
war criminals only for violating immigration laws.
   The Soviet prosecutor's office has given the team lists of
suspected war criminals who are believed to be living in Britain,
Hetherington said. Other names and evidence have come from two
Holocaust research centers, the Simon Wiesenthal Center in Los
Angeles and the Yad Vashem Memorial in Jerusalem.
   The team compiled a list of 250 suspected war criminals but has
trimmed it to 110 after reviewing evidence, Hetherington told
reporters at the British Embassy.
   The first witnesses will be interviewed Sept. 26 in Lithuania,
said another investigator, William Chalmers.
   Chalmers and Hetherington said Soviet authorities had been
helpful in providing information about the suspects and arranging
interviews.
   Hetherington, Britain's former director of public prosecutions,
said there was no evidence the British government hid the
identities of the suspects after the war.
   Asked why it took more than 40 years for Britain to investigate
the suspects, he replied: ``It's only in the last few years this
sort of thing has been an issue. ''
   He said the team hoped to present its recommendations to Hurd
next summer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
