<1ST_LINE>r i PM-India-Sikhs     07-22 0189</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Sikhs,0194</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sikh Militants Blamed For 11 Deaths</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen believed to be Sikh militants
killed 11 people, including eight Sikhs, in northern Punjab state,
the United News of India said today.
   The victims' bodies were found in an area about 25 miles east of
the city of Amritsar, the news agency said.
   Five Nihangs, members of a Sikh fundamentalist sect, were shot
and killed on a highway near the town of Mehta Chowk, the news
agency said. Three Sikhs, including two women, were gunned down in
the nearby village of Shero Padha.
   Three unidentified bodies were found in Chogowan, another
village nearby, the agency said. The report said the killings
occurred Thursday.
   The killings raise to 1,544 the number of deaths in Punjab this
year blamed on Sikh militants, who are fighting for an independent
homeland in the state.
   The militants have killed at least 685 fellow Sikhs in their
violent campaign. Moderate Sikhs often are targets of the violence.
   Sikhs only 2 percent of India's 800 million people but are a
majority in Punjab. Sikh radicals claim discrimination by the Hindu
majority.
</TEXT>
