<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Brown     07-22 0213</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Brown,0222</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Orders Soul Singer To Perform Benefit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AIKEN, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has ordered soul singer James Brown
to hold a benefit concert for police and abused children as part of
a sentence on drug and weapons charges.
   The 55-year-old Godfather of Soul pleaded guilty Thursday to
resisting arrest and carrying a pistol. He pleaded no contest to
possession of the drug PCP.
   Circuit Judge James E. Moore fined Brown $1,200 and placed him
on probation until he performs a concert to benefit the local
chapter of the Fraternal Order of Police and Helping Hands, a
private organization for abused children.
   No concert date has been set.
   ``This is a back-door way of getting me to do a concert,'' Brown
said after the sentencing. ``I would have done a concert for the
children anyway. ... I would have done it gladly, but they didn't
have to arrest me.''
   But he added, ``I just thank God I was able to get out of here.''
   The singer could have received up to 2{ years in jail and $3,000
in fines on the charges.
   ``It's better than placing him on the streets to do community
service,'' said prosecutor Bob Harte. ``A concert is something he
can do that no one else could.''
</TEXT>
