<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ClubFire     07-22 0203</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Club Fire,0211</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Flash Paper Used By Male Dancer Ignites La Bare Nightclub</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It got hotter than usual during a male dancer's
act when ``flash paper'' he was using started a fire and sent
people fleeing.
   Eighteen dancers, 10 employees and 75 patrons in the women-only
La Bare nightclub escaped without injury Thursday night, said
manager Keith Narducci.
   Witnesses said the dancer, who worked under the name Eagle, had
tossed a flash-paper cigarette toward the ceiling during his act.
The blaze spread across the entire ceiling in about 15 seconds,
they said.
   ``They kept playing music and the guy kept dancing. Then when he
started pointing at it (the ceiling), I said, `Hey, something's
wrong here,' but they never said there was a fire,'' an
unidentified patron told the Dallas Morning News. ``I just think it
stinks.''
   The blaze caused an estimated $100,000 to the nightclub and
$20,000 damage to a pizza restaurant, fire officials said.
   Flammable flash paper often is used by magicians and other
performers to produce bursts of fire.
   Eagle told the newspaper that when the club is rebuilt, he will
continue to use flash paper. ``We'll be a little more careful next
time,'' he said.
</TEXT>
