<DOCNO> AP880722-0097 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-88 0829EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DeformitySettlement     07-22 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Deformity Settlement,0312</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Ordered To Honor Settlement with Family of Quadriplegic Baby</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has ordered the government to honor a
settlement made with a couple whose baby was born severely
handicapped at a military hospital, even though the child has died.
   ``One must expect that the moral fibers of our nation _ honor,
integrity and commitment _ will be reflected as a model to our
citizens,'' U.S. District Judge Thomas E. Scott said in the ruling.
   Lavern Reed, who was with the Coast Guard, sued the government
in 1986, alleging that negligence during his son's delivery at
Homestead Air Force Base hospital resulted in the child being born
quadriplegic, deaf, blind and brain-damaged.
   The hospital and government never admitted negligence and were
not found liable. However, the government negotiated a settlement
with the family to provide for Benjamin's long-term medical care
and compensation for the family.
   The Reeds said the government reneged when their 16-month-old
died just after the $2 million settlement was reached.
   Government officials called and said, ``He's dead _ now you
don't need the money,'' said Linda Reed, who lives with her husband
in Ilwaco, Wash.
   The government argued it didn't owe the money because there was
never a binding agreement and because no court approved the
settlement before Benjamin died.
   The settlement had included a $700,000 medical trust fund, with
the unused portion to go back to the government when Benjamin died,
said the Reed's attorney, Ira Leesfield.
   Under Scott's ruling, issued Monday, the family will receive the
remaining $1.3 million, which was a guaranteed settlement for the
parents.
   ``The government has wholly failed its people by not upholding
these deeply rooted ideals in this case,'' the judge said. ``The
government, more than any other party, must be held to honor its
commitments.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880722-0098 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-88 0847EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MissingRockwells     07-22 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Missing Rockwells,0273</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mystery Of Missing Rockwells Spurs Suit Against Posner</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financier Victor Posner is being sued
over a series of Norman Rockwell portraits of steelworkers
commissioned by Sharon Steel Corp.
   Rockwell was 72 and nearing the end of his career when Sharon
Steel paid him $50,000 in 1966 to do 14 illustrations. Rockwell,
who died in 1978, was best known for his folksy Saturday Evening
Post covers.
   Bankruptcy trustee James Toren discovered the Rockwells missing
when he began counting corporate assets for Sharon Steel, which
filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection in 1987.
   Posner, who added Sharon Steel to a rapidly growing list of
companies that vaulted him into the Forbes magazine list of 400
wealthiest Americans, had moved the paintings to his Miami Beach
headquarters in 1969.
   On April 27, Toren wrote to Posner asking for the paintings,
said to be worth up to $350,000. He is still waiting for an answer.
On June 3, he sued Posner in U.S. Bankruptcy Court in Erie, Pa.,
demanding the paintings.
   ``I don't know where they are,'' said Renee Motram-Doss,
Posner's aide. ``To this minute, I am unaware of the exact charge
or the exact location of the illustrations.''
   Toren also claimed this week that Posner paid himself $16.1
million in unjustified and excessive salaries from Sharon between
1983 to 1987.
   Posner in February pleaded no contest to income tax fraud for
allegedly inflating the value of a land donation. He was sentenced
to finance a $3 million program to study homelessness and work as a
volunteer at a soup kitchen.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
