<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Gorbachev-Reagan     07-22 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gorbachev-Reagan,0400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High Popularity Rating For Gorbachev Signals Stronger East-West
Ties</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 70 percent of West
Germans questioned in a survey approve of Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev, and 41 percent approve of President Reagan, according to
results released today.
   Another poll indicated that West German mistrust of the Warsaw
Pact has ``dropped dramatically,'' the respected Allensbach
Institute said.
   The Allensbach poll said that of about 2,000 West Germans
queried in late May and early June, 71 percent had a ``favorable
opinion'' of Gorbachev compared with 41 percent for Reagan.
   ``General Secretary Gorbachev has exceeded a popularity rating
of 70 percent, something that normally only federal presidents have
accomplished in the federal republic (West Germany),'' institute
director Elisabeth Noelle-Neumann wrote.
   Results of the poll regarding mistrust of the Warsaw Pact also
were released today.
   In a commentary explaining those results, Noelle-Neumann said:
``The mistrust towards the Soviet Bloc has dropped dramatically
since Gorbachev has been at the helm.''
   At the start of the decade, 58 percent of West Germans expressed
mistrust of the Soviet bloc compared with 25 percent in the latest
survey, according to Allensbach. The latest poll was conducted in
January and involved about 2,000 people.
   The institute said those polled included people over 16
throughout West Germany and in West Berlin. It did not release a
margin of error for the results.
   The poll results are in line with indicators that many West
Germans believe a positive trend in East-West relations will
continue.
   Chancellor Helmut Kohl told a news conference Thursday that his
Moscow summit in October will make improved East-West ties
``irreversible.''
   Defense Minister Rupert Scholz favors a ``direct dialogue''
between West German and Soviet military officials on defense
matters, according to an interview published Thursday in the
Allgemeine Zeitung newspaper of Hanover and the Tagesspiegel of
West Berlin.
   A growing number of West German companies are seeking business
with the Soviets.
   Kohl on Thursday made clear he will use his Kremlin trip to
cement better East-West ties.
   ``I want to make sure that the favorable tendencies we now see
in East-West relations are irreversible,'' Kohl told reporters.
   West Germans hope that improved ties between Washington and
Moscow will eventually result in better relations with Communist
East Germany.
</TEXT>
