<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Mexico-Prison     07-22 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mexico-Prison,0440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inmates Bribed Guard for Guns, Sparked Prison Riot</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAVIER PICHARDINI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prison riot that left 10 convicts dead
began as an escape attempt by four inmates who bribed a guard to
get them weapons, authorities said.
   Twenty people were injured in the riot Wednesday at a
penitentiary in Morelia, 150 miles west of Mexico City, the
Michoacan state attorney general's office said.
   Genovevo Figueroa, state public security director in Michoacan,
said Thursday that of the 20 injured, 13 were convicts and seven
were guards. All the injuries were minor, he said.
   About 2,000 inmates are housed at the prison, many for drug
trafficking, bank robbery and homicide.
   Figueroa's office said it was investigating possible complicity
by people on the outside.
   A statement released Thursday night by state Attorney General
Jose Franco Villa's office said four prisoners paid about $1,080
for two 9mm pistols from a guard. It identified the guard as Jorge
Moreno Zarate.
   A spokesman for the attorney general, Isauro Gutierrez, said
Morteno Zarate resigned at the beginning of the month but was a
guard when he allegedly obtained the firearms.
   Authorities were looking for Zarate, Gutierrez said.
   The statement said three of the four inmates who sparked the
riot were serving sentences for drug trafficking and the fourth was
convicted of bank robbery.
   The four were joined by another inmate who helped wrest an M-1
assault rifle from a guard and by a sixth prisoner who made a
firebomb using a soft drink bottle, the statement said.
   It said the four planned to escape July 6, assuming that on the
day of Mexico's national elections, security would be lax. But when
they saw security was normal, they postponed their plans, the
statement said.
   The riot began at 9:45 a.m. Wednesday when prisoners being led
to trial disarmed five guards and a police officer, Franco Villa
told reporters.
   He said other prisoners took advantage of the presence of ``a
considerable number of (visiting) relatives and friends of the
prisoners'' to disarm more guards.
   ``With these new arms, others intensified the aggression against
security elements,'' he said.
   He said the prisoners hurled a firebomb into administrative
offices, destroying virtually all files on pending court cases in
six courtrooms.
   Other inmates exchanged gunfire with watchtower guards before
the riot was brought under control, he said.
   Police captured five inmates outside the penitentiary, Franco
Villa said.
   The attorney general denied an earlier report that prisoners
held 15 secretaries and eight nurses hostage.
</TEXT>
