<2ND_LINE>PM-CVN--Parties,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>It's a Party Party on Democrats' Last Night</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-CVN-Convention Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democratic Party did just that _ party _ well
into the morning as delegates, journalists, party faithful and
hangers on marked the end of the Democratic National Convention.
   At the Georgia World Congress Center, the massive convention
facility next door to the convention hall, thousands danced into
the early hours at a ``Victory '88'' party.
   Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis and his running mate Lloyd
Bentsen received thunderous applause from a crowd when they walked
across the street to the giant bash.
   ``This has been a great convention and it sets the stage for a
great Democratic victory in November of 1988,'' Dukakis told the
throng.
   When he completed his five minutes of impromptu remarks, an
orchestra started playing Greek tunes and Dukakis danced two or
three steps, setting off wild cheers.
   While the house band from a posh local nightspot played Motown
and rock, several delegates danced with big state-name signs from
the convention floor.
   Ben Jones, a former TV actor _ ``The Dukes of Hazzard'' _ and
now a Democratic candidate for Congress from Georgia, bounded out
of the World Congress Center with the Georgia sign about 1:30 a.m.
   He said he planned to present the sign to Bobby Kahn, head of
Atlanta '88, the convention planning committee.
   Across downtown at the New Georgia Railroad depot _ not a new
depot at all, but an old depot refurbished by the state _ some
1,200 attended a ``Boston to Austin'' party for the Massachusetts
and Texas delegations, members of Congress, and many other invited
guests.
   The menu: oysters and shrimp for Boston, fajitas and hot sauce
for Austin. At the bar: Samuel Adams Boston Lager and Lone Star
Beer, plus Cape Cod cocktails, margaritas and other drinks.
   Cost of the bash, thrown by Ocean Spray of Plymouth, Mass., and
the Enron Corp. of Houston: ``About 50,'' said public relations
spokesman Roy Meyers.
   He meant thousand.
   Entertainment was provided by The Fabulous Thunderbirds, an
uptempo rock-blues band from Texas. ``We play these things every
once in a while,'' said lead singer Kim Wilson. ``We kind of
represent the state in a way.''
   Wilson, however, didn't want to represent who he was voting for.
``One of the nice things about voting is you do it in secret,'' he
said, although he would concede that the Dukakis-Bentsen ticket
``looks good to me.''
   Jesse Jackson's supporters partied Thursday night at their
headquarters hotel.
   ``I will do whatever Jesse says do,'' said Walter Dale, a
campaign worker from Chicago. ``If he says vote for (Republican
George) Bush, we'll do it.''
</TEXT>
