<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-88 0910EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-HerseyApologizes     07-22 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hersey Apologizes,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>John Hersey Apologizes For Not Crediting Another Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pulitzer Prize-winning author John Hersey has
acknowledged appropriating another writer's facts and phrases
without attribution for a New Yorker article on novelist James Agee
and offered an apology.
   The flap developed after Laurence Bergreen, author of ``James
Agee: A Life,'' noticed as many as 20 parallel passages in Hersey's
article about Agee in the magazine's July 18 issue, The New York
Times said today.
   ``It seemed to me that once you got beyond the opening anecdote
in which he (Hersey) described his meeting with Agee that the whole
article was a condensation of my biography,'' Bergreen told the
newspaper.
   Bergreen said he contacted his lawyer after he learned the
Hersey article was going to be reprinted this fall by Houghton
Mifflin as the preface to a new edition of Agee's ``Let Us Now
Praise Famous Men.''
   Agee, a critic, novelist, journalist and screenwriter, died in
1955.
   Hersey, who won the Pulitzer for fiction in 1945 with his ``A
Bell for Adano,'' told the Times in a telephone interview from his
Massachusetts home at Martha's Vineyard, ``Where I quoted directly,
I gave credit.
   ``But since Mr. Bergreen's biography is the most comprehensive
so far published, I should have given him some direct credit, and
that I will now do.''
   Hersey said he did not think he made a big mistake. ``I'm very
sorry if I've offended Mr. Bergreen. I don't believe my real
offense in terms of normal practice is great,'' he said.
   ``There's always a fine line between facts and the work of
another writer,'' said Hersey, who is the author of numerous
articles and more than 20 books including ``Hiroshima,'' which
filled an entire issue of The New Yorker in 1946.
   Bergreen's other works include ``Look Now, Pay Later: The Rise
of Network Broadcasting.'' He is also working on a biography of
Irving Berlin.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
