<HEAD>Four More People Sued In Soccer Riots Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Victims of soccer riots that killed 39
people in 1985 have sued the mayor of Brussels and three other
people, the prosecutor's office said today.
   Lawsuits filed Wednesday also name the city of Brussels and the
European Soccer Union, an office spokesman said.
   Twenty-six Britons were charged with first-degree responsibility
in the riots at Heysel Stadium in Brussels in May 1985. The
violence broke out during the final match of the European Cup
championship between English and Italian teams.
   Those charged are to go on trial Oct. 17. Three Belgian
officials have been accused of deadly neglect.
   The new suits name Brussels Mayor Herve Brouhon; Viviane Baro,
deputy mayor in charge of sports; Jacques Georges, president of the
European Soccer Union; and Hans Bangerter, secretary general of the
union, said the office spokesman. He spoke on condition of
anonymity in keeping with office rules.
   More than 100 supporters of the Italian soccer club Juventus
Turin who survived the riots and relatives of the victims filed the
new suits, he said. They are claiming damages of $12,900 to
$385,000 per person.
