<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Court-ChurchPrivilege     07-22 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Court-Church Privilege,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Orders Church Officials to Disclose Confessions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mormon Church officials must disclose
whether a member confessed to molesting children years before his
arrest, an appeals court ruled.
   The ruling Thursday came in a lawsuit filed against the Church
of Jesus Christ of Latter-Day Saints by the mother of a child the
church member admitted molesting.
   The suit claims Kenneth Ray told three bishops as early as 1968
that he had been having sexual contact with children. The suit said
the church failed to report Ray to state authorities until 1984,
leaving children vulnerable to abuse.
   Ray was excommunicated by the church in 1984 for conduct
unbecoming a member and later pleaded no contest to child molesting.
   Cynthia Brown, who sued Ray, Ray's former wife and the Mormon
Church seeking unspecified damages on her daughter's behalf, sought
to force the bishops to disclose whether Ray told them he had been
sexually abusing children.
   The church objected, saying the bishops were protected by the
clergyman-penitent privilege.
   Superior Court Judge Cheryl Hendrix ordered the bishops to give
depositions, and the Arizona Court of Appeals agreed Thursday.
   The appellate court, in a 3-0 decision, said Ray had waived his
privilege by disclosing to police what he had told the bishops.
   A Mormon Church official in Mesa, David Udall, declined comment
on the ruling, saying he had not read it.
</TEXT>
