<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PotWarehouse     07-22 0204</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pot Warehouse,0210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>$30 Million-a-Year Pot Operation Raided in Seattle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police raided a marijuana-growing operation in a
warehouse equipped with automatic lights, timers and a liquid
fertilizer dispenser, and said the operation could have harvested
crops worth $30 million a year.
   ``This is easily the biggest we've ever had,'' police Lt. Harry
Berghmans said Thursday.
   During a raid Wednesday night, police found 2,500 marijuana
plants in the 20,000-square-foot warehouse. Officer Dan Fordice
estimated the operation could produce four crops a year or about
10,000 plants, each worth an estimated $3,000 at maturity.
   No one was found in the building and no arrests were made,
Fordice said.
   The leased building was divided into 10 rooms, each containing
numerous planter boxes with six to eight plants per box and
automatic lighting, fertilizing and venting, police said.
   One room contained two huge vats of liquid fertilizer that was
fed to plants through tubes running to the individual rooms with
automatic timers to control the flow to each plant.
   Fordice said police learned of the operation through a tipster.
A check of power records indicated unusually high electricity
consumption at the warehouse began last November, suggesting the
operation may have begun then, he said.
</TEXT>
