<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ToyotaPlant     07-22 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Toyota Plant,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Red, White And Blue Cars Just A Coincidence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GEORGETOWN, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first showroom-bound cars off the
assembly line at Toyota's first wholly-owned American plant will be
one of three colors _ red, white or blue. But the automaker says
it's mere coincidence.
   Commercial production of the 1989 Camry started on schedule at
the plant July 11, two years after ground was broken, said D.
Michael Dodge, plant general manager.
   The first cars were white, the easiest color to apply because
the paint is non-metallic. White also is popular with customers,
Dodge said.
   This week, the plant began making dark red cars. It will add
dark blue in two weeks, he said, and follow that with black and
dark gray.
   Later, Toyota will produce more difficult colors that will be
offered on Camrys for the first time this fall. There will be nine
colors in all.
   The Camrys go on sale in October, said Debra Sanchez, a
spokeswoman for Toyota Motor Sales in California.
   The plant is now producing 19 cars a day. It will reach 40 cars
a day by the end of August and turn out 17,000 to 20,000 by the end
of the year, Dodge said. Eventually production will reach 200,000
Camrys a year.
   The plant now employs 1,345 people, with an eventual workforce
of 3,000 in the assembly plant and 500 more in an engine plant yet
to be built.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880722-0112 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-88 1021EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-VDTLawsuit     07-22 0204</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-VDT Lawsuit,0209</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Companies Challenge Suffolk's VDT Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAUPPAUGE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Suffolk County's new first-in-the-nation
law regulating the use of video display terminals in the workplace
is superseded by state and federal law and is unconstitutional, a
lawsuit claims.
   The law affects all companies in the Long Island county with 20
or more of the computer terminals and with operators who spend at
least 20 hours a week working on them.
   The law, which took effect Monday, requires employers to provide
work breaks, eye care and eyeglass benefits, and special furniture
and lighting.
   Gary Sazer, representing the four companies that filed the suit
in state court Thursday, said state and federal law have provisions
for controlling hazards in the workplace, ensuring consistent
legislation throughout the state.
   The suit also claims that the law violates constitutional rights
against unlawful searches because it authorizes county officials to
inspect private offices without a warrant to ensure compliance.
   The federal Occupational and Safety Health Administration is
studying VDTs in the workplace to determine if regulation is
needed, he said.
   The four companies suing were ILC Data Device Corp. of Bohemia,
Lumex Inc. of Bay Shore, and Micra Corp. and Digital Data Systems
Inc., both of Hauppauge.
</TEXT>
