<DOCNO> AP880722-0113 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-88 1023EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SakharovLetter     07-22 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sakharov Letter,0454</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pravda Publishes Briton's Letter To Sakharov</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party newspaper Pravda today
published a letter from a Briton who urged Nobel Peace laureate
Andrei Sakharov to condemn what he called lack of freedom and human
rights in Britain and the United States.
   Tom Hewson urged Sakharov to appeal to Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher and President Reagan on behalf of victims of real estate
development and those who cannot afford health care.
   ``Following your public plea for certain freedoms ... I wish to
suggest that you also make as impassioned appeals to both Mrs.
Thatcher and President Reagan about the appalling lack of freedom
and human rights in America and the United Kingdom,'' Hewson wrote.
   He referred to a June 3 news conference by Sakharov that he saw
on British television.
   Sakharov could not be reached for comment on the letter.
Telephone calls to his home went unanswered.
   Hewson, 72, was interviewed by The Associated Press in London
from his home in Maidstone, Kent, and read the original English
version of the letter.
   He said he is a retired businessman with three children who saw
the news conference in which Sakharov told reporters that Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev had not yet guaranteed human rights.
Sakharov also called for the release of political prisoners.
   ``I do not belong to any political party. I'm just a
straightforward individual who feels that the Russian people ought
to know that the ordinary people in this country are being hard
done by,'' Hewson told the AP.
   ``When I saw Sakharov complaining in Russia..., I thought it was
time somebody balanced the thing up and let the Russian people know
about conditions in England.''
   Hewson suggested Sakharov take on the causes of families evicted
from the Isle of Dogs, a partially derelict industrial and dockside
piece of real estate in London being developed for high-tech
businesses and residences.
   Hewson also said that that newborn babies are dying in Britain
because of a lack of money for heart operations and that American
hospitals refuse to treat the seriously ill for lack of health
insurance. He asked Sakharov to protest that.
   Sakharov, Hewson wrote, should also protest evictions of
unemployed Americans and Britons from their homes for not paying
mortgages.
   Sakharov, a physicist and leading Soviet human rights activist,
won the Nobel Peace Prize in 1975. He spent seven years in internal
exile and was freed in December 1986.
   Hewson said he was surprised Pravda published his letter.
   ``For one thing, I only put an 18-pence stamp on the letter and
I think a letter to Russia costs 31 pence,'' said Hewson.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
