<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--BurgerBan     07-22 0159</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Burger Ban,0165</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fast-Beef Chain Pays Town to Appear in Commercial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOPE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Town residents will soon be carrying signs
saying ``Ban Burgers'' and ``Burgers Go Home,'' but they certainly
have nothing against fast food.
   The picketing is part of a commercial Arby's, the roast beef
sandwich chain, plans to film in this town of 2,100.
   ``The premise for the commercial is that a town bans burgers,''
said Mark Blair, a member of the town board.
   The switch from fast-food hamburgers to roast beef sandwiches
shouldn't be too difficult _ Hope has no fast-food restaurants.
   The producers wanted the town to ban burgers for real.
   ``That is the intention, that the town signs a proclamation,''
said director Marion Maus of Academy Film Productions Inc. of
Baltimore. ``They're not going to be policed, but it definitely is
a part of the strategy.''
   The town, which declined to ban the hamburger officially, will
receive $3,000 for its participation.
</TEXT>
