<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru   07-22 0633</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0446,0654</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Riot Police Guard Temple Mount, Arab-Americans Complain of
Harassment</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with Moslem prayer day on Temple
Mount, Arab-Americans complain of harassment. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAN IZENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 100 helmeted police wielding clubs
and tear gas rifles guarded the sacred Temple Mount today to
prevent possible violence as thousands of Moslems gathered to
worship on their holy day.
   Palestinian-Americans said they were being harassed by Israeli
authorities, and a top U.S. diplomat urged them to stand up for
their rights and file complaints with U.S. consular officials.
   Most of the 3,500 worshipers who gathered on the Temple Mount
filed peacefully out of mosques at the end of services. But about
50 youths held up a Palestinian flag and shouted: ``Jews, Jews, get
out of Palestine!''
   District police chief Rahamim Comfort said police arrested a
Palestinian woman and her husband after she tried to smuggle eight
firebombs past police guards and custodians into the mosque area.
   The Temple Mount, known in Arabic as the Haram al-Sharif, is the
third holiest site in Islam. It is believed to be the place from
which the prophet Mohammed ascended to heaven on horseback.
   It also is the location of the ancient Jewish Holy Temple
destroyed by the Romans 2,000 years ago and is regarded by Jews as
their holiest site.
   Police prepared for potential violence over the weekend when
Jews mark the Tisha B'Av fast day and Moslems begin celebrating the
four-day Id al Adha festival.
   Both holidays focus on the Temple Mount, with Jews marking the
destruction of the Temple and Moslems celebrating the story of
Abraham's aborted sacrifice of his son.
   In a meeting called by the Washington-based American-Arab
Anti-Discrimination Committee, about 200 Palestinian-Americans
claimed harassment by Israeli authorities.
   They said they were frequently singled out for demeaning
searches at Israel's borders and their money was sometimes
confiscated.
   ``Palestinians are treated like criminals,'' said Hammad Siyam,
49, of West New York, N.J., waving his American passport.
   Siyam, who was born in the West Bank village of Mukhmas, said
three months ago airport authorities confiscated $82,950 from a
village resident and the money had still not been returned.
   According to a senior U.S. official, Israeli authorities have
confiscated about $200,000 from Arab-Americans in the past three
months as part of an effort to stop the flow of funds intended to
support the 8-month-old uprising in Israeli-occupied territories.
   Since the violence began Dec. 8, 231 Palestinians and four
Israelis have died.
   Philip Wilcox, the U.S. consul general in Jerusalem, said
Israeli officials agreed to return the money, but he did not
discuss details of the agreement.
   Palestinian-Americans also complained that Israel only granted
them tourist visas, while U.S. Jews were given immediate residency.
   Israel grants automatic citizenship to all Jews desiring it
under the 40-year-old Law of Return.
   ``How come an American Jew from Brooklyn who has never been here
before has the right to stay in the West Bank forever, and I have
to go back after three months?'' said Ahmad Baker, a physician born
in the West Bank and living in Norfolk, Va.
   Avi Pazner, a spokesman for Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, said
Jews were a special case but ``as far as American tourists are
concerned, everybody gets the same treatment.''
   Palestinians said Israeli policy has divided many families
because Arab-Americans married to residents of the occupied lands
are not automatically granted residency.
   Wilcox said U.S. officials have discussed family reunification
with Israeli officials. He did not elaborate.
   On Thursday, Israeli troops fired on demonstrators protesting
the shutdown of Palestinian schools in the occupied lands and Arab
east Jerusalem. Hospital officials said three Palestinians were
killed and 16 wounded.
   Thursday's protests were among the most violent since the
uprising began.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
