<1ST_LINE>r a PM-InmateEscapes     07-22 0211</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Inmate Escapes,0217</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Superintendent Violated State Gun Policy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prison superintendent whose shotgun and
car were stolen by an escapee violated rules regulating storage of
a weapon, according to state officials who said they are unsure
whether he will be disciplined.
   Arthur Tate Jr. of the Chillicote Correctional Institute
violated state policy requiring personal weapons be stored in a
locked cabinet, Robert Prosser, spokesman for the Department of
Rehabilitation and Correction, said Thursday.
   The superintendent's 12-gauge shotgun and his car apparently
were taken by murderer Earl Jacobs, who escaped Wednesday. Jacobs,
51, was held in a minimum-security area of the prison that was not
fenced in or guarded.
   Prison officials believe Jacobs took the gun and Tate's car keys
after entering the rear door of Tate's unlocked home on the prison
grounds.
   Prosser said Tate had not been questioned about the gun, nor had
any thought been given to disciplinary action.
   Jacobs had served 26 years of a life sentence for murdering a
village marshal in 1962. Jacobs had never before attempted to
escape from the prison, said prison spokeswoman Lynn Goff.
   Jacobs had been on honor status at the prison since 1980 and was
assigned to tend Tate's yard at the time of his escape.
</TEXT>
