<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0465,900</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Praises Dukakis Speech But Hits Dukakis-Bentsen Differences</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede Washington</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: TOP 10 grafs new; picks up 3rd graf, Bush hurled.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush today praised the
acceptance speech of rival Michael Dukakis but said he intends to
highlight the differences between the Democratic nominee and
Dukakis' own running-mate, Lloyd Bentsen.
   Bush told reporters that ``an effective use for Lloyd Bentsen''
would be for him to persuade Dukakis to change his positions on gun
control, prison furlough programs and a host of other issues.
   ``The differences are enormous'' between the Democratic
presidential and vice-presidential candidates, said Bush, who has
gone out of his way in recent days to praise the Texas Democrat as
a conservative.
   Speaking with reporters at an Italian festival here, the vice
president refused to be critical of Dukakis on anything other than
issues. The vice president said he watched Dukakis' speech to the
Democratic convention. ``I thought he gave a very good speech,''
Bush said. ``He did a very good job.''
   Bush was asked about Dukakis' statement that he wanted a vice
president who would come to him immediately if he found out about
something like the U.S. arms sale to Iran.
   Bush said he didn't know what the Massachusetts governor was
talking about. ``Ronald Reagan and I have worked as a team. I can
go in there and talk to him any time I want,'' he said.
   ``I don't know what that was all about, but I don't think it was
complimentary,'' Bush said, referring to Dukakis' comments.
   Bush said he was not troubled by his apparent dip in public
opinion polls following the Democratic convention, claiming as he
has before that he prefers fighting back as an underdog.
   ``I never thought it would be a cakewalk,'' the vice president
said.
   Bush on Thursday said he ``can't wait for the debates'' in this
presidential year, referring to what he said would be debates
between Dukakis and Bentsen.
   Bush hurled the barbs at the Democrats even as he claimed to be
trying to keep ``a relatively low profile'' as the rival party
commanded the spotlight in Atlanta.
   ``I wouldn't call this real campaigning. I don't want to overdo
it,'' Bush, who is certain to face Dukakis in November, told an
airport news conference in Greenville, S.C.
   Bush, who sandwiched two news conferences between private
fund-raising events in Greenville and in Charlotte, N.C., on
Thursday, was appearing today at an Italian festival in Milwaukee
and then flying to Bayhead, N.J., for a fund-raising event for the
Republican National Committee.
   Bush has all but spent the $27 million allowed to him under
pre-convention federal campaign spending law, and is using a host
of fund-raising events for the national party to help finance much
of his travel between now and the Republican convention next month
in New Orleans.
   He returned to Washington on Thursday night from the Carolinas
and said he planned to watch Dukakis' acceptance speech on
television at his residence at the U.S. Naval Observatory.
   Bush said Dukakis struck him as ``a very good man'' but he
suggested the Massachusetts governor seemed ``more positive than
the rest of the proceedings'' in Atlanta.
   He said the Democratic convention had produced its share of
``the ploy, the old rhetorical shout'' and that he did not intend
to respond directly to criticism of him from a succession of
Democratic speakers.
   ``I can't wait for the debates _ Dukakis vs. Bentsen. It's going
to be great,'' he quipped at an airport news conference in
Charlotte.
   Later, in Greenville, Bush said he didn't mind running against
what he said amounted to three Democratic candidates: Dukakis,
Bentsen and Jesse Jackson.
   ``I think there's two different stripes and three different
people. There's `very liberal,' and then there's Lloyd Bentsen.''
   ``My goal is to focus on the top of the ticket,'' Bush said.
   The vice president conceded that Democrats have seized national
attention with their convention. But, he added, the memory of
Democratic unity would soon be ``gone with the wind.''
   Bush allowed that Democrats staged an impressive show of unity
at their convention. But, he added, ``I don't know what's bubbling
under the surface of unity. There's a lot of bubbling discontent on
their side.''
   ``But that's got nothing to do with me,'' he added. ``My
business is to take on Michael Dukakis.''
   Meanwhile, administration and Bush campaign sources said James
A. Baker III will resign as treasury secretary to become Bush's
campaign chairman no later than Aug. 5.
   Bush said he would have something publicly to say on Baker's
role ``several Thursdays from now,'' reinforcing that timetable.
   Sources said New York investment banker Nicholas Brady, a former
Republican senator from New Jersey and chairman of the president's
task force studying last October's stock market crash, is the
leading contender to replace Baker as treasury secretary. The
sources spoke only on condition they not be identified.
   Bush spent last Saturday through Wednesday on a fishing trip
with Baker, a longtime friend and political adviser, in a remote
area near Cody, Wyo.
   ``I was in the wilderness _ no newspapers, no television, no
radio,'' Bush said. ``It was heaven.''
   Baker flew to California after the fishing trip so he could
discuss his decision to leave the administration and to head Bush's
campaign with President Reagan, administration sources said.
   Baker will become campaign chairman, a job that has been left
open for him. Baker ran Bush's 1980 presidential effort and was
senior counsel to Reagan's re-election campaign in 1984.
   Bush campaign manager Lee Atwater told reporters that he expects
to retain his current job title if Baker comes on as the No. 1
campaign official.
</TEXT>
