<1ST_LINE>r w PM-JuvenileDrugs     07-22 0154</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Juvenile Drugs,140</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Capitol Police Note Gigantic Increase in Teen Drug Arrests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of juveniles arrested for selling
drugs in the District of Columbia increased by 456 percent in 1987
compared to a year earlier, according to a city study.
   The report, released Thursday by the district's office of
criminal justice and analysis, indicates that 35 percent of those
under the age of 18 who were arrested tested positive for drugs.
The hallucinogen PCP was the drug most commonly used, the report
stated.
   The report attributes the rise in youth drug arrests to the
increased use of juveniles by drug dealers.
   In a repeat of a surprise finding from 1986, the city's
fashionable Georgetown section remains among the areas where
violent crimes are most likely to occur.
   Arrests of adults for drug possession decreased 18 percent in
1987, but arrests of adults for drug dealing incerased by 5 percent.
</TEXT>
