<HEAD>Six Crew Members Killed in Crash of Angolan Cargo Plane</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thoughout to UPDATE with report that bad weather caused
crash. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Angolan cargo plane crashed in bad
weather as it prepared to land in the Nigerian capital of Lagos,
and all six crew members aboard were killed, the official Angolan
news agency said today.
   The ANGOP report said the Boeing 707 was about 12 miles from
Murtala Mohamed Airport in Lagos when it crashed Thursday.
   The report said the plane from the state-owned TAAG company's
fleet was en route from Ostend, Belgium, to the Angolan capital,
Luanda, and was to land in Lagos to refuel. The report was
monitored in Lisbon.
   The statement said fog and low clouds were believed to have
caused the crash, ANGOP reported. It added that communications with
the pilot showed the flight was proceeding normally without
technical problems.
   ANGOP said a team of TAAG technicians left for Lagos to
investigate. The agency said the bodies of the six crew members
were recovered.
