<HEAD>Agriculture Department Declares Wisconsin Disaster Area</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Agriculture Department today declared
all 72 Wisconsin counties a disaster area because of the drought.
   The move makes some farmers eligible for Farmers Home
Administration loans to help offset losses.
   The announcement by Rep. Steve Gunderson, R-Wis., came a day
after U.S. Agriculture Secretary Richard Lyng visited a
drought-stricken dairy farm.
   While rain has fallen in Wisconsin the past week, it has come
too late to help many farmers salvage their crops. Corn and hay
have been hard hit by the drought. Both are used as money crops and
as feed for cows.
