<DOCNO> AP880722-0131 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-88 1156EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DefenseProbe-Documents 1stLd-Writethru avotingfor.``Oneofthenicethingsaboutvotingisyoudoitinsecret
07-22 0706</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Defense Probe-Documents, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0552,0722</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Unsealed Court Papers Detail Searches on Long Island</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 3 grafs with other actions in connection with
affidavits.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators seized files about a Florida
condominium, a golf tournament and contributions from a New York
paper company that was searched as part of the Pentagon fraud and
bribery inquiry, court papers show.
   The same court documents, unsealed Thursday, say one focus of
the investigation is on the possible extortion of campaign
contributions from companies by private consultants and others.
   This information was contained in an attachment to a search
warrant executed last month at the Kane Paper Co. in Baldwin. James
Kane, the president of Kane Paper, is the founder of the Long
Island Aerospace Political Action Committee.
   Among the documents seized at Kane Paper, which included
searches of trash receptacles, were a ``Florida condo file,'' a
``contribution file,'' a ``political file box'' and a folder
labeled ``golf tournament 1984-87.''
   The document also indicated investigators were probing whether
an employee of the Unisys Corp., a private consultant and others
bribed federal officials involved in the authorization or
appropriation of defense contracts.
   The Unisys employee named was Dennis Mitchell, whose office also
has been searched, and the private consultant was Charles Gardner,
a former Unisys employee.
   Unisys, a military contractor that manufacturers the Aegis fire
control and radar systems, earlier this week announced that it had
suspended six employees from its surveillance and fire control
unit, which Gardner formally headed.
   The Mitchell search warrant said investigators were looking into
a possible plot by Mitchell, Gardner and others ``to defraud Unisys
by diverting monies to individuals and business entities to
illegally influence the defense contracting process, and for their
own personal use.''
   According to published reports, Rep. Roy Dyson, D-Md., toured
the Unisys plant in Great Neck and was handed several campaign
contribution checks by Mitchell. Those checks and several others
mailed later totaled $14,000 and were from businessmen and others
interested in seeing increased military spending on Long Island,
the news reports said.
   Dyson, a member of the House Armed Services Committee, was on a
trip to see Unisys this year when his top aide, Tom Pappas,
committed suicide by jumping from a Manhattan hotel the day after a
Washington Post story said he made unusual work demands on members
of Dyson's staff.
   Another person who has been searched in the case is Richard
Seelmeyer, a former aide to the late Rep. Joseph Addabbo of Queens.
   The mention of campaign contributions came in one line in the
attachment that said investigators were looking into a scheme to
``extort campaign contributions from companies doing business with
...'' The rest of the statement had been deleted.
   The document was among four search warrants and related papers
ordered unsealed by U.S. District Judge Edward Korman of Brooklyn
in response to an application by Newsday Inc., a New York and Long
Island newspaper.
   The other search warrants were executed at the Hazeltine Corp.
in Greenlawn, the office of Mitchell in Great Neck and the home of
Gardner.
   The newly disclosed documents detail the numerous financial
records, computer files, letters and other property seized by
federal investigators at the four locations.
   The papers were heavily edited to protect individuals and
companies not previously named in court papers. This was a
condition to the disclosure set by Korman.
   In Washington, Pentagon spokesman Dan Howard said he had not
seen the court papers unsealed in New York and had ``no immediate
comment'' on them.
   Meanwhile, The Hartford (Conn.) Courant on Thursday asked U.S.
District Judge John H. Pratt in Washington to unseal affidavits
supporting a search of offices there of Pratt & Whitney, the jet
engine maker. Pratt already has denied a request by The Washington
Times for the same documents.
   In Minneapolis, U.S. Magistrate Earl Cudd today took under
advisement a request by Cowles Media Co., publisher of the Star
Tribune, for release of the affidavits supporting a June 13 search
of three offices at a Unisys plant in Eagan, Minn. Prosecutors on
Thursday opposing the release.
   Cudd said he would rule next week on whether the documents
should be released unedited or kept under seal.
</TEXT>
