<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AsbestosSuit     07-22 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Asbestos Suit,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Overturns Decision To Combine 35,000 Asbestos Suits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court has overturned a judge's
ruling combining 35,000 asbestos-related lawsuits against a company.
   A three-judge panel of the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
said Wednesday that consolidating the suits would slow resolution
of the cases.
   U.S. District Judge Robert L. Vining Jr. last month consolidated
the personal injury lawsuits against Raymark Industries Inc. at the
company's request, creating the biggest asbestos-related injury
case ever.
   More than 100 plaintiffs had objected to having their lawsuits
consolidated, saying none of them had been notified about the move,
according to court records. They also argued that the evidence did
not justify the action.
   In overturning the consolidation decision, the appeals court
said, ``The court's order, which essentially moves their cases back
to square one, could hardly place petitioners in a more drastic
predicament.''
   Raymark has been the target of 70,000 asbestos lawsuits
involving 82,000 people during the past 10 years. The suits claim
people developed asbestos-related diseases after exposure to
insulation and other Raymark products.
   Half the cases have been resolved by trial, settlement or
dismissal.
   Raymark, which expects 65,000 more cases to be filed during the
next decade, sought to have the suits combined in a class action
because the separate claims were depleting the company's insurance
coverage.
</TEXT>
