<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DullesPlane     07-22 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dulles Plane,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Safety Board Investigators Examine Crash Site</HEAD>
<HEAD>Retransmits a0631 to change cycle designation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHANTILLY, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National Transportation Safety Board
investigators searching for clues to the cause of a fiery crash of
a twin-engine charter plane combed through wreckage for the second
day today, said a NTSB spokesman.
   ``We don't know the flight history of the plane yet,'' said Ted
Lopatkiewicz. But he said the plane's owner, Fairways Corp., has
said it purchased the aircraft new in 1969.
   The 19-seat, propeller-driven commuter plane crashed Wednesday
during take-off at Dulles Interntional Airport west of Washington.
The only person on board was the pilot, Melvin Shockley of Fairfax,
Va., who was killed.
   Fairways has been identified by aviation officials as a charter
service based at National Airport, but The Washington Post has
reported that it is operated by the Central Intelligence Agency and
that information about the identity of the pilot was delayed at the
request of the CIA.
   CIA officials have said they would not confirm of deny any
contractural or proprietary relationship with Fairways.
   Fairways spokesman Joseph Hexter would not comment on reports
that his firm is connected to the CIA, saying only ``Fairways Corp.
is a charter airline which flies passengers for the United States
government and private companies.''
   Lopatkiewicz said Shockley, who was not identified until late
Thursday, had worked for Fairways for three years and was well
qualified to fly the plane.
   He said the pilot last week conducted a roundtrip flight to St.
Louis with a Lear jet, returning to National Airport with the jet
on Sunday.
   ``That was his last flight before the accident,'' said
Lopatkiewicz.
   The plane had been at Dulles for a routine maintenance check and
was headed back to National when it crashed.
</TEXT>
