<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-88 1218EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-BiologicalWarfare     07-22 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Biological Warfare,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scientists Say Defense Department Starting Dangerous Germ Warfare
Research</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of scientists said today that the
Department of Defense is asking for $300 million to start
biological weapons research that could be dangerous to the military
and to civilians worldwide.
   The scientists, organized as a group called the Committee for
Responsible Genetics, announced that it is circulating a petition
to encourage all American biological scientists to not participate
in Pentagon research that could result in the development of
biological weapons.
   ``It is clear that the world has come to the point that the
production of biological weapons is relatively simple,'' said
Christian Anfinsen, a Nobel Prize-winning biologist at Johns
Hopkins University in Baltimore. ``We could develop warheads to
spread anthrax (disease) within 6 months and so could the Soviets.''
   But, said Anfinsen, ``no war could be won this way'' because a
counterattack would be swift and deadly.
   The scientist said that with the advances in biology of recent
decades, scientists in many countries now could use genetic
techniques to develop viruses or bacteria against which there could
be no defense.
   Anfinsen and three other scientists said at a news conference
that the Department of Defense is asking for a $300 million
appropriation to accelerate its research into a defense against
biological weapons. They said the Pentagon plans to reopen the
Dugway Proving Ground in Utah as a biological weapons testilng
center.
   A Department of Defense spokesman, Lt. Col. Rick Oborn, said he
had no immediate comment on the statements.
   Jonathan King, a professor of biology at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology, said that the same techniques needed to
develop a defense against biological weapons can also be used to
develop the weapons themselves.
   ``In an offense biological warfare program, the first thing you
do is develop a vaccine,'' he said.
   King also said that the danger of biological weapons is that
they could lead to uncontrolled contamination of vast populations
if they are released.
   ``Biological weapons are not like gunpowder or nuclear bombs,''
he said. ``Biological weapons can spread and reproduce.''
   King and the other scientists said that Department of Defense
officials now are actively recruiting biologists to conduct germ
warfare research.
   ``I have been approached and most of us have,'' said King.
   The Committee for Responsible Genetics is circulating among
university biologists a petition that contains a pledge to not
engage knowingly in research that would further development of
biological warfare agents.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880722-0135 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-88 1222EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--DukakisConnects Bjt   07-22 0652</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Dukakis Connects, Bjt,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>The Buttoned-Down Governor Connects With Crowd on Big Night</HEAD>
<BYLINE>An AP News Analysis</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Inside the Omni hall late Thursday night, the
buttoned-down governor of Massachusetts strode into a spotlight,
walked confidently past the front row of delegates and climbed to a
height he had not reached before.
   When Michael Dukakis punched the air in the direction of the
Massachusetts delegation, his most fevered backers simply let go.
Standing, stomping and cheering, they fused into a screaming wave
of released energy.
   Before he finished the first line of his speech, they were again
on their feet. ``Let's go, Mike! Let's go, Mike!''
   ``... the race to the finish line begins. ...''
   Another wave of cheering. Seated side by side, Mary Anastopoulos
of Lowell, a daughter of Greek immigrants, and Amy Anthony, the
governor's tough-talking housing secretary, had to prop each other
up _ their shoulders shaking and their eyes red.
   ``... I accept. ...'''
   A roaring, pulsing outburst of flag-waving, sign-pumping energy,
reflected in Dukakis' own growing sureness and force.
   At the rim of The Omni, in a skybox above and just behind the
Massachusetts seats, campaign manager Susan Estrich stood front and
center, surrounded by her senior staff, surveying their handiwork.
   At her side was husband Marty Kaplan, an executive with the
Magic Kingdom of Disney. Sitting and standing together, they
personified the marriage of politics and show business unfolding
with stopwatch timing all around them.
   Far away, across the hall, a man they know as Michael and joke
about as a loner and pedant, was hitting his lines, opening his
self, and _ on the biggest night of his political life _ doing his
job.
   ``...time to exchange voodoo economics for can-do economics.
...''
   Amplified and fortified by all the wizardry of big-time
productions, Dukakis became the focus of the hunger in the hall for
belief, for challenge and above all for victory.
   ``... those handsome and proud and articulate Jackson children.
...''
   With his gestures and his language, Dukakis encompassed nearly
all of the doubters, leaving Bill Strickland of Amherst, Mass., a
down-the-line Jackson coordinator, to shrug and join in.
   As representatives of the governor's home state, the
Massachusetts delegation was jammed with delegates and staff,
filling every seat and jamming the aisles, standing anywhere they
could perch to shout, pump their signs up and down, and punch
little American flags in the air.
   Seasoned politicians, some of the state's highest elected
officials, men who usually sneer at cornball enthusiasm, were
clapping in unison, bouncing on their toes in time to march music,
and cheering for a man they thought they knew.
   ``... we will never bring disgrace to this, our country. ...''
   By mid-speech, the only peole moving besides TV correspondents
were the Dukakis whips, working the aisles as best they could,
making sure every delegate had a sign and a flag at the right
moment, leading the cheers, pushing and whipping the faithful along.
   For politically alert people from Massachusetts, there was
nothing new in the speech _ no stories or facts or attitudes they
had not heard before, in some cases many times.
   But by the end, the Massachusetts corner of the building and all
the gear and people in it were fused into a giant, pulsing,
stomping, cheering body.
   Dukakis worked all his levers and pushed all his themes _
family, success, seriousness, purpose, and, above all, a will to
win.
   On their way out, the hoarse and sweaty delegates paused to get
their bearings, surprised at themselves and at him.
   Some were openly fired up. Others had that quiet look often seen
in the eyes of the Dukakis team that says they would walk through
walls for the guy.

</TEXT>
<HEAD>____</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Christopher B. Daly, the AP Statehouse bureau
chief in Boston, has covered Michael Dukakis for five years.
</TEXT>
