<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Royal Insult,0152</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>King Pardons Minister Imprisoned For Remarks on Monarchy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   King Bhumibol Adulyadej on Friday
pardoned a former minister who was imprisoned for insulting the
monarchy when he said life in the royal palace was much easier than
peasant life.
   Veera Musikapong, a former deputy minister, began serving a
four-year sentence last month after the Supreme Court upheld a
lower court conviction on charges of ``lese majesty,'' an offense
against a ruler's dignity.
   Veera, 40, made the remarks in July 1986 while campaigning in
the northeastern Buriram province for a Parliament seat.
   He resigned in September 1986 when opposition parties seized on
the issue to attack the government of Prime Minister Prem
Tinsulanonda.
   In upholding Veera's conviction, the Supreme Court reduced his
sentence from six to four years.
   Interior Minister Prachuab Soontrangkul informed reporters
Friday of the king's decision to pardon Veera.
</TEXT>
