<DOCNO> AP880722-0140 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-88 1246EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Drought-CARE     07-22 0215</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-CARE,0220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Overseas Needy Suffer U.S. Drought</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Recipients of assistance from the international
relief agency CARE, many of them victims of drought in their
homelands, are being victimized a second time as the drought in
this country dries up the supply of basic food commodities, the
agency said.
   Prices for such foodstuffs as wheat, corn and cooking oil are
escalating, forcing CARE to reduce the amount available for
distribution to Africa, Asia and Latin America, said CARE spokesman
George Wirt.
   ``Already the kinds of foods and the amounts of foods that will
be available are being affected,'' said Rudy Von Bernuth, the
agency's director of programs. ``We have already lost powdered milk
for next year.''
   CARE's food programs are funded by government grants and private
contributions. While income remains constant ``the prices are going
up so fast that the tonnage level needed to support the programs
will not be met.''
   ``In literal terms it will mean less on their plates,'' Von
Bernuth said. ``Resources are going to be stretched very thin.''
   For example, Wirt said, the price of vegetable oil has gone from
$7.12 a gallon earlier this year to $8.55. It's expected that
bulgur wheat, which recently sold for $183 a ton, will top $200 a
ton, he said.
</TEXT>
