<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--BankFire-Falcons     07-22 0172</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Bank Fire-Falcons,0176</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fire Fails To Faze Falcons</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pair of peregrine falcons apparently still
consider the Union Bank building home despite a fire that burned
offices several floors below their roost.
   ``They're fine,'' said Union Chairman John Harrigan, who
monitors the nest on the 39th floor by a closed-circuit television
in his office a floor below.
   Offices on the 34th and 35th floors of the 39-story building
were scorched Monday night after a paint thinner-soaked cloth
touched an outlet and ignited a fire.
   The peregrines were brought to Union Bank six years ago by the
national Peregrine Fund and the Western Foundation of Vertebrate
Zoology in an effort to re-establish the endangered species
downtown.
   The falcons already have raised a male offspring.
   ``They identify very much with this building. It is the center
of their little universe,`` Harrigan said. ``They came by yesterday
(after the fire) and looked the place over. I don't know what they
thought. They might have thought it was a little smoky.''
</TEXT>
