<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SAmerica-USDrought Bjt   07-22 0737</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAmerica-US Drought, Bjt,0758</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Drought Is Billion-Dollar Boon To Argentina And Brazil</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Olacyr de Moraes is cq. in 5th graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RANDALL HACKLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The drought in the United States
is turning into a multi-billion-dollar boon for farmers in
economically distressed Argentina and Brazil, agricultural experts
say.
   While U.S. crops wilt under the worst drought conditions since
the Dust Bowl, recently harvested crops of soybeans and winter
wheat in Argentina and Brazil are fetching the highest export
prices in years, the experts say.
   Many of Argentina's 450,000 farmers are planting as much as
possible to cash in on record prices for soybeans, which last year
replaced wheat as the country's No. 1 cash crop. Argentina is the
third-largest producer of soybeans after the United States and
Brazil.
   Soybean plantings increased 19 percent in Argentina and 15.6
percent in Brazil this year compared to 1987, the experts say.
   Olacyr de Moraes, Brazil's soybean king and one of the country's
richest men, just bought 74,100 acres in northern Maranhao state to
plant the crop.
   After suffering from years of low world grain prices, Argentine
farmers of wheat, corn, sorghum and soybeans see a bright
short-term future. They are buying land and ordering new tractors
and farm equipment.
   ``We're all conscious that our well-being is owed to the drought
in the United States,'' said Rogelio Luraschi, manager of the
Carlos Casado farm cooperative outside Rosario, 200 miles northwest
of the capital.
   Earlier this month, Agriculture Secretary Ernesto Figueras
estimated revenues this year from grain exports _ primarily
soybeans, wheat and corn _ at 3.8 billion dollars, up 2 billion
dollars from 1987.
   In Brazil, the government estimated revenues from soybean
exports, its top cash crop, at $3.5 billion this year, up $1.2
billion from 198. It expects a bumper soybean crop of 18.2 million
tons, up from 17 million tons in 1987.
   The multi-billion-dollar boost couldn't have come at a better
time.
   Argentina is plagued by an average annual inflation rate of 322
percent, unproductive state industries and worker unrest over wages
that fail to match the rising cost of living.
   Brazil too is suffering from an economic crisis. It is the
developing world's largest debtor, owing creditors $121 billion.
Mexico is second, followed by Argentina, which owes $55 billion.
   Although the Argentine and Brazilian soybean crops are close to
being fully harvested, farmers in both countries say they are
holding on to much of their stock to see what the market will do.
   For instance, the price of a 132-pound bag of Brazilian soybeans
has tripled since April, compared to an inflation rise of 68
percent in the same period. Inflation in Brazil is averaging 600
percent this year.
   ``The new international prices will signify a big boost in
revenues for the country, '' said Guillermo Alchouron, president of
the Argentine Rural Society, an association of the nation's most
important farmers and ranchers.
   But the Argentine Association of Grain Producers fears the
government may cut new-found profits by reimposing export duties
abolished last year.
   When Argentine President Raul Alfonsin denied such plans last
month, Alchouron said: ``Farmers were waiting for this message.
It's necessary to prevent the deterioration of a sector like
farming, which can bring the country out of the (economic) crisis.''
   One result of higher international grain prices is the rising
cost of farmland in productive areas like that outside Rosario,
which has doubled since January, Argentine farmers say. Brazilian
soybean farmers report similar trends even in the normally dry
northeast.
   Feed prices also have risen for poultry and livestock producers,
forcing some Argentine producers to slaughter their livestock or
reduce poultry stocks.
   Even the price of cookies in Argentina, the fourth-largest
consumer of cookies per capita in the world, has risen because of
the rise in the price of wheat, producers note.
   Curiously, Argentina's government has been low key about its
farmers' good fortune.
   The daily business newspaper Ambito Financiero of Buenos Aires
noted the government ``doesn't want to show too much euphoria with
all of this because it is negotiating for fresh funds with the
foreign lending institutions.''
   Hector Huergo wrote in Somos Magazine last month that Argentine
farmers would be wise to take their profits now.
   ``As Keynes said, in the long-term, we'll all be dead,'' Huergo
said. ``In the meantime, the question is how to take advantage of
the drought.''
</TEXT>
