<1ST_LINE>u i PM-UN-Iran-Iraq 3rdLd-Writethru   07-22 0679</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Iran-Iraq, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0603,0701</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Secretary-General Invites Foreign Ministers to UN</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with Perez de Cuellar inviting
foreign ministers to New York. Pick up 7th graf pvs: `Perez de
Cuellar...' DELETES last 3 grafs.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
said today he has invited Iran and Iraq to send their foreign
ministers to New York next week to discuss implementing a
U.N.-sponsored cease-fire and peace plan.
   There was no immediate reaction from Iran or Iraq, but envoys of
both nations have said their foreign ministers or other high
officials would accept an invitation from the secretary-general.
   ``I very much hope to see them early next week in New York,''
Perez de Cuellar told reporters.
   Iran, meanwhile, accused Iraq of trying to sabotage U.N. efforts
to end the 8-year-old Persian Gulf war by pushing for face-to-face
peace talks.
   Iraq has urged direct negotiations with Iran in New York before
a cease-fire goes into effect. Iran has rejected the proposal,
saying it only will negotiate through the secretary-general.
   The U.N. Chief declined to comment directly on the format for
negotiations, but Middle East sources said Iraq would be interested
in proximity talks through the secretary-general as intermediary
between the belligerents.
   Perez de Cuellar did not say whether Iraq formally has agreed to
receive a U.N. technical team to work out details of a cease-fire.
   Iran already has agreed to receive the eight-man team, which is
to arrive in Tehran Sunday from Jerusalem and Vienna. Iraq has not
made a similar committment.
   ``I expect the team to arrive in the area in the next few
days,'' Perez de Cuellar said.
   There was no official word on whether Iraq would accept the
team. Iraqi officials said the U.N. request to receive the team is
under study.
   The Baghdad government has called for direct talks before a
cease-fire and has said that the visit of the team to Iraq and its
request for talks in New York were being discussed together.
   Perez de Cuellar said that after the team's weeklong visit he
would be able to set all the dates to put Security Council
Resolution 598 in motion.
   The resolution, passed a year ago, calls for an immediate
cease-fire, prisoner exchange, troop withdrawal, comprehensive
peace talks and an impartial body to determine which side started
the conflict.
   Iran announced Monday that it unconditionally accepts Resolution
598 and wants an immediate cease-fire. Iraq, which has said for the
past year that it accepts the resolution, now says Iran should
prove its sincerity in direct talks before a cease-fire.
   Iranian Ambassador Mohammad Ja'afar Mahallati denounced Iraq's
new proposals as efforts to ``sabotage the peace process.'' He said
Iraq was trying to introduce ``extraneous elements which will only
complicate the whole thing.''
   ``Iraq wants to gain some more territory and leverage,'' he said.
   Iranian Counselor Mohammad Javad Zarif said Iraq is ``going
against its own statements endorsing Resolution 598 which calls for
an immediate cease-fire.''
   He said Iran has ``unconditionally accepted the resolution and
its implemention in explicit statements'' by his nation's highest
leaders.
   ``This is not a tactical continuation of the war and there is no
excuse for Iraq to delay implementation of Resolution 598,'' he
said.
   Iraqi Foreign Minister Tariq Aziz sent a five-point proposal to
Perez de Cuellar on Wednesday, calling for direct talks in New
York, Baghdad and Tehran.
   ``The request of the secretary-general to dispatch a mission is
under discussion in Baghdad,'' Iraqi Ambassador Ismat T. Kittani
told a news conference Thursday.
   But he refused to say whether Iraq would allow the team to visit
after direct talks were arranged.
   ``We are at a critical juncture and there should not be a
stampede to cease-fire _ that's only a small part of a
comprehensive and durable peace,'' he said. ``Pressuring Iraq would
be counter-productive.''
   He said that he was surprised that Iranian officials refuse to
talk directly with Iraq.
   ``With whom are they going to negotiate and sign a comprehensive
peace agreement?'' he asked. ``The secretary-general?''
</TEXT>
