<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-88 1354EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--DukakisStrategy     07-22 0691</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Dukakis Strategy,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>It's Back On The Road For A `50-State' Campaign With Careful
Targets</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-CVN--Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A triumphant Michael Dukakis and running mate
Lloyd Bentsen left Atlanta on Friday promising a 50-state campaign.
But several states will be clearly emphasized as the Democrats work
to piece together a winning Electoral College puzzle.
   Dukakis and his aides said all week that they ``would not
concede one single state to the Republicans in the fall,'' and in
appearance they won't. But concessions aside, the intinerary for
the first post-convention campaign swing is instructive for what it
says about Dukakis' fall strategy.
   Texas, California and Pennsylvania will be key battlegrounds,
aides said in a series of briefings this week. All three states are
on the schedule for the quick, cross-country trip Dukakis and
Bentsen began the day after they accepted their nominations. There
also are stops in Missouri and North Dakota _ tougher challenges
for the Democrats but an early warning to Republican George Bush
not to take things for granted, anywhere.
   ``Where we are strong, we will be highly visible,'' said one
senior Dukakis adviser. ``Where we are not so strong, we will try
to turn things around and if we can't we'll give the troops enough
ammunition to maintain a battle.''
   The war for the 270 electoral votes needed to win the White
House likely will be waged on two fronts.
   Bentsen is up for re-election to the Senate and will spend the
bulk of his time running a dual campaign in Texas, something
Republicans already are criticizing. Dukakis aides said Bentsen
also will campaign throughout the South and Southwest, recently
Republican regions vital to a Democratic victory in the fall. While
doing the job he was appointed to do _ heaping praise on Dukakis _
Bentsen also will woo elderly and blue-collar voters with talk of
his key role in the passage of catastrophic-illness health care and
plant-closing legislation, Dukakis and Bentsen aides said.
   Dukakis, having signed bills balancing his state budget, will
spend much of the hundred-plus days before the election
crisscrossing the country with his message of competence and
economic opportunity. Campaign aides see victories in a half-dozen
big states _ California, New York, Illinois, Ohio, Michigan and
Pennsylvania _ as vital. Those states hold 175 electoral votes.
Texas, with its 29 electoral votes, is a crucial test that will
show the wisdom or lack of it in selecting Bentsen, and Dukakis
aides say they also think Florida is winnable.
   ``This is a truly national ticket, with a national message that
can win in November and will not allow the Republicans, as they
have in the past, to take any state for granted,'' Dukakis
spokesman Dayton Duncan said.
   A leading Republican critic of the Democratic ticket sees it
otherwise.
   Sen. Bob Dole of Kansas, like other Republicans tying Jesse
Jackson to the ticket, said Friday that ``the liberal candidates
will target the Northeast while the other candidate takes to the
South.''
   Dukakis left Atlanta with a double-digit lead over Bush in
national polls, but just moments after his optimistic and unusually
emotional acceptance speech, he cautioned delegates about
overconfidence.
   ``We're going to need you all,'' he told a post-convention
party. ``This is going to be a tough, tight, competitive race.''
   That ``all'' includes Jackson supporters. By next week the
Dukakis campaign expects to announce that numerous Jackson campaign
aides have joined ranks with the nominee.
   The additions will take over as state directors of the Dukakis
effort in several states, as well as co-directors and deputy
directors, said Charlie Baker, the Dukakis campaign's director of
field operations. A dozen state directors' posts are as yet
unfilled, including those in several states Jackson won.
   Baker refused to name the Jackson aides being recruited but said
he would have a list for Dukakis to review as he headed South, then
West, then to the Midwest, and finally back East with Bentsen.
   Dukakis, who insists on interviewing all prospects for top
campaign jobs, will conduct some interviews on the trip and others
shortly after returning to Boston, Baker said.
</TEXT>
