<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AbortionInjunction     07-22 0213</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Abortion Injunction,0218</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Refuses to Block Aboartion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EDMONTON, Alberta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge today refused a man's request
to prevent his former girlfriend from having an abortion.
   Justice Joanne Veit of Court of Queen's Bench said, however,
that the man, Randy Mock, 25, could sue for damages for such things
as emotional trauma if 18-year-old Michelle Brandanburg goes
through with the abortion.
   Mock had obtained a temporary injunction preventing Ms.
Brandanburg from having the abortion. The 48-hour injunction
expired Thursday.
   Mock's lawyer, Rosanna Saccomani, had argued Thursday that the
two were bound by an oral contract when they agreed as a common-law
couple in February to stop using contraceptives so they could have
a child.
   ``There was an intention to create a child. ... That was what
the parties wanted,'' she said. ``She should continue with her
obligations.''
   The pair, who had gone together for 18 months, broke up in June.
Ms. Saccomani said that they still care about each other but that
Ms. Brandanburg's family opposed the relationship. She said Mock
was willing to raise the baby himself.
   Donna Oliver Dyck, who represented Ms. Brandanburg, told the
court that Mock had no rights as the father of an unborn child and
that the application to stop the abortion was ludicrous.
</TEXT>
