<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WaterFlap     07-22 0238</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Water Flap,0244</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>City Restores Water Service to Elderly Recyclers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LINCOLN CITY, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An anonymous benefactor has paid the
garbage collection bill for an elderly couple, prompting the city
to call a truce with the ardent recyclers and restore their water
service.
   The city cut off water July 13 to Clarence James, 84, and his
wife, Dorothy, 82, under an ordinance requiring all residents to
have garbage collection, which costs at least $2.57 a month. The
couple refused to pay the fee, saying they don't generate enough
non-recyclable trash to warrant such service.
   City Manager Doug Zenor said he received $25 Thursday to pay for
reconnecting the couple's home to the city water system. He would
not say who paid the bill except that it wasn't the Jameses or a
city employee.
   Kim Nisbet, a secretary at North Lincoln Sanitary Co., said
somebody paid a year's fees for the couple.
   Calls to the couple's home went unanswered.
   Council members adopted the mandatory garbage collection law
last fall because people were using trash bins at parks and on
highways to get rid of household garbage, Zenor said. He said the
ordinancy has made the city cleaner.
   He said that before the ordinance, 1,600 to 1,700 homes had
water and sewer service but no garbage service. A number of homes
in this beach city, 75 miles southwest of Portland, are second
residences for people who live elsewhere.
</TEXT>
