<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Honored Women,0167</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Women To Be Inducted Into Hall Of Fame</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SENECA FALLS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Astronaut Sally Ride and poet
Gwendolyn Brooks will be inducted into the National Women's Hall of
Fame in a ceremony later this year, Hall of Fame spokeswoman Susan
Barber said today.
   Ride, 37, became the first American woman in space in 1983 when
she flew on the space shuttle. On her second flight the next year,
she carried a scarf from the hall of fame that belonged to aviator
Amelia Earhart, also an inductee.
   Brooks, 71, of Chicago, was the first black woman to receive a
Pulitzer Prize for poetry. She won in 1950 for her volume of poetry
``Annie Allen.'' In 1958, she succeeded Carl Sandburg as poet
laureate of Illinois.
   Seneca Falls, between Syracuse and Rochester, is considered the
birthplace of the women's movement because it is where a group of
protesters in 1848 wrote the ``Declaration of Sentiments'' calling
for equal rights for women.
</TEXT>
