<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-88 1429EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Reagan-Brazil     07-22 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Brazil,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Moves Against Brazil</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan moved today to
impose trade sanctions on Brazil for denying patent protection to
U.S. and other foreign pharmaceutical firms.
   ``The United States cannot tolerate the piracy of its
intellectual property,'' White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwatezr
said in a statement issued as Reagan vacationed at his ranch north
of here.
   The president's action means that the United States will hold
hearings to determine what penalties to impose for Brazil's alleged
trade infractions.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the hearings would
determine what products would be subject to sanctions.
   He said Brazil eliminated patent protection for pharmaceuticals
in 1945 and for pharmaceutical processes in 1969.
   The president acted at the request of the Pharmaceutical
Manufacturers Association, a Washington-based trade organization.
Fitzwater said U.S. companies lose an estimated $36 million a year
because of Brazilian policies that permit unahtorized copying of
pharmaceutical products and processes that were invited by U.S.
firms. Eighteen of the association's members do business in Brazil.
They claim losses including lost export sales, unrecovered research
costs and reduced profit margins.
   Today was the deadline for the administration to complete its
investigation of the charges.
   Reagan said his action was part of a three-year campaign by the
United States to challenge infringement of its intellectural
property rights throughout the world.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
