<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Italy-ToxicWaste     07-22 0222</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-Toxic Waste,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Italian Ships Will Take Waste Back From Nigeria</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Italian ships will bring several tons of
unidentified toxic waste back to Italy from Nigeria's Port Koko,
Civil Defense Minister Vito Lattanzio announced Friday.
   The minister said he could not immediately say where or how the
toxic wastes will be disposed of in Italy.
   Lattanzio's announcement was expected to ease diplomatic
tensions between Italy and Nigeria and lead to the release of the
Italian freighter Piave, which was seized by Nigerian authorities
pending a solution of the case.
   The Nigerian government claimed hundreds of drums filled with
toxic waste were illegally taken to Port Koko while the Italian
company which shipped the waste claimed it had been authorized by
Nigerian officials.
   Lattanzio said one Italian freighter already sailed for Nigeria
while the second will leave within a few days.
   Last month another load of toxic waste was shipped back to Italy
after authorities in Djbouti, Venezuela and Syria refused its
disposal.
   The 2,100 metric tons of toxic material belonging to Italian
chemical firms are aboard the freighter Zanoobia, currently
anchored in the Italian port of Genoa.
   A metric ton is equivalent to 2,205 pounds.
   An Italian firm won a $5.3 million contract to dispose of the
Zanoobia's waste. Unloading operations have not yet been started.
</TEXT>
