<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MalpracticeAward     07-22 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Malpractice Award,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>$3.2 Million Negligence Award</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kaiser Foundation Hospitals and Northwest
Permanente have been ordered to pay $3.2 million to a woman who
received substandard care during labor and delivery of her son,
born with mental and physical disabilities.
   An attorney for Kaiser admitted to a three-judge arbitration
panel that substandard care provided to Cheryl Ostergren caused
injury to her son, Keith, in January 1985. The award was made
earlier this month.
   Northwest Permanente is a professional corporation of physicians
practicing at Kaiser Foundation Hospitals. Ostergren first received
care at Sunnyside Medical Center and later at Bess Kaiser Medical
Center in Portland, both of which are operated by Kaiser.
   A complaint filed in Multnomah County Circuit Court alleged that
doctors and nurses failed to interpret fetal monitor readings
showing the fetus in distress. Attorney Keith Tichenor alleged the
baby should have been delivered by Ceasarean section or by use of
forceps.
   The birth was unreasonably delayed, resulting in mental
retardation, cerebral palsy, and mental and physical development
delay, according to the complaint.
   Evidence presented at a hearing indicated the child will need
lifelong care.
   The case was removed from circuit court to arbitration under
terms of a Kaiser contract with patients calling for arbitration of
claims of more than $500 against Kaiser or Northwest Permanente
physicians and surgeons.
   Arbitrators Pat Dooley, a retired circuit court judge, and
lawyers Charles Paulson and David Landis on July 13 set damages at
$3,230,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
