<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Burns     07-22 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burns,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justice Department Decides Against Burns Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department has concluded there is
no basis on which to conduct a criminal investigation of former
Deputy Attorney General Arnold Burns for promoting his former law
partner for a judgeship, sources said Friday.
   The criminal division's public integrity section reached the
conclusion, said the sources, speaking on condition of anonymity,
after reviewing information about the relationship between Burns
and Stuart Summit, who has been nominated to the 2nd U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals in New York.
   Burns was still receiving payments from the law firm and had
investments in limited partnerships with Summit at the time he was
urging Summit's nomination last year.
   Burns resigned in protest in March over a different issue _ the
continued leadership of the department by Attorney General Edwin
Meese III, who then was under an independent counsel's
investigation for alleged conflicts of interest. That probe
concluded without indictment, though independent counsel James
McKay said Meese ``probably'' violated the law on four occasions.
Meese has since announced his own resignation, but insisted that he
was vindicated.
   The Washington Times disclosed Burns' support for Summit in
articles last month, suggesting the former deputy attorney general
might have violated federal conflict-of-interest law.
   When asked about the public integrity section's decision, Summit
said he was ``not surprised, there never was anything to it'' and
said he was pleased about the outcome.
   Burns and former criminal division chief William Weld plan to
testify next Tuesday about their March 29 protest resignations.
   They quit out of concern that the continued tenure of Meese was
hurting Justice Department operations and morale.
   Congressional sources and sources close to the Justice
Department have said the leaking of unfavorable information about
Burns and Weld has been an attempt to discourage them from
testifying before the Senate Judiciary Committee.
   The Washington Times this month disclosed that Weld had been the
focus of an internal Justice Department investigation into whether
he smoked marijuana at a wedding in 1982. Weld has emphatically
denied the allegation, made in an anonymous letter, and the
department's Office of Professional Responsibility closed the
matter.
</TEXT>
