<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DrugAgent-Slain     07-22 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug Agent-Slain,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mexican Offical Allowed DEA Agent's Killer To Go Free, Documents
Charge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man who allegedly ordered the murder of a
U.S. drug agent was allowed to escape by a Mexican police official
who embraced him at an airport and sent him on his way, court
documents charge.
   According to the documents filed Thursday in U.S. District
Court, reputed Mexican drug trafficker Rafael Caro Quintero was
involved in a standoff with federal Drug Enforcement Agents and 20
to 30 Mexican police officers when the police official, Armando
Pavon Reyes, intervened.
   Authorities had caught up with Caro Quintero as he was about to
escape from the country from a Guadalajara airport, the documents
say. Both the officers and Caro Quintero's people had guns drawn
when Pavon Reyes embraced the reputed drug kingpin, according to
the documents.
   Caro Quintero, suspected of ordering the February 1985 murder of
DEA agent Enrique Camarena, then reportedly got on an airplane and
left.
   He was captured in Costa Rica in April 1985 after a brief
shootout with police.
   The documents outline the prosecution's case against Rene
Verdugo Urquidez, Raul Lopez Alvarez and Jesus Felix Gutierrez, all
charged in connection with Camarena's kidnapping and murder.
   Opening statements in the trial are due next week.
   The documents say Camarena ``was repeatedly and severely beaten
about the head and face with a blunt instrument'' and was killed by
a blow to the head.
   Nine people were charged in the case but one, Ines Calderon
Quintero, recently was killed by Mexican police, said Assistant
U.S. Attorney Roel Campos. Four others are in custody in Mexico.
   Pavon Reyes' whereabouts are uncertain. U.S. Attorney Robert
Bonner said he is in a Mexican jail, but Jose Antonio Gonzalez, the
Mexican attorney general's attache in Washington, D.C., said Pavon
is a fugitive.
</TEXT>
