<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ColoradoTrail 1stLd-Writethru a0674 07-22 0715</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colorado Trail, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0674,0730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Completion of 470-Mile Trail Culminates 15-Year Effort by
Volunteers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs the 17th graf, beginning ``I'd say,'' to restore dropped
first reference to Gov. Lamm.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLEN HADDOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 470-mile Colorado Trail, 15
years in the making mostly by volunteers and winding through
aspen-covered mountain valleys, is to be dedicated this weekend.
   But some of its builders couldn't wait. They're already out
hiking.
   Spanning two-thirds of Colorado, the Colorado Trail passes
through five national forests, cross the Continental Divide five
times and skirts not only 14,000-foot Rocky Mountain peaks but also
historical sites, ghost towns and environmental no man's lands
scarred during the mining boom days.
   Most of the trail was built by 3,000 volunteers, said Dennis
Neill, a Forest Service spokesman. Many spent entire weeks of
vacation clearing brush and building trail.
   ``The Forest Service did the dangerous stuff, like blasting
rocks and chain-sawing trees, but the volunteers brought in by the
Friends of the Colorado Trail Foundation did the real work,'' Neill
said.
   The trail begins at Waterton Canyon southwest of Denver, and
climbs gradually over Kenosha Pass to Breckenridge. Then it wends
its way toward Copper Mountain near Leadville and past a cluster of
14,000-foot peaks west of Buena Vista and Salida.
   It turns southwest near Saguache and veers toward Molas Pass,
near 11,000-foot-elevation Silverton, before dropping into the
Animas River drainage in the San Juan Mountains to Durango, in
southwestern Colorado.
   The trail has been a struggle since its inception in 1973 when
Bill Lucas, then regional forester in Denver, and a group of hikers
hashed out the idea one evening.
   The Forest Service was being criticized for providing only the
extremes of recreation _ rugged wilderness treks or roadside
camping.
   Lucas' idea was to use trails to link major tourist centers. A
hut system would be developed so hikers would not have to lug tents
and stoves.
   ``The huts are still a long way off,'' Neill said.
   At first, plans called for the Colorado Trail to be finished in
1978, two years after it was launched as one of the state's
centennial-year projects. The foundation bearing its name collected
its first $150,000 easily, including a $100,000 grant from the
Denver-based Gates Foundation.
   But the foundation did not get anything done because of
``unrealistic expectations,'' said Mayo ``Butch'' Sontermeyer, a
Fort Collins lawyer who served on the foundation board from its
beginning.
   About the time the foundation sort of fell apart, Gudy Gaskill
of Evergreen, who had been involved from the beginning, decided to
take charge of the volunteer effort.
   Gaskill, now 61, organized crews to clear a mile of trail a
week. By using volunteer labor, she and the Colorado Mountain Club
got the work done for $500 a mile, compared with the $8,000 per
mile she estimated it would cost the Forest Service.
   ``You can't say enough about Gudy's leadership,'' Neill said.
``She can out-walk, out-run and out-work anybody half her age. I
know, because she did it to me.
   ``I'd call it her fanatical attachment to a dream. She got
things moving again and the bulk of the trail work has been done in
the last four years, since she, (former Gov. Richard) Lamm and
(then regional forester) Jim Torrence got things rolling again.''
   Gaskill couldn't be reached for an interview this week because
she was out hiking her trail. She was expected to reach Durango in
time for a dedication ceremony Saturday at the Junction Creek
Trailhead, five miles northwest of town.
   A second ceremony, Sunday at Waterton Canyon near Denver, is to
feature the arrival of four Durango residents who have spent the
last two weeks running the trail.
   In a previous interview, Gaskill said the trail is a historical
route, ``showing what happened in Colorado.''
   ``It goes by record devastation such as Climax (open pit
molybdenum mine), timber cuts and burned areas, as well as splendid
pristine areas,'' she said.
   ``It shows the whole spectrum of the backcountry,'' she said.
``There are areas close to historical sites and others close to
man-made environmental damage, as well as reforestation sites where
major forest fires occurred. We go near or through three ghost
towns and three mining towns.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880722-0168 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-88 1440EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon-Violence     07-22 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon-Violence,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Car Bomb in West Beirut Kills Seven</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car bomb exploded near a Syrian
military base in Moslem west Beirut during morning rush hour
Friday, killing 10 people, wounding 51 and destroying more than a
dozen cars, police said.
   Thirty-three pounds of explosives concealed under the rear seat
of a yellow Mercedes-Benz and connected to a timing device went off
at 10:40 a.m. in the working-class Cola neighborhood, they said.
   The blast occurred between a pharmacy and a gas station about 20
yards from the Syrian military intelligence base and a Syrian
checkpoint erected at the entrance, police said.
   ``We have not been informed of any Syrian casualties,'' said a
police officer on the scene, who could not give his name according
to police regulations.
   Reporters counted 19 parked cars destroyed, six of them gutted
down to smoldering piles of metal. Glass shards littered the
bloodstained main Cola street as civil defense rescuers collected
parts of human bodies torn apart by the explosion.
   No group claimed responsibility for the attack, which appeared
aimed at discrediting Syria's law-enforcing mission in the Moslem
sector of the Lebanese capital.
   It was the 10th car-bombing in violence-ridden Lebanon this
year, bringing the overall casualty toll in such attacks to 106
dead and 354 injured.
   Most of the victims in Friday's blast were Lebanese civilians
from the gas station and three adjacent high-rise apartment
buildings that sustained severe damage, he said. The driver of the
car was also killed.
   ``We saw something like lightning and then an ear-splitting
blast rained glass shards on us. We were flat on our bellies,''
said Ahmad Muti, an employee at the Cola gas station.
   Syrian troops, armed with rocket-propelled grenades and AK-47
assault rifles, sealed off the blast scene. They fired their in the
air to make way for ambulances rushing victims to hospitals.
   At least three Lebanese news photographers were beaten by Syrian
soldiers as they tried to shoot pictures of the wreckage.
   In the last car-bombing four days ago, a car blew up in
Christian east Beirut's Ashrafiyeh residential district, killing a
civilian and wounding another.
   Lebanon's 13-year-old civil war, pitting Moslems against
Christians, has claimed more than 130,000 lives since it broke out
in 1975.
</TEXT>
