<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--DNC     07-22 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--DNC,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Top Democratic Panel Adds Members in Dukakis-Jackson Deal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a last-minute, high-pressure deal, aides to
Michael Dukakis and Jesse Jackson agreed Friday to expand the
Democratic National Committee by nearly twice as many positions as
the two camps had come to terms on earlier this week.
   Jackson, the runner-up to Dukakis for the presidential
nomination, took the majority of the new seats, as expected under
the agreement worked out by the two candidates and announced Monday.
   After more than two hours, the committee went along with the
plan to add two new vice chairs and 20 new at-large members.
   And in addition, DNC Chairman Paul Kirk named Jackson's son,
Jesse Jackson Jr., to another at-large slot.
   ``This is a time we need everyone. We must have everyone for
victory in November,'' Kirk said. ``This will be a further
expansion of our party.''
   The new vice chairman of the party for voter registration is New
Orleans Mayor Sidney Barthelemy.
   The new vice chairman representing the state party officials is
Rick Weiner, head of the Michigan party.
   Barthelemy backed Jackson and Weiner voted for Dukakis at the
convention.
   The new at-large members include Jackson aides Ron Brown, Willie
Barrow, Yolanda Carraway and Toney Anaya.
   The new at-large members from the Dukakis camp include John
Sweeney, president of the Service Employees International Union;
Los Angeles City Councilman Richard Alatorre, and Dukakis aide
Susan Brophy.
   The changes in the national party's structure are intended to
meet the presidential runner-up's demand that the DNC be more
reflective of the rank and file.
   All these changes had to be written into the party's charter and
were adopted without dissent.
</TEXT>
