<DOCNO> AP880722-0170 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-88 1442EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CVN-Jackson Bjt   07-22 0771</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN-Jackson, Bjt,760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Warns He's Prepared to Turn on `Street Heat'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson on Friday began to fulfill his
pledge of Democratic unity but warned Michael Dukakis and Lloyd
Bentsen that he is prepared to turn on the ``street heat'' to make
sure they heed his followers' agenda.
   In a dramatic meeting with several hundred supporters, Jackson
presented the newly nominated Dukakis-Bentsen ticket with
magnanimous words of praise and assured the delegates, ``It is in
order and it is right to support this ticket because of our access
to it and relationship with it.''
   But Jackson also cited historical precedent that social change
comes from a combination of leadership and ``street heat.''
   He promised that through registering millions of voters this
year, ``There will be enough heat to cook our meat and enough heat
for George Bush to get out of the kitchen.''
   To Dukakis and Bentsen, Jackson said somberly, ``You ask us
trust you. All that we can ask of anyone is that they not betray
that trust.''
   He told his supporters:
   ``I feel hopeful. ... I feel secure, confident you will be
protected in your role in the campaign,'' in the newly expanded
Democratic National Committee, and in ``the role I choose to serve,
one that is supportive, one that is respected and that's enough.''
   He added that he and his supporters had gained respect and
access, and ``we've never had those two things before.''
   The Jackson delegates reacted warmly to Dukakis, but were more
subdued during Bentsen's brief remarks.
   Dukakis recalled that Bentsen had earned his civil rights
stripes years ago as one of the two senators who voted to kill the
poll tax.
   Dukakis then appealed for the group's support.
   ``We're going to need you. We want you. We can't win without
you,'' Dukakis said.
   Rep. Ron Dellums, D-Calif., set a tone of acceptance for
Dukakis. The congressman delivered a moving tribute to Jackson and
said that while the group had wanted Jackson in the White House,
``Last night, I saw a man mount the podium and react to Jesse
Jackson with dignity and respect unheralded.''
   The room erupted in applause and cheers of ``Duke, Duke,'' in
the first sign that the ice was being broken for Dukakis, who
lauded Jackson and his family in a speech Thursday night.
   Jackson introduced Dukakis to the room as ``a man I've come to
know and respect ... a man I've come to know in great detail and
love because of his own sensitivity to family and the people.''
   Walking a line in which he tried to build enthusiasm for Dukakis
at the same time as he put the nominee on notice that pressure for
his own agenda would continue, Jackson said:
   ``I bring to you the man I intend to watch up close on a cold
day Jan 20, 1989, when he becomes and deserves to become the next
president of the United States of America.''
   Jackson emotionally noted Dukakis' wish that his immigrant
father could have seen him nominated for the presidency.
   With eyes glistening and a catch in his voice, Jackson said that
by the same token, ``I wish Dr. (Martin Luther) King could have
been here'' for the Democratic convention that saw Jackson come in
a respectable second to Dukakis.
   Acknowledging that some of his backers were bitterly
disappointed when Dukakis did not pick him for his running mate,
Jackson said, ``The victory lies not in what Gov. Dukakis and Lloyd
Bentsen can do for us. The victory lies in the fact that our minds
have changed about ourselves and our reasonable expectations have
been expanded.''
   He reiterated that he does not want a job or title in a Dukakis
administration or campaign. Instead, he said, ``I want to serve,
(be) free to serve at my own pace, free to support, free to
challenge.''
   Jackson made what may have been hints about his own future
plans, noting as he often has the historical significance of his
candidacy in the evolution of blacks' power that began decades ago
with the civil rights struggles. ``We have every reason to be
hopeful, to be excited. Know that we are close to where we are
going, a long time from where we started and in our lifetime, you
and I will be in the White House.''
   Later he said, ``We are well on our way. ... I don't feel no
ways tired. Even (President) Reagan ran three times, tired as he
was,'' he added in what the crowd seem to interpret as a hint of a
future presidential bid.
</TEXT>
