<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ContraSuit     07-22 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Contra Suit,0457</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Christic Institute Announces Appeal Of Contra Suit Ruling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILL LESTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An attorney for the Christic Institute filed formal
notice Friday that he will appeal the dismissal of a $24 million
lawsuit against some Iran-Contra figures alleging guns-for-drugs
deals and a 1984 terrorist bombing.
   The Christic Institute will appeal to the 11th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals a June 23 ruling by Chief U.S. District Judge
James Lawrence King that the plaintiffs, journalists Tony Avirgan
and Martha Honey had failed to prove their allegations, said
attorney Daniel Sheehan.
   The group is representing the journalists, who filed suit
against 29 people, including Richard Secord and Albert Hakim,
Contra leader Adolfo Calero, former CIA deputy director of
operations Theodore Shackley, and retired major general and
anti-communist crusader John K. Singlaub.
   ``The bottom line is that something in excess of 90 percent of
summary judgments by trial judges are reversed,'' said Sheehan.
``The major purpose of the appeal is to get the case reinstituted
and expand the scope of the trial.''
   Sheehan said he has 10 days to file the appeal.
   The suit was filed in May 1986, six months before the
Iran-Contra affair became public. Many of the people it brought to
light, such as Secord, Hakim, Calero and Singlaub, have been
indicted or forced to appear before congressional committees
investigating that case.
   The suit involved heroin smuggling from Laos, the ``Phoenix''
assassination program in Vietnam, the Bay of Pigs fiasco, cocaine
smuggling from Colombia, illegal Contra arms running, bombings,
threats, disappearances -all to push what the plaintiffs believed
was an activist right-wing ideology.
   It alleges that Shackley and others, using drug profits,
assassinated officials first in Vietnam, then Iran, Nicaragua and
other nations.
   The key event in the suit was the May 1984 bombing of a news
conference held by Contra commander Eden Pastora in La Penca,
Nicaragua. Three journalists and five Pastora supporters died.
Avirgan was hurt and his camera damaged in the explosion, allowing
him to file a civil damage suit under federal law.
   The suit charged the bombing was arranged by Shackley, Contra
leaders and others angry that Pastora refused to join
anti-Sandinista groups he considered too close to the CIA and
deposed Nicaraguan dictator Anastasio Somoza Debayle.
   An attorney for Singlaub, Thomas Spencer Jr., alleged the
lawyers who filed the suit were guilty of bad faith and asked King
this week to penalize them. He said the Christic Institute, as well
as other plaintiffs, should be liable for more than $275,000 in
legal fees and $88,000 in expenses for Singlaub alone.
   Total fees for all defendants have been estimated at more than
$800,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880722-0172 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-88 1526EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Burma-MartialLaw     07-22 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burma-Martial Law,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Martial Law Imposed North Of Rangoon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government imposed martial law on the
central city of Prome on Friday after a week of Moslem-Buddhist
rioting that left one person dead and six injured.
   Government radio announced that a state of emergency also was
imposed on the city, which is 180 miles north of the capital.
   Rioting broke out there July 16 and spread to nearby villages
after a fight between a Buddhist customer and Moslem shop owner. No
details were released on the reason for the fight.
   ``Since the situation has developed beyond the control of the
local civil administration, the council of state placed Prome
township under martial law with effect from 6:00 p.m. July 22, with
a view to maintaining law and order and to prevent religious
riots,'' the announcement said. About 200,000 people live in Prome.
   A curfew was still in effect in Taunggyi, where a quarrel
between a Buddhist monk and Moslem youths sparked a riot July 11 in
which four people were killed and 20 wounded.
   Those riots followed unrest in Rangoon, the capital, in March
and June involving students from various universities and
educational institutions.
   The government closed nearly all universities and colleges after
the unrest and imposed a dawn-to-dusk curfew in the capital.
Hundreds of people were arrested.
   The protests appeared to reflect mounting opposition to the
authoritarian rule of U Ne Win, who seized power 26 years ago in a
military coup.
</TEXT>
