<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SpaceShuttle     07-22 0233</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Space Shuttle,0239</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shuttle Test Firing Delayed Two Days</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA said Friday it is delaying the
launch pad test-firing of space shuttle Discovery's main engines
two days until July 30.
   The decision was made after shuttle managers reviewed
preparations and concluded that all elements were not ready,
including a hazardous gas detection system that is not completely
checked out.
   The 20-second firing of the main engines is considered critical
to certifying Discovery for the first shuttle flight since the
Challenger explosion killed seven astronauts on Jan. 28, 1986.
   It will test modifications made in the engines and provide
countdown experience for the launch team.
   NASA officials said the delay in the test-firing could postpone
for a day or two the launch, now scheduled for early September.
   However, the status of the launch date is very much in doubt as
engineers are puzzling over how to fix a small gas leak in a
steering engine system that is separate from the main engines.
   They hope to make the repair on the pad and avoid rolling
Discovery back to a hangar, a move that could delay the flight by
as much as two months.
   Experts are considering several ways to reach the inaccessible
leak, from cutting a hole through the cargo bay wall to running a
snake-like tube through the gas line in an effort to plug the leak.
</TEXT>
