<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-88 1629EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BeachWaste     07-22 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Beach Waste,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Environmental Officials Find No Smoking Gun for Beach Waste</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York's top environmental official Friday
said there is no single source for the medical debris and other
trash that has washed up on beaches in the New York City area in
recent weeks.
   The waste may have come through the sanitation system, from
untreated sewage, illegal dumping, littering from boats or some
combination of all these, said Environmental Conservation
Commissioner Thomas Jorling.
   An unusual, extended wind pattern also is partly to blame for
washing the debris ashore, he said in a preliminary report on the
waste that has forced the closing of miles of popular beach in past
weeks.
   ``There is no single answer that puts this thing behind us,''
Jorling said.
   The presence of garbage such as cigarette butts and condoms
mixed in with medical debris suggests the debris had more than one
source, Jorling said.
   He called it extremely difficult to trace the waste, which
includes syringes, rubber gloves and at least 10 vials of blood.
   One vial out of seven tested has shown the presence of the AIDS
virus, he said. Three more brought in Thursday were still being
tested, he said.
   Peter Slocum, Health Department spokesman, said none of the
vials tested thus far had any identifiable markings.
   Even if investigators find markings on the medical waste, it's
doubtful they'll be able to find and prosecute illegal dumpers, he
said.
   ``It's a very tricky case to make,'' Jorling said. ``You start
with an isolated blood vial on the beach some hundred miles or more
from any possible point of origin, and taking that blood vial back
through steps in a chain is a very difficult investigative burden
to carry.''
   On Thursday, officials in Monmouth County, N.J., identified an
Asbury Park sewage plant as the likely source of pollution that has
plagued four New Jersey seashore communities since last week.
   Beaches in Asbury Park, Ocean Grove, Bradley Beach and
Avon-by-the-Sea were closed by high levels of fecal bacteria in the
water.
</TEXT>
