<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AIDSSuit     07-22 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Suit,0234</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Blood Bank Loses Appeal to Protect Name of Donor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENVILLE, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A blood bank has lost an effort to
protect the identity of a donor whose blood may have been tainted
with the AIDS virus.
   The South Carolina Supreme Court dismissed an appeal of an order
requiring the Carolina-Georgia Blood Bank to identify the donor
whose blood was used in a transfusion for Daisy Lee Young.
   Mrs. Young, 74, was being treated for AIDS-related symptoms when
she died at Spartanburg Regional Medical Center earlier this year.
   Lawsuits filed by her husband and her estate allege she acquired
AIDS from a transfusion received at Self Memorial Hospital in
Greenwood after a 1985 hip operation. The suits accuse the blood
bank and the hospital of negligence.
   Circuit Judge Frank McGowan Jr. ruled in May that the blood bank
had to release the name of the donor. The blood bank appealed,
saying the donor's right to privacy outweighed the plaintiffs'
interests.
   The Supreme Court refused the case July 8.
   The blood bank now is asking that McGowan to limit the questions
lawyers can ask the donor and that the donor be referred to as John
Doe in any court documents.
   Scientists say a blood screening test that came into use in 1985
has virtually eliminated the risk of AIDS from a transfusion.
</TEXT>
