<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-88 1518EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CVN--PoliticalRdp Bjt   07-22 0713</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Political Rdp, Bjt,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democrats' Team Heads for the Campaign Trail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis and Lloyd Bentsen, the Democrats'
shiny-new national ticket, began the general election campaign
Friday with the boost of high praise from Jesse Jackson. Republican
George Bush immediately tried to drive a wedge into the ticket,
citing ``tremendous differences'' between the running mates.
   With the week's peaceful and unified national convention as his
base, Dukakis crossed the Atlanta street that had divided his
campaign from Jackson's to ask for enthusiastic support.
   ``We're going to need you. We want you. We can't win without
you,'' Dukakis told several hundred cheering Jackson supporters in
a hotel ballroom. ``We have 110 days, and I hope we can enlist
every single one of you in this cause.''
   Then Dukakis and Bentsen headed to Texas, Bentsen's home state,
to start a three-day cross-country swing that was designed to be a
fast start for the Democrats' effort to win the White House back
from the Republicans.
   For his part, Jackson lavished praise on Dukakis even more
generously than he had in his campaign valedictory to the
convention Tuesday night.
   The Democratic presidential nominee is ``a man I've come to
know, to respect ... a man I've come to ... love because of his own
sensitivity to family,'' Jackson said. ``I bring to you a man I
plan to watch up close ... when he becomes ... the next president
of the United States _ Michael Dukakis.''
   Amid cheers of ``Duke! Duke! Duke!'' Jackson promised excitment
for the Democratic ticket in the fall and glory in the future.
   ``It is in order and it is right to support this ticket because
of our access to it and our relaionship with it,'' Jackson said.
``We have every reason to be hopeful, to be excited, to know that
we are close to where we are going, a long way from where we
started...And in our lifetime you and I will be in the White
House.''
   Dukakis delivered on a key Jackson demand Friday, as the
Democratic National Committee added new officials and new members
to ``expand the party.'' A majority of the new members were Jackson
backers.
   Jackson repeated that he wants no title from Dukakis: ``I want
to serve, free to serve at my own pace, free to serve, free to
challenge.''
   In Milwaukee, Bush praised Dukakis' acceptance speech at the
Thursday night convention session, but suggested there might be
internal problems for the Democratic ticket.
   ``I thought he gave a very good speech,'' Bush told reporters at
an Italian festival. ``He did a very good job.''
   The Republican vice president has gone out of his way in recent
days to praise fellow Texan Bentsen as a conservative even as he
has painted Dukakis as a liberal.
   ``The differences are enormous,'' Bush said, between the
Democratic presidential and vice-presidential candidates.
   Bush told reporters that ``an effective use for Lloyd Bentsen''
would be for him to persuade Dukakis to change his positions on gun
control, prison furlough programs and many other issues.
   Bentsen has also drawn praise from Jackson, desite their many
differences on the issues. But Jackson warned Friday that Bentsen
bears a heavy burden that accompanies the support from more liberal
Democrats.
   ``In a real sense, your occasion is now,'' Jackson told Bentsen.
``You ask us to trust you. All we can ask of anyone is that they
not betray that trust.''
   Even as Jackson praised Dukakis and Bentsen, he promised them
that there would be differences in the Democratic family, saying
the progressive agenda will be won with ``a combination of street
heat and leadership.''
   He promised Dukakis, ``There will be enough heat to cook our
meat and enough heat for George Bush to get out of the kitchen.''
   Dukakis was quick to point out that he and his running mate have
strong records on civil rights.
   The Massachusetts governor recalled the civil rights struggle
and spoke of his own experience traveling to Washington, D.C., in
1953 and seeing the intense segregation of the nation's capital at
that time.
   Then he emphasized that Bentsen, as a Texas congressman had
voted in 1948 to against the poll tax that was used to deny voting
rights to blacks.
</TEXT>
