<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-88 1754EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-US-BrazilTrade 1stLd-Writethru a0708 07-22 0667</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Brazil Trade, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0708,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Slaps Trade Sanctions on Brazil</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: To update with Pharmaceutical Manufacturers Assocation
reaction INSERTS one graf after 10th graf bgng ``By denying ... ''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan imposed trade
sanctions against Brazil on Friday in retaliation for that
country's denial of patent protections for U.S. pharmaceutical
products.
   Acting under a section of the Trade Act of 1974, Reagan started
a process which will lead to sanctions against $200 million worth
of yet unspecified Brazilian imports.
   Reagan's move came after what the White House said was a
years-long quest by the U.S. government and the American
pharmaceutical industry to persuade Brazil to enact ``adequate
patent protection.''
   Brazil has been unwilling to abolish a longstanding industrial
property code which holds that pharmaceutical products and the
pharmaceutical manufacturing process are ineligible for patent
protection.
   The Pharmaceutical Manufacturers Association petitioned the
government for an investigation, arguing that Brazil's refusal to
protect intellectual property rights has restricted U.S. commerce
and cost American pharmaceutical manufacturers more than $160
million from 1979-86.
   An administration official, commenting on condition of
anonymity, said the loss to U.S. producers is now running at about
$36 million a year.
   ``We regret that it is necessary to impose trade sanctions in
this matter,'' White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said in a
statement read to reporters here as Reagan neared the end of a
week-long vacation.
   ``But the U.S. cannot tolerate the piracy of its intellectual
property,'' he said. ``Over the past three years, we have
challenged the infringement of U.S. intellectual property rights
and denial of rights throughout the world.''
   Fitzwater said this policy has ``resulted in strengthened patent
laws in many foreign countries.'' He said ``this progress stands in
stark contrast to Brazil's lack of action in this area.''
   ``By denying this basic commercial right,'' Fitzwater said,
``Brazil permits unauthorized copying of pharmaceutical products
and processes that were invented by U.S. firms. This not only
deprives American companies of sales, it discourages investment in
the research and development of new drugs.''
   The Pharmaceutical Manufacturers Assocation said it welcomed
Reagan's move. The association's president, Gerald J. Mossinghoff,
said, ``the United States cannot permit its pharmaceutical industry
to sustain substantial losses as a result of Brazil's refusal to
recognize patent rights for pharmaceutical products and processes.''
   The United States had come close to slapping trade sanctions on
Brazil earlier this year, but backed away when that country
responded to complaints about its policies regarding importation of
software products.
   The administration official said the sanctions would more likely
take the form of tariffs against $200 million in Brazilian imports
_ as opposed to embargoing $200 million in that country's products.
   Reagan's order triggers a process through which the U.S.
government will hold public hearings to determine which Brazilian
products will be affected by the punitive measures.
   Fitzwater said the administration had given Brazil ``every
opportunity to change'' its patent policy. He also said that while
he did not believe Brazil would retaliate, ``that's always a
possibility.''
   Reagan has only occasionally invoked sections of the trade laws
to retaliate against countries suspected of engaging in unfair
trade practices, and Congress is near completion of legislation
that would revamp American trade laws.
   Reagan vetoed an earlier version, citing several factors,
including a provision requiring major employers to give workers at
least 60 days notice of layoffs and plant closings. That provision
now has been passed, as separate legislation, by both the House and
Senate via veto-proof margins.
   The White House has not said specifically whether Reagan would
veto the new plant-closing bill, although that is believed to be
his intention. Nor has it said whether he would veto the revised
trade bill, which is still pending in the Senate.
   Last year, Reagan imposed sanctions against Japan, accusing it
of dumping electronic products into the United States at
below-market prices and of refusing to open its own markets to U.S.
computer components and other such products.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
