<DOCNO> AP880722-0190 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-88 1755EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MsvsMrs     07-22 0609</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ms vs Mrs,0628</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Ms.' Judge Involved In Series Of Confrontations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TARA BRADLEY-STECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge who threatened a lawyer with
jail for using her maiden name in court is known for threatening
attorneys with arrest and calling them names, including ``dumb
Jew,'' lawyers said Friday.
   Senior U.S. District Justice Hubert Teitelbaum, 73, prompted
feminists to demand his resignation when he recently ordered
attorney Barbara Wolvovitz to use her husband's last name and not
use `Ms.' during a race discrimination trial.
   Attorneys who have tried cases before Teitelbaum said Friday his
courtroom antics began years ago.
   ``He's very bright. He's very knowledgeable in the law. But he's
very domineering. He takes over your case and tries it for you,''
said Pittsburgh attorney Harvey Daniels.
   Teitelbaum, a former U.S. attorney and FBI agent who first took
the bench in 1971, could not be reached for comment Friday. There
were no answers at either his office or home telephones. He has
consistently refused to talk to the press.
   Leonard Sharon, a former Pittsburgh attorney now practicing in
Auburn, Maine, said Teitelbaum ordered him arrested and called him
a liar in 1984 when he tried to file a petition, which the judge
claimed contained erroneous information.
   ``I didn't lie, but if he has facts that say I did, someone else
should'' have decided the issue, Sharon, 42, said Friday. ``He
can't pitch and call balls and strikes at the same time.''
   Sharon said his wife, Claudia, also an attorney, entered the
courtroom carrying their infant just in time to see marshals
surround him.
   ``Teitelbaum told her `You get out of the courtroom' and said
something to the effect that she should be home watching the
baby,'' Sharon said.
   The judge vacated his order.
   Sharon said he later was subpoenaed to testify before a federal
judicial panel investigating a complaint against Teitelbaum filed
by Stanley Preiser, a former Pittsburgh lawyer who now practices in
Charleston, W.Va., and Boca Raton, Fla.
   Sharon said he doesn't know the outcome of the investigation,
and Preiser said he was prohibited by court rules from disclosing
it.
   Preiser said Teitelbaum called him a ``dumb Jew'' during an
August 1985 hearing when he asked the judge to reschedule a case
around a Jewish holiday.
   ``He said `It was the first time I had known you were Jewish,
because I have never met a dumb Jew before,''' recalled George
Mahfood, Presier's co-counsel in the case.
   ``I was stunned and astounded,'' said Preiser, 60. ``That
courtroom was totally different from any other American courtroom I
had been in before.''
   Teitelbaum stepped down from the case after the two attorneys
asked the 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals to disqualify him.
   On Jan. 19, 1973, Teitelbaum sent federal marshals to the
Allegheny County Courthouse for attorney Allen Brunwasser, who was
finishing a trial in the local court. As soon as the trial ended,
Brunwasser was escorted to Teitelbaum, who jailed him for 48 hours
for contempt for not attending a hearing scheduled at the same time.
   Brunwasser served the time, but the 3rd Circuit cleared
Brunwasser of the contempt conviction.
   ``There is no more powerful man than an American judge sitting
in his courtroom,'' Brunwasser said. ``He is a king.''
   Meanwhile, Ms. Wolvovitz's clients, Charles Gavin and William
Sutton, who lost their race discrimination case against PPG
Industries Inc., said Friday they will act as their own attorneys
in an appeal.
   They claim the jury was prejudiced by Teitelbaum's comments to
Ms. Wolvovitz, who they said promised Teitelbaum she would not cite
the Ms.-Mrs. flap on appeals and won't represent them on that
ground.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
