<1ST_LINE>r i AM-CVN--ConventionAbroad     07-22 0396</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Convention Abroad,0421</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Overseas Opinions on Democratic Convention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a sampling of foreign opinion Friday on the Democratic
National Convention, which ended Thursday in Atlanta, Ga.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>FRANCE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Le Monde, the prestigious independent newspaper:
   ``In the euphoria of the Atlanta convention, the Democrats
celebrated their force and their best point for the upcoming
presidential campaign: unity ....
   ``In the image of its new champion, the cerebral and opinionated
Dukakis, the Democratic Party is no longer flamboyant but
`performance-oriented.'''
   Liberation, a leftist newspaper:
   ``The Atlanta convention adopted a platform which will count as
one of the shortest in the history of the party. General and
imprecise enough to permit interpretations and adaptations, it will
certainly not trigger a great debate of ideas ....
   ``(Dukakis) is also a simple man, economic, living like a middle
American, the ideal or almost the American dream incarnated by this
son of an immigrant. Does that suffice to preside over the destiny
of the world's first power, or at least is it the idea Americans
themselves have of their president? Dukakis has less than four
months to convince them.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>WEST GERMANY</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Friedrich Bohl, a member of Parliament in the governing
Christian Democratic Union party, said:
   ``We welcome the fact that the convention has turned down Jesse
Jackson's call for rejection of the first use of nuclear weapons.
This decision is in the best interests of European and German
security. It is in line with NATO's strategy, which has kept the
peace in Europe since World War II.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>GREECE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Greeks reacted with restraint to the nomination of Michael
Dukakis, despite his Greek background. Newspapers published only
brief stories from reporters who attended the Atlanta convention.
   In a brief congratulatory message to the candidate, the
Executive Committee of Premier Andreas Papandreou's governing
Panhellenic Socialist Movement said ``the Greek people worldwide
were moved'' by the Democrat's presidential nomination.
   But residents of Pelopi, the small mountain village on the
island of Lesbos that calls itself the hometown of Dukakis, reacted
with jubilant song and dance and an all-night party at the news.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>NICARAGUA</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The leftist Sandinista government's newspaper, Barricada, gave
banner-headline display to remarks by Dukakis. ``Dukakis: Reagan
Era Ended,'' its seven-column headline trumpeted.
   In boldface print above a news agency story, the paper quoted
Dukakis as saying ``Sandinistas aren't a threat to U.S. national
security; it's drugs.''
</TEXT>
