<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-88 1932EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ABA-Aquino     07-22 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-ABA-Aquino,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>ABA Asks Aquino to Probe Killings of Two Lawyers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Bar Association is asking Philippine
President Corazon Aquino to condemn the slayings of two
human-rights lawyers there.
   Lance Lindblom, a representative of the 340,000-member group,
was meeting Thursday and Friday with the Free Legal Assistance
Group of the Philippines and planned to deliver a letter signed by
ABA President Robert MacCrate, said Craig Babb of the ABA's
Washington, D.C., office.
   The ABA letter specifically mentions Alfonso A. Surigao Jr., who
often represents military detainees and was killed by gunmen June
24 at his Cebu City home, and Emmanuel Mendoza, 57, who was
ambushed in his car July 2.
   ``We respectfully urge that you publicly condemn these recent
attacks against human rights lawyers and that you order thorough
investigations,'' it says, citing ``reports that the Philippine
military may have been involved in the murder'' of Surigao.
   ``The American Bar Association is deeply concerned over the
murder of Mr. Surigao and Mr. Mendoza and the harassment and
killings of several other lawyers in the Philippines over the past
few months,'' MacCrate wrote.
   ``We are further concerned that, to our knowledge, there have
been no arrests in these cases, nor in the earlier killings'' of
three other civil-rights lawyers, he wrote.
   Baab said Friday he did not know if Lindblom had delivered the
letter to Mrs. Aquino. It asks her to inform the ABA of progress in
the investigations.
   The ABA has sent similar letters to other countries since 1975,
when it adopted a policy supporting the independence of lawyers and
judges around the world, Baab said. In 1985, it sent a letter to
Mrs. Aquino's predecessor, then-President Ferdinand Marcos, after
attacks on lawyers.
</TEXT>
