<DOCNO> AP880722-0195 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-88 2100EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-MovieCensors     07-22 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Movie Censors,0460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nudes Or No Nudes: Law On Film Censorship Being Debated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Censors are debating whether to ban sex and
serious crimes from Chinese movies and are considering establishing
the country's first rating system to keep children from seeing some
films altogether.
   The rating system would protect younger children from movies
that could ``harm their healthy minds,'' the official China Daily
and Outlook magazine reported.
   A proposed law now would mark the first time since communist
China was established in 1949 that explicit standards have been set
about what can and cannot be portrayed in a Chinese movie.
   In the past, censorship changed with the political climate of
the country. When the country was ruled by hard-line leftists,
censorship was quite strict. When moderates took command,
censorship was relatively lax.
   Outlook quoted Chen Haosu, vice minister of radio, film and
television, as saying the regulations were needed to eliminate the
ambiguity surrounding artistic expression.
   ``If there's no law, then you can interfere with anything,''
Haosu was quoted as saying.
   But some artists in China say they thrive on the ambiguity,
preferring to work within the present vague situation where a
liberal turn in the political wind might allow a controversial work
to slip by.
   China produces more than 100 feature films a year and boasts the
largest movie industry in the world, employing 500,000 workers.
   In the 10 years since China began to open to the West about a
dozen movies have been ``killed'' by China's censors, Ai Zhisheng,
the minister of radio, film and television, told Outlook.
   Others have been revised ``with the help of the film company,''
he said.
   Outlook said censors agreed Chinese films should not hurt China
or the unity of its numerous nationalities, nor should they distort
history or exert an unhealthy influence on the morals of the people.
   But it said censors disagreed on nudity and crime.
   An article of the proposed law bans naked bodies and sex scenes
from all movies. But Outlook said some officials argued nudity and
sex should be forbidden only when they have no relation to the plot.
   Another proposed article forbids graphic descriptions of
criminal acts because officials fear they might trigger copy-cat
crimes. Outlook said some officials favored limiting the clause to
only serious crimes such as rape and drug trafficking.
   Outlook said some officials were also pushing to institute a
rating system for movies.
   ``There are many movies that aren't good for children or that
shouldn't be seen without the presence of an older family member,''
Chen was quoted as saying. He said China needed to establish a
rating system as soon as possible.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880722-0196 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-88 2102EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AuthorApologizes     07-22 0602</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Author Apologizes,0617</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>John Hersey Apologizes to Fellow Author Over Lack of Credit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MONROE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Author John Hersey apologized Friday for using
uncredited material from another writer's book in a New Yorker
article on James Agee.
   Hersey said he should have credited some of his sources,
``especially Laurence Bergreen's `James Agee: A Life,' the most
comprehensive and thoroughly researched biography of Agee so far
published.''
   Bergreen had told his lawyer to complain to The New Yorker and
to Houghton Mifflin, which had commissioned the piece as an
introduction to a new edition of Agee's ``Let Us Now Praise Famous
Men.''
   Houghton Mifflin said in a statement: ``Mr. Hersey feels that
several of the sources on which he draws for facts about Mr. Agee's
life, beyond his own recollections, should be credited, and they
will be.''
   Agee, a critic, novelist, journalist and screenwriter, died in
1955.
   ``The facts that a biographer or historian digs up don't belong
to him. They belong to the public. Anybody has a right to use
them,'' Hersey said Friday in a telephone interview from his home
on Martha's Vineyard.
   ``But the one thing that is protected is the mode of
expression,'' he continued. If in the course of a 12,000-word
article ``I used a dozen or so words. ... I certainly did not
intend to steal them from him.''
   He said he thought there was ``a fine line'' between one's right
to use material and one's respect for the work of another writer
and that his offense was not great in terms of normal practice.
   Bergreen said he came across the July 18 issue of the New Yorker
during a lunch break and because ``I had interviewed Hersey for my
biography I turned to read it with considerable interest.''
   ``As I read it I discovered that there were a number of passages
which were very closely modeled on my own in the book. There were
numerous instances where he was using my phrasing, my choice of
words and structure and so on.''
   With the exception of an introductory anecdote about Agee, ``the
rest of the piece, which was a rather long one, amounted to a
condensation of my biography,'' Bergreen said.
   For example, Bergreen's book described a scene between Agee and
Alma Mailman, his second wife: ``Alma once tied a blue ribbon in
Agee's hair, as if he were a poodle. Forgetting the bow was in
place, he opened the door to converse with a delegation of church
ladies who had come a-calling.''
   In The New Yorker article, Hersey wrote: ``One day, Alma
pretended that Jim was a poodle, and tied a blue ribbon in his
hair. Some church ladies came to call, and Jim the poodle dressed
for showing went to the door and let them in.''
   Hersey confirmed that he had written the editors of The New
Yorker, saying in part, ``I very much regret any discourtesy on my
part, or any distress caused to Mr. Bergreen or others'' by his
omission of credit.
   Rhonda Pinzer, the public relations director of The New Yorker,
said the next issue would contain a Department of Amplification,
which is how the magazine deals with such questions. She could not
confirm that it would contain Hersey's letter.
   Hersey, who won the Pulitzer Prize for fiction in 1945 with his
``A Bell for Adano,'' is the author of more than 20 books including
``Hiroshima,'' ``The Child Buyer,'' and ``The War Lover.''
   Bergreen also wrote ``Look Now, Pay Later: The Rise of Network
Broadcasting'' and is working on a biography of Irving Berlin.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
