<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ClaiborneHearing     07-22 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Claiborne Hearing,0407</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Federal Judge Seeks to Resume Law Practice</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MACY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Exactly two years after the U.S. House
voted to remove him from the bench, an impeached federal judge who
served 17 months in prison for tax evasion sought Friday to resume
practicing law in federal court.
   The Nevada Supreme Court in November cleared Harry Claiborne to
practice at the state level and his attorney, David Goldwater, on
Friday repeated the argument he used there, that Claiborne has been
punished enough.
   He should be allowed ``the basic civil right to make a living,''
and ``to be restored the dignity his profession affords him,''
Goldwater added.
   Jay Sourwine, president-elect of the Nevada Bar Association,
told U.S. District Judge Robert Broomfield, ``The Claiborne affair
has caused a great deal of damage to the bar and to the state court
system. We urge you don't let it do damage to this court.''
   Broomfield, of Phoenix, Ariz., took the matter under advisement
and gave no indication when he might rule.
   ``I think I have paid a price for a debt I feel I didn't owe,''
Claiborne, 71, told reporters. ``I was denied parole twice. I did
the mandatory maximum sentence that I could do.
   ``You don't go to a minumum-security prison unless you're
parolable. I was an unusual case, I guess.''
   He also joked about one of Goldwater's comments.
   ``I'll always make a living,'' he said. ``Even if I have to dig
ditches.''
   Claiborne was convicted of failing to report $106,651 on his
1979 and 1980 income tax returns. The U.S. House voted 406-0 two
years ago Friday to impeach Claiborne, who was removed from office
after an October 1986 Senate trial. He was the first federal judge
banished from office by Congress in 50 years.
   Claiborne charged at the time of his impeachment trial and again
Friday that he was the victim of a government vendetta because he
attacked agencies like the FBI and Justice Department Strike Force
while on the bench. He alleged misconduct by federal agents and
bias on the part of U.S. District Judge Walter Hoffman, who
conducted his 1984 income tax trial and sentenced him to prison.
   The state Supreme Court, in its 163-page decision in November,
said Claiborne shouldn't be punished any further.
   He was named a federal judge in 1978.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
