<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Gay-LesbianConference     07-22 0459</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gay-Lesbian Conference,0476</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study Says Lesbians Suffer More Stress Than Heterosexual Women</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A survey of lesbian health problems found that
homosexual women experience much more stress than heterosexuals but
share similar concerns about physical and mental health, its
authors said Friday.
   ``It dispels some of the myths about lesbianism,'' said
co-author Caitlin Ryan, social worker and researcher.
   The National Lesbian Health Care Survey, undertaken with some
federal funding, was presented at the weeklong 10th National
Lesbian and Gay Health Conference and AIDS Forum, which ends
Tuesday.
   The survey by Ryan and co-author Judith Bradford of Virginia
Commonwealth University was conducted by sending 10-page
questionnaires to 4,600 women. The 2,000 respondents from
throughout the nation ranged from 17 to 80 years old.
   Eighty percent of the respondents were between 25-44 and about
70 percent were in professional or managerial jobs; 46 percent of
participants had one child or more or were childless but wanted to
have one. Most lived in metropolitan areas.
   Ryan said she had no error margin for the results because the
study was the first of its kind and because no one knows the size
of the base population of lesbians.
   ``The data indicate that lesbians are very much like
heterosexual women in their concerns about health care and mental
health concerns,'' Bradford told an audience of about 200 people
who attended the survey presentation.
   ``But it is quite different as far as access to non-discriminate
care, and the level of stress,'' she said.
   Among the study's findings:
   _Substance abuse among lesbians becomes greater as they age,
especially among the 50-55 age group. ``The older lesbians tend to
be very isolated,'' Ryan said. ``Their partner may die, and they
become very depressed and turn to substance abuse.''
   _More than one-third of those surveyed said they were physically
abused as a child.
   _Half said they have been verbally attacked and 8 percent
reported they had been physically attacked because of their
homosexuality.
   _Fifteen percent said they lost jobs because they were lesbians.
   _Seventy-five percent said they relied on some form of
counseling.
   ``The percentage of us who are worried about jobs is
considerably higher than the concern about jobs expressed by
heterosexual women,'' Bradford said.
   ``Where we found the great differences is in the area of mental
health, in stress-related issues,'' Bradford said.
   ``This does not surprise us, but we can document it. We can see
through our data how health issues that are related to stress are
greater in our population,'' she said.
   The research began with $20,000 in funding, supplemented later
by $8,000 from the National Institute of Mental Health.
   About 1,500 homosexual men and women are at the gathering that
includes a speech scheduled Monday by Sen. Edward M. Kennedy,
D-Mass.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
