<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Korea     07-22 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea,0422</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Korean Leaders Say They'll Consider Proposed Meeting With
North</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korea's political leaders said
Friday they will consider a North Korean call for parliamentary
talks on easing military and political tensions on the divided
Korean peninsula.
   Leaders of the nation's four main political parties said they
would try to produce a united response by the end of next week.
   National Unification Minister Lee Hong-koo told a National
Assembly committee that the South Korean government would favor
opening the proposed talks as a means of promoting contact with
North Korea.
   Communist North Korea sent an invitation Thursday to the South
Korean National Assembly for talks with the Supreme People's
Assembly in Pyongyang on a non-aggression pact drawn up by the
North.
   In Washington, State Dept. spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley applauded
the idea.
   ``We believe this could be a very positive development and hope
the joint assembly meeting will take place,'' she said.
   South Korean government and opposition leaders said preliminary
negotiations would be needed to work out the terms and details
before any agreement could be reached on parliamentary talks.
   ``The political leaders have agreed to consider affirmatively
the North Korean proposal for parliamentary talks,'' said Lee
Dong-bok, chief secretary to the National Assembly speaker.
   Lee said the governing and opposition leaders reached the
agreement after a briefing by government officials.
   No agreement was reached on the agenda or method of the talks,
he said.
   Kim Dae-jung, president of the Party for Peace and Democracy,
said after the meeting, ``We will make efforts to seek an early
realization of inter-Korea parliamentary talks.''
   The North Korean proposal called for the legislatures of the two
Koreas to hold joint sessions alternately in their capitals to
discuss various tension-easing subjects, including non-aggression
and arms reduction.
   The rival Koreas have presented a series of what they called
``peace proposals'' in recent months, but none of them was accepted
by either side. On several occasions, the two sides even refused to
receive letters from the other side.
   Korea was divided by U.S. and Soviet forces that ended the
Japanese occupation at the end of World War II. Efforts to reunite
the peninsula failed and separate governments were declared in 1948.
   The North invaded South Korea in 1950 to start the three-year
Korean War. About 42,000 U.S. troops are based in South Korea under
a mutual defense treaty.
</TEXT>
