<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Clements     07-22 0205</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Clements,0211</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texas Governor Remains Hospitalized, Hopes To Go Home Saturday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Bill Clements, hospitalized after
suffering what doctors called a mild stroke, hoped to go home
Saturday, his staff said.
   Clements was in high spirits Friday and awaiting his doctors'
decision on whether he could be discharged, said Reggie Bashaur,
the governor's press secretary.
   Bashur said Clements on Friday discussed economic development
projects and possible appointments with George Bayoud, his chief of
staff.
   Clements talked for five minutes Thursday night with President
Reagan about the Democratic National Convention and the
presidential campaign, Bashur said.
   Seton Medical Center officials reported that Clements' condition
remained good and that medication was keeping his heartbeat regular.
   Dr. David Morris, a heart specialist, and Dr. Jerry Tindel, a
neurologist, said tests indicated that Clements was suffering from
a slight irregularity in his heartbeat, which could have caused a
tiny blood clot to form in his heart before passing through his
bloodstream and into his brain, causing the stroke Monday night.
   The governor, who admitted himself to the hospital Tuesday
evening, suffered some vision problems in his right eye, doctors
said. But they predicted that he could resume his normal schedule
in about a week.
</TEXT>
