<1ST_LINE>r a AM-StoogesConvention     07-22 0468</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Stooges Convention,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nyuk, Nyuk _ Stoogemania Reigns At Convention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES WEBB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Call 'em crazy, call 'em goofy, call 'em a
little bit childish _ and convention goers gathering this weekend
just might respond with a pie in your face or a poke in your eyes.
   ``Everybody sees a little bit of one or another of the Stooges
in them _ or they'd like to,'' says Frank Reighter, organizer of
the second annual Three Stooges Convention in suburban Trevose.
   Fans of the Stooges are gathering to buy and sell memorabilia,
reminisce with relatives and associates of the Stooges, and watch
some of the 190 shorts and dozens of feature movies the Stooges
made between 1930 and 1965 _ titles such as ``Dizzy Doctors'' and
``All the World's A Stooge.''
   A pie fight will break out at some time. A ``Shemp-a-thon'' is
also scheduled _ a showing of some obscure films starring ``Shemp''
Howard after he left the Stooges.
   ``In Louisiana, they showed a Shemp-a-thon and a lot of people
showed up thinking it was a shrimp-a-thon,'' said Gary Lassin,
president of the 2,500-member 3 Stooges Fan Club, the
Lansdale-based sponsor of the three-day convention. ``They have a
lot of knuckleheads down there.''
   Reighter said he expects 1,000 to 1,500 people from as far away
as the West Coast and Canada to join in the celebration of the
face-slapping, head-butting, prat-falling brand of slapstick and
high jinks that made the Stooges famous.
   The original Three Stooges, created as foils for vaudeville
comedian Ted Healy in the 1920s, were Morris ``Moe'' Horowitz, who
later changed his name to Howard; his brother Samuel, or ``Shemp'';
and Philadelphia native Larry Fineberg, a.k.a. Fine.
   In the early '30s Shemp left over a pay dispute and Moe's
brother Jerome, or ``Curly,'' joined the group, which split from
Healy and shuffled off on its own to the tune of ``Three Blind
Mice.''
   Curly later became ill and was himself replaced by Shemp, who
was succeeded by two other Stooges _ Joe Besser and Joe DeRita, the
only surviving member of the comedy team.
   Moe was the last original Stooge to die, in 1975.
   Curly will live on this weekend in the likeness of David Knight,
a Palmyra, N.Y., construction worker who moonlights as an
impersonator of the bald-headed, barking buffoon who was so often
the butt of Moe's jokes.
   ``I did a `nyuk, nyuk,' and a couple of `woo woos' and it just
took off from there,'' said Knight, who thinks the Stooges' comedy
has lived on because ``it transcends all generations.''
   The trio's films were once outlawed by some mothers who thought
the Stooges were too violent.
   ``Mom couldn't accept that that wasn't a real hammer Curly was
getting hit with,'' Reighter said, ``but kids could.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880722-0205 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-88 2116EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Unrest     07-22 0569</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Unrest,0588</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leaders in Disputed Region Warned About Continued Strikes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 100 officials fired unjustly in the
troubled region of Nagorno-Karabakh have been reinstated, but those
urging continued strikes may face criminal or disciplinary action,
the Tass news agency reported Friday.
   The reinstatements appeared to be the latest effort by officials
to end crippling strikes in the region and ease an ethnic dispute
that has raged since February.
   However, the nightly television news program Vremya described
the atmosphere in Nagorno-Karabakh as tense. Only two buses were in
service in the region's central city of Stepanakert, the television
report said.
   The region, which is part of the Soviet republic of Azerbaijan,
has been idled by strikes and demonstrations as Armenians, who
comprise more than two-thirds of the area's population, have
pressed their demands for annexation with neighboring Armenia.
   A decision by the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet, the nominal
parliament, on Monday declared annexation ``impossible,'' but the
labor unrest in Nagorno-Karabakh has continued.
   It was not clear how many Stepanakert residents were on strike,
but the state-run media reports suggested little if any improvement
in the labor situation there.
   Tass quoted a national prosecutor in warning government
ministers and industrial managers who fail to take all measures at
their disposal to end the strikes.
   ``More than 100 people who were earlier dismissed from their
factories for a variety of reasons determined by abnormal and
inter-ethnic relations have been reinstated,'' Tass reported.
   However, a criminal investigation of at least one enterprise
director is under way and others face disciplinary action, the news
agency said.
   The strikes have caused millions of dollars in damage to the
Azerbaijani economy and prevented deliveries of materials to
factories in other regions.
   Soviet media reported food shortages throughout Nagorno-Karabakh
and blamed the shortages on workers' refusal to handle deliveries
to the region. Government statistics released Thursday showed
Azerbaijan was the only Soviet republic that failed to meet its
industrial output quotas for the first half of 1988.
   Residents of Yerevan, the capital of the Armenian republic, had
been staging sympathy strikes and demonstrations prior to the
Presidium decision, but leaders there called off labor actions last
week.
   However, thousands of Armenians have been gathering nightly at
Yerevan's central square to protest the rejection of the annexation
drive.
   Vremya showed film from an interview with security troops in
Yerevan who described the situation there as ``complicated'' but
improving.
   A correspondent for Armenpress, Armenia's official news agency,
reported that only about 7 percent of Yerevan's industrial workers
failed to show up for work on Friday.
   The mostly Christian Armenian population of Nagorno-Karabakh has
complained during that they suffer discrimination under the
jurisdiction of Azerbaijan, which is predominantly Moslem.
   The leadership of the region of 160,000 residents voted earlier
in July to join Armenia, but that action was vetoed by the
Azerbaijani leadership.
   The Soviet Constitution professes to give citizens the right to
choose their government, but it also gives each of the 15
constituent republics the final say on any proposed border changes.
   The Presidium decision leaned on that constitutional provision
in ruling that Nagorno-Karabakh should remain part of Azerbaijan,
which has governed the region since 1923.
   Armenians began a campaign to annex Nagorno-Karabakh in
February. At least 32 people died in ethnic rioting that broke out
later that month in the Azerbaijani city of Sumgait.
