<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Weather     07-22 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Weather,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Flood Hits China's Northeast, 14,000 Houses Destroyed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Torrential rains destroyed 14,000 houses and
flooded 410,000 acres near one city in northeastern China, the
official Xinhua news agency agency said Saturday.
   It said rains have been falling non-stop for six days on Qiqihar
near Harbin, capital of Heilongjiang province. Xinhua said some
counties near Qiqihar have been getting 3.7 inches of rain a day
and the hardest-hit areas have received more than 5 inches of rain
a day.
   About 2,000 government officials were sent to organize relief
work, the report said.
   In Hong Kong, the Chinese-language newspaper Ta Kung Pao said a
typhoon which swept across southeastern China this week killed 20
people and injured 159.
   China's official media said Thursday that Typhoon Warren had
left 17 dead and 153 injured. It caused destruction estimated at
$270 million.
   Ta Kung Pao said in a report from Canton, capital of the nearby
Guangdong province, that more than 4 million people suffered losses
after the typhoon hit Guangdong Tuesday night with winds up to 80
mph. It said about 150,000 homes were damaged or destroyed, with
more than 13,000 toppled.
   Warren destroyed more than 925,000 acres of crops, 270 bridges,
480 miles of roads and more than 620 miles of telephone lines and
caused about 370 miles of dykes and levees to burst or break, Ta
Kung Pao reported.
   Among the hardest hit areas was the coastal city of Shantou.
Canton, about 190 miles to the southwest, received heavy rain but
was spared the full force of the typhoon.
   The Guangdong provincial Foreign Affairs Office said Friday it
had no information on the damage.
</TEXT>
