<1ST_LINE>u i AM-UN-Iran-Iraq 1stLd-Writethru a0751 07-22 0512</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Iran-Iraq, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0751,0525</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran May Accept Direct Talks, Iraq to Accept Truce Mission</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout to include more about Iraqi five points
and EDIT.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The secretary-general invited the foreign
ministers of Iran and Iraq to New York next week to discuss a
cease-fire, and Iran indicated Friday it may agree to the direct
peace talks sought by the Iraqis.
   Iraq agreed to accept a technical team Secretary-General Javier
Perez de Cuellar directed to visit Tehran and Baghdad to work out
details of a cease-fire in the 8-year-old war, U.N. officials said.
   ``What we have said to the secretary-general is very clear: That
whatever he deems necessary we can go along with,'' Ambassador
Mohammad Ja'afar Mahallati of Iran said at a news conference in
answer to repeated questions about negotiating directly Iraq.
   ``Iranian President (Ali) Khamenei said Iran is ready to go
along without any limitations whatsoever on implementation of
Resolution 598 on request, if the secretary-general requires.''
   He did not answer the question directly, but said the
secretary-general had not requested direct talks. Perez de Cuellar
said earlier this week he would prefer such negotiations, but did
not respond to Mahallati's statement.
   The secretary-general invited the foreign ministers, Ali-Akbar
Velayati of Iran and Tariq Aziz of Iraq, to visit U.N. headquarters
early next week for talks with him about implementing Security
Council Resolution 598, which calls for an immediate cease-fire in
the Iran-Iraq war.
   Velayati accepted and will arrive Monday for a one-week stay,
Mahallati said. U.N. officials said Aziz also had accepted.
   Iraq says direct negotiations with Iran are necessary to work
out details of a peace agreement. Iran previously rejected direct
talks.
   The cease-fire technical team of nine military officers and a
civilian is due in Tehran on Sunday.
   Francois Giuliani, the secretary-general's spokesman, said
Friday that Iraq had given approval for the team to visit Baghdad
in the next few days.
   Iran promptly welcomed the team, but Iraq at first withheld its
approval.
   On Wednesday, Iraq gave the secretary-general a five-point plan
calling for direct talks, Iranian guarantees not to attack either
Iraq or neutral shipping, and dredging by the United Nations of the
disputed Shatt-al-Arab waterway.
   The waterway forms the southern border between the two countries
and is Iraq's only outlet to the sea.
   Also Friday, Iran formally protested to the United Nations about
Baghdad's latest offensive of the nearly 8-year-old war, and
claimed the Iraqis used chemical weapons.
   Mahallati told reporters: ``We are sending letters in protest of
continued Iraqi aggression against Iran in violation of appeals by
the secretary-general ... and also about extensive use of chemical
weapons by Iraq.''
   He said 60 people were killed and 800 wounded in the alleged
Iraqi chemical attack Friday.
   Iraq did not respond to the charge. It has acknowledged previous
use of chemical weapons but claims Iran introduced them to the war.
   The Iraqi advance occurred in a disputed area of the central
frontier region about 125 miles northeast of Baghdad.
</TEXT>
