<HEAD>Two More Fires Put Out on Stricken Oil Rig</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ABERDEEN, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers led by Texas troubleshooter
Red Adair put out two of the remaining fires on a North Sea
platform ravaged by the world's worst oil rig disaster, the
platform's operator and main owner said Friday.
   A huge explosion followed by a fierce fire wrecked the Piper
Alpha oil platform 120 miles off Scotland on July 6, killing 167
men.
   The Los Angeles-based Occidental Petroleum Corp. said workers
doused fires in two wells with sea water and capped them with
cement.
   John Brading, chairman of Occidental's British operations, said
that good weather over the past 24 hours had helped Adair's team.
However, he said the platform would remain very dangerous until all
of the wellhead fires had been extinguished.
   One fire was still burning, and another wellhead remained to be
capped.
 
