<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel     07-22 0700</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel,0727</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Troops Block Worshipers, Police Ready For Tough Weekend</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Troops blocked Moslem worshipers from reaching
Jerusalem on Friday and riot police reinforcements were sent to the
Holy City in anticipation of a troubled weekend.
   Israeli officials said Jerusalem was becoming the center of a
7{-month-old Palestinian rebellion in the occupied territories in
which 231 Palestinians and four Israelis have died.
   They said greater tension was expected this weekend because of
coinciding Arab and Jewish holidays that focus on the sacred and
disputed Temple Mount.
   More than 100 club-wielding riot police stood guard Friday in
the walled Old City, where about 3,500 Moslems gathered for prayer.
   Moslem leaders said 17,000 worshipers had been expected on the
Friday before the four-day Moslem holiday Eid al-Adha. Many were
turned back at Israeli roadblocks, however and curfews kept home
about 270,000 Palestinians.
   Dozens of Orthodox Jews in black coats watched from rooftops
around the Temple Mount as a Moslem prayer leader told his flock
Jews ``think only with their power and their weapons.''
   ``The last day is approaching. ... Victory will come soon!
Listen, you occupiers who are preventing Moslems from the West Bank
and Gaza from praying in the mosques!,'' he shouted through mosque
loudspeakers.
   Israel seized the West Bank from Jordan and the Gaza Strip from
Egypt in the 1967 Middle East war.
   About 30 police vehicles lined up opposite the sacred Western
Wall, or Wailing Wall _ the last remnant of the Jewish Temple
destroyed by the Romans 2,000 years ago. Sharpshooters took
positions on surrounding roofs.
   District police chief Rachamim Comfort told reporters an Israeli
Arab couple was detained at the Temple Mount entrance when they
tried to bring in a box packed with eight firebombs.
   Comfort said hundreds of extra police were stationed in the
city. At sundown Saturday, Jews start to observe the Tisha B'Av
fast day _ marking the destruction of the temple _ and on Sunday,
Moslems begin celebrating Eid al-Adha _ the story of Abraham's
aborted sacrifice of his son on the Mount.
   Police did not intervene Friday when about 50 Palestinian youths
raised the outlawed Palestinian flag on the Temple Mount and held a
brief march, shouting: ``Kill the Jews!'' and ``Jews, Jews, get out
of Palestine!''
   Worshipers beat up a young Palestinian woman who went onto the
Temple Mount with a tape recorder. She said they mistook her for a
police informer.
   ``There's no doubt that everything that touches upon this open
nerve ending called religion has a high explosive potential,''
Ephraim Sneh, former head of Israel's military administration in
the occupied lands, told Israel radio.
   ``The center (of the conflict) is now in Jerusalem.''
   City Manager Aharon Sarig said recent violence in the city
``proves that Jerusalem is actually the focus of all things.''
   Arab-Americans complained on Friday of being singled out for
harassment by Israeli authorities.
   Philip Wilcox, the U.S. consul general in Jerusalem, diplomat
urged them to stand up for their rights and file complaints with
U.S. consular officials.
   He spoke to about 200 Arab Americans at a gathering called by
the American Arab Anti-Discrimination Committee, a Washington-based
lobbying group which plans to open a Jerusalem chapter.
   Israeli officials denied the allegations.
   Participants at the meeting said their money was confiscated at
the border and they were frequently subjected to demeaning searches.
   ``Palestinians are treated like criminals,'' said Hammad Siyam,
49, of West New York, N.J., waving his American passport.
   Siyam was born in the West Bank village of Mukhmas.
   ``How come an American Jew from Brooklyn who has never been here
before has the right to stay in the West Bank forever, and I have
to go back after three months?'' said Ahmad Baker, a West Bank-born
physician now living in Norfolk, Va.
   Avi Pazner, a spokesman for the prime minister, said Jews were a
special case, allowed to stay in Israel under the 40-year-old Law
of Return.
   San Francisco-born Leila Ahmed Abu Hilal, 24, who married a
Palestinian from east Jerusalem three years ago, said she leaves
Israel once every three months, when her tourist visa expires,
because Israeli officials have not given her a residency permit.
  
</TEXT>
