<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NavajoTrial     07-22 0512</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Navajo Trial,0527</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officer's Brother Testifies Defendant Threatened Officer Before
Slaying</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge on Friday dismissed
charges against one of four Navajo men on trial in the killing of
two tribal police officers after a desert drinking party last
December.
   The charge against Marques Atene, 22, was thrown out by U.S.
District Judge J. Thomas Greene at the request of the prosecutor,
Assistant U.S. Attorney Stewart Walz, after the prosecution rested
its case.
   Atene had been charged with first-degree murder along with his
half brother, Ben Atene Jr., 24, and two others men, Thomas Cly,
22, and Vinton Bedoni, 31, in the deaths Officers Roy Lee Stanley
and Andy Begay.
   The trial against the others was scheduled to continue Saturday.
They are being tried in federal court because the deaths occurred
on an Indian reservation.
   ``I'm glad to be out of this situation,'' Atene said after the
dismissal. ``I'm happy about it.'' But he said he had no plans to
return to the Navajo Reservation, adding, ``I'm scared right now of
Navajo police. I don't trust them.''
   Prosecutors contend Stanley and Begay were shot at a Dec. 4
bonfire celebration, bundled into the back of a police truck,
driven to a canyon, doused with flammable liquid and set on fire.
The medical eximaner concluded that they were still alive when the
fire was set. The remains were found Dec. 5 in Copper Canyon
southeast of Lake Powell.
   Marques Atene's attorney, Walter Bugden Jr., said Walz asked for
the dismissal because a ``reasonable jury'' could not convict his
client.
   ``That's terrible that the charges were brought against Marques
in the first place, and the government did the right thing by
dismissing the charges,'' he said. Walz said he moved for dismissal
because he couldn't prove guilt beyond a reasonable doubt. He would
not comment further.
   Testimony in the trial, which began Monday, focused largely on
Atene's co-defendants, and Bugden said the witnesses had testified
only that Atene was at the bonfire and that he was seen picking up
beer cans.
   ``That's not a crime,'' he said.
   Last week, Greene had denied defense motions to dismiss charges
against all four defendants. The defense contends that 13 witnesses
were coerced by FBI agents and tribal investigators who threatened
them with jail and expulsion from the reservation, but Greene
rejected that argument.
   Before the prosecution wound up its testimony Friday, the
brother of one of the slain officers said that Cly threatened his
brother a month before he died.
   Larry Stanley testified that he was with his brother Roy when
the officer arrested Cly for possession of liquor within the Navajo
Reservation, where possession of alcohol is illegal.
   Stanley quoted Cly as saying to the officer: ``Your badge means
nothing. You're going to die later.''
   Under cross-examination by Cly's attorney, Stanley said his
brother had been threatened numerous times by other people he'd
arrested. Stanley also acknowledged that he had told FBI
investigators that the threat was made in August, but later amended
the date to about Nov. 3.
</TEXT>
