<1ST_LINE>r i AM-ReaganDocumentary     07-22 0648</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan Documentary,0666</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Depicted as `Good King' in British Documentary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ronald Reagan wanted to make Americans believe in
their country again during his eight years as president, and in a
British television documentary, even his critics find it hard to
pin anything bad on what one called the ``good king.''
   Still, history may take a dim view of some legacies of the
Reagan years, such as billions of dollars in national debt, critics
said in the last of a three-part series on Reagan and his
presidency.
   The commercial television series, ``Reagan on Reagan,'' ended
Friday on Channel 4.
   Interviewed for the program, the 77-year-old president talked of
the Iran arms scandal and said he approved weapons sales to the
Iranians because he just ``couldn't sit by'' while U.S. hostages
were held.
   Commenting on what was probably the deepest crisis of his
presidency, Reagan defended the weapons sales, saying he had
believed the Iranians would help gain release of hostages held by
Iranian-linked Islamic groups in Lebanon.
   ``You can't sit by when you know that you've got citizens of
your country who are held in savage captivity by barbarians of that
type,'' he said.
   Reagan also told Channel 4, ``I'd always believed that there was
a kind of a hunger for a spiritual revival ... in our country. Not
only a revival in those things of morality and family and so forth,
but in our nation as a whole, and we set out to do that.
   ``I hear from a great many people who say that they now have a
restored belief in our country.''
   Whether weighing highs like the superpower arms treaty or lows
like the Iran arms scandal, both critics and supporters seemed
confounded by the secret of Reagan's popularity as they spoke of
him for the program.
   Rep. Tom Foley, D-Wash., majority leader of the House of
Representatives, said Reagan ``will be remembered perhaps as a good
king, but a bad prime minister.''
   ``He is a generous man, and he is a good man,'' said Sen. Daniel
Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., ``It's just that some very bad things
happened during his presidency, (and) part of the ominous quality
was that it was difficult to see how ominous those things were.''
   Former Treasury Secretary Donald Regan said, ``You don't know
how he does it, but he does it ... and in the last analysis when
the game is over, they don't ask you how you won the game, but
whether you won the game or not.''
   Historian Garry Wills suggested the ``astonishing protection''
of Reagan stems from his ability to make Americans believe in their
country again, as he promised he would.
   Wills, author of ``Reagan's America,'' said the president's
success is a ``a matter of the emotional investment American people
have made in him. If he is not what we thought he is all along,
then we look like fools.''
   With December's signing of a superpower arms treaty to eliminate
medium-range nuclear missiles, Reagan ``changed the agenda of arms
control from limiting the rate of increase to making very big
reductions,'' said Secretary of State George P. Shultz.
   Still, critics said the nation suffered under Reagan in some
ways, including in its economy.
   ``The bottom 60 percent of the population have been getting a
smaller share of total income ... and the top 20 percent of the
population are getting an increasing share of total income,'' said
Lester Thurow, dean of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology's
Sloan School of Management.
   Investment banker Peter Petersen said in speaking of the U.S.
debt, ``I think history will say we've made some of the worst ...
choices in the history of our country.''
   He argued that foreign policy will suffer because ``the attempt
to stand tall while you're on bended knees will be a rather
difficult posture to sustain.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
