<1ST_LINE>u i AM-CostaRica-Contras     07-22 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Costa Rica-Contras,0508</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Say Bermudez To Step Down As Contra Military Commander</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUAN MALTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Col. Enrique Bermudez will step down
as military commander of Nicaraguan rebel forces to defuse the
controversy caused by his appointment to the Contras' directorate,
a fellow leader said Friday.
   Alfredo Cesar, one of the seven Contra directors, also said he
is asking President Oscar Arias of Costa Rica to try to arrange a
new round of peace talks between the U.S.-backed rebels and
Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government.
   Cesar is the chief Contra negotiator in the talks.
   He told a news conference the new Nicaraguan Resistance
directorate ``will delegate areas of responsibility and, in this
sense, Col. Enrique Bermudez will step down next week from the
general command of the National Liberation Army.
   ``In this manner, Col. Bermudez, who now forms part of the
directorate, will only be the military supervisor of our military
forces, but without any command.''
   Bermudez was a colonel in the National Guard of the rightist,
pro-American Somoza dynasty that ruled Nicaragua for 42 years until
it was overthrown by the Sandinistas in July 1979. He long has been
a source of friction within the Contra coalition known as the
Nicaraguan Resistance.
   The controversy heated up after Bermudez was elected to the
directorate, the political leadership, at a meeting Monday in the
Dominican Republic.
   Seven commanders of the small Contra organization called the
Southern Front, which fights in southern Nicaragua, resigned in
protest.
   Cesar publicly appealed to the seven to withdraw their
resignations, saying they had been badly informed about the changes.
   ``The resignation of these commanders and the threats by other
groups such as the Social Christians and members of the Central
Front to withdraw is precipitous, but we must also recognize they
feel frustrated because they do not receive (American) aid,'' Cesar
said.
   Cesar said the Southern Front received no U.S. humanitarian aid
because the Costa Rican government did not approve its delivery
through Costa Rica.
   The Southern Front has a political base in Costa Rica. The
Northern Front led by Bermudez is based in Honduras, which raised
no objections to deliveries there.
   The U.S. Congress has not approved any military aid to the
Contras since February.
   Cesar said the Contras asked Arias two months ago for permission
to deliver humanitarian aid still in the pipeline through the Costa
Rican Red Cross, but have received no reply.
   The Sandinistas said Bermudez's election was engineered by the
U.S. Central Intelligence Agency and would make ``the possibility
of negotiating peace even more remote.''
   The Sandinistas and the rebels have been trying to negotiate an
end to their seven-year war since March, prompted in large part by
the regional peace plan that won Arias last year's Nobel Peace
Prize.
   A temporary truce has been in effect, with repeated extensions,
since March 21. No new talks were scheduled after last round ended
in deadlock June 9.
</TEXT>
