<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines-Rebels     07-22 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines-Rebels,0476</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Filipino Groups Urge Peace Talks With Rebels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two human rights groups asked
President Corazon Aquino on Friday to renew peace talks with
communist rebels, and lawyers who defend people charged with
rebellion demanded protection from reprisals.
   Friday's appeals were issued by the Philippine Alliance of Human
Rights Advocates and the Ecumenical Movement for Justice and Peace.
They followed a call by Roman Catholic bishops last week for
resumption of talks that collapsed in January 1987.
   Mrs. Aquino did not respond to the appeals. She has expressed
willingness to talk if the rebels make a formal request. The
insurgents say the government will use negotiations to trap top
leaders of the 19-year insurgency.
   Her government and the rebel National Democratic Front
negotiated after a 60-day cease-fire that began in December 1986,
but the government refused to accept rebel demands for inclusion in
the government and fighting resumed in February 1987.
   The National Democratic Front is the umbrella for a dozen
Marxist organizations, including the Communist Party of the
Philippines and its military wing, the New People's Army.
   About 50 civil rights lawyers marched to the presidential palace
Friday to ask Mrs. Aquino to protect them from reprisals for
defending clients charged as communist rebels.
   The march followed a two-day conference during which lawyers
from the United States, Philippines and four other countries
discussed the slayings of at least five Filipino human rights
lawyers in the last eight months and reported harassment of many
others.
   Conference participants released texts of letters from the
American Bar Association to Mrs. Aquino and U.S. Secretary of State
George Shultz expressing concern about recent killings of human
rights lawyers here.
   In the letter to Mrs. Aquino, the ABA cited the June 24 murder
of lawyer Alfonso Surigao Jr., who protested the treatment of
leftists detained by the military, and the killing July 2 of
Emmanuel Mendoza, another civil rights attorney.
   Neither case has been solved, but a Philippine Constabulary
colonel was relieved of his duties after being linked to the
Surigao murder.
   The lawyers group met with Defense Secretary Fidel Ramos, who
assured them human rights violators will be prosecuted, said Norman
Dorsen of the Lawyers Committee for Human Rights in New York.
   A resolution adopted at the meeting asked that the government
investigate the killings and take steps to protect lawyers from
harassment by security forces.
   On Thursday, the Free Legal Assistance Group released a report
saying more human rights lawyers have been killed or harassed
during the first two years of Mrs. Aquino's administration than
during the last nine years of deposed President Ferdinand Marcos'
20-year rule.
   It said five lawyers have been killed since Mrs. Aquino came to
power in February 1986 and four were slain from 1977 to 1986.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
