<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Thailand-Election     07-22 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Thailand-Election,0214</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prem Seen Likely To Remain as Prime Minister</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sunday's general election is expected
to produce a governing coalition that will ask Prime Minister Prem
Tinsulanonda to continue in office and pursue the conservative
policies he has followed since 1980.
   Prem's current coalition became riddled with factionalism and he
called elections two years early.
   A total of 3,612 candidates from 16 parties are contesting 357
seats in the House of Representatives and no party is expected to
gain a majority.
   Thai elections generally center on personalities, not issues,
and the main question has been whether Prem should continue as
prime minister.
   Prem has not said if he will accept another term but analysts
consider him the most probable choice. They say the 67-year-old
former army commander, who has no party affiliation, is in the best
position to forge the compromises needed for a governing alliance.
   Most coalition leaders favor keeping him in office and he has
the support of three other elements involved in the decision: the
military, bureaucracy, and King Bhumibol Adulyadej.
   Whoever is selected as prime minister, no change is expected in
Thailand's pro-Western conservative policies.
   Parties in the current coalition are the Democrats, Thai Nation,
Social Action and Citizens.
</TEXT>
