<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-88 2154EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Bolivia-Cocaine     07-22 0566</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bolivia-Cocaine,0583</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Convicted Cocaine Kingpin Has No Worries</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER MCFARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A convicted cocaine trafficker, presented
at a news conference Friday, said, ``When one is with God, one has
nothing to worry about.''
   Roberto Suarez Gomez, considered to be one of South America's
narcotics kingpins, was arrested Wednesday at his ranch near the
city of Trinidad.
   Reporters were allowed to see him where he is being held at the
narcotics control office in a La Paz subburb but they were not
permitted to question him and his comments were limited.
   Suarez Gomez, 57, said he was feeling well and then Information
Minister Herman Antelo stopped him from making further comments and
said Suarez Gomez would be free to talk to the news media after he
is transfered next week to the San Pedron prison in La Paz.
   Suarez Gomez faces a 15-year prison sentence after being
convicted earlier this year of drug trafficking charges in
Trinidad, 320 miles northeast of La Paz. He was tried in absentia
and has not appealed the sentence, according to Interior Minister
Juan Carlos Duran.
   ``The government's top priority is combatting the cocaine trade
which is a threat to our democratic system,'' Duran told the news
conference.
   Ten anti-drug policemen captured Suarez Gomez as he was sleeping
at his ranch 25 miles north of Trinidad. The police confiscated 20
automatic weapons and also arrested two men they said were Suarez
Gomez' bodyguards.
   The United States seeks the extradition of Suarez Gomez. Foreign
Minister Guillermo Bedregal said that could not happen because the
two countries do not have an extradition treaty dealing with drug
trafficking and there is a prison sentence pending against Suarez
Gomez here. Bedregal noted that negotiations are under way between
the United States and Bolivia on an expanded extradition pact.
   Suarez Gomez was indicted in Florida in 1980 on a charge of
conspiring to transfer 854 pounds pounds of cocaine to the United
States.
   Jack Hook, a U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration spokesman in
Miami, claimed Suarez Gomez was involved in dealing in tons of
illegal drug shipments.
   ``He's really the same as the upper levels of the Medellin
cartel,'' said Hook. ``He could be considered one of the pioneers
involved in manufacturing and trafficking cocaine to the United
States.''
   The Medellin cartel, named so because it is centered in the
Colombian city of Medellin, is considered the major cocaine
trafficking organization in Latin America.
   Police intensified the search for Suarez Gomez after he recently
said in an interview on Channel 4 television that ``the American
government is the king of cocaine and the viceroy is the Bolivian
government.''
   He claimed politicians and law enforcement officials received
bribes from drug traffickers. In the ensuing political furor the
government suspended Channel 4's operating license for six months.
   President Victor Paz Estenssoro signed a law Wednesday that
makes most coca growing illegal. Coca leaves, the raw material for
cocaine, are traditiontlly chewed by Bolivian peasants and the law
is expected to include at least 80 percent of the production.
   About 350,000 people in Bolivian's population of 6.2 million
depend on coca leaf farming and cocaine production for their
livelihood, according to Duran.
   It is estimated that the illegal drug trade for Bolivia, South
America's most impoverished country, amounts to about $300 million
per year compared to $500 million for all legal exports.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
