<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NoSpeaking 1stLd-Writethru a0719 07-22 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-No Speaking, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0719,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Council Bans Public Speech at Meetings</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts time element in 2nd graf</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SUGARCREEK, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Sugarcreek Borough Council has
decided that residents were being too free with their speech, and
has decided that constituents should be seen and not heard at
meetings.
   The five council members voted unanimously Wednesday night to
ban public comment during meetings because Council President Tom
Sloss said earlier speaking policies were being abused.
   Borough Solicitor Max Gabreski said twice-monthly council
meetings in this Venango County town of about 5,900 continue to be
open to the public under the state's Open Public Meetings Law.
   ``The right to attend is not the right to participate,'' he said.
   ``Each councilman is available to constituents in their district
by phone or in person,'' the new policy states. Citizens with
questions are invited to contact Borough Administrator Karen Noel
for an answer or to set up an appointment to view public records.
   The council previously had required the public to notify the
borough secretary five days in advance if they wished to speak.
   ``In many situations, people were interrupting,'' Sloss said.
``They were making threats to council ... and for us to try to
conduct business under those circumstances, when people were
constantly at us ... it was just no way to conduct a meeting.''
   ``It does not bar anyone talking to any councilman. It does not
prohibit them from seeing anything they want,'' Ms. Noel said. ``If
residents are not pleased with it, they can not vote for these
particular men at the next election. They have that choice as
well.''
</TEXT>
