<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Mica-Cuba 1stLd-Writethru a0725 07-22 0507</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mica-Cuba, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0725,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mica Shocked That Cubans Revoked Visa</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 4 grafs after 4th graf, In his, with dispatch from
Cuba and to edit for conformity; picks up 6th graf, `It is'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Dan Mica has written a letter to
President Fidel Castro expressing ``shock'' and ``astonishment''
over the Cuban government's decision to revoke visas which he and
several aides had been given for travel to Cuba.
   The Florida Democrat had planned to visit Cuba to inspect U.S.
diplomatic facilities as part of his duties as chairman of a House
Foreign Affairs subcommittee.
   But Cuba revoked the visas Tuesday evening shortly before Mica
and his companions were scheduled to fly to the island, citing the
presence of Cuban human rights advocates at a reception given by a
U.S. diplomatic official a week ago.
   In his letter to Castro, dated Thursday and released on Friday,
Mica said, ``I am shocked that you should choose to interfere with
a legitimate congressional visit to conduct internal U.S. business
and review the operations of our mission in your country.''
   A dispatch from Cuba's Prensa Latina news agency quoted a Cuban
Foreign Ministry statement as saying the reception ``was organized
to make it possible for American diplomats to instruct their
counterrevolutionary servants and was not a normal diplomatic
activity''
   The foreign ministry went on to say that the meeting was
interference in the internal affairs of Cuba and ``a gross
provocation that steps completely away from the functions foressen
for the U.S. Special Interests Section in our country, for which it
has enjoyed and enjoys all the facilities offered by our
government.''
   The dispatch was monitored in Mexico City.
   Mica said in his letter that he and his staff have visited a
number of overseas posts, including in the Soviet Union, and never
encountered any hindrance from the host government.
   ``It is ironic that the congressional group you capriciously
kept out of Cuba has traveled freely to the capitals of your allies
behind the Iron Curtain,'' Mica wrote.
   Mica added that Cuba's explanation for revoking the visas was
``astonishing'' because the action occurred just weeks before a
scheduled visit of a delegation from the United Nations Human
Rights Commission to Cuba.
   ``If the mere fact that members of the Cuban Committee on Human
Rights attended a party results in punitive action against the
United States, one can hardly imagine that the Cuban people would
feel free to meet and provide information to representatives of the
U.N. Human Rights Commission,'' he said.
   Mica called on Castro to make it clear to the people of Cuba
that they are free to speak openly to the commission members.
   Otherwise, he said, ``I can only interpret the events of the
past few days as a brazen attempt to intimidate those in your
country who might try to meet with the U.N. group,'' Mica said.
   The State Department also has criticized the Cuban action and
lodged an official protest with Cuban authorities on Thursday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
