<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     07-22 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heavy Rain Falls On Eastern North Carolina</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms dumped heavy rain over parts of the South on
Friday, soaking parched crops and causing some flooding, and rain
also fell on parts of the drought-stricken Midwest.
   Eastern North Carolina got heavy rain from a cluster of nearly
stationary thunderstorms that were part of a large area of slowly
moving showers and thunderstorms that formed ahead of a cold front
along the Atlantic Coast states.
   Wilmington, N.C., got a record 6.49 inches of rain for the date,
well over the former record of 3.88 inches set in 1877.
   The water flooded street drains in downtown Wilmington, stalling
cars and tying up traffic.
   Rain also was heavy over other areas of eastern North Carolina,
where New Bern got 1.60 inches and 1.31 inches fell on Jacksonville.
   But rainfall in North Carolina's southern and central Piedmont
is running about 8 inches below normal for the year, while the
mountains would need 14 inches in a short period to eliminate the
drought, experts said.
   In southern Mississippi, Columbia got 1.5 inches of rain and
half-inch diameter hail.
   Mobile, Ala., got more than an inch of rain within 25 minutes
and Huntsville got over half an inch within one hour.
   In northeastern Florida, more than 2{ inches of rain was
reported within one hour south of Lake City.
   In the Midwest, widely scattered thunderstorms carried briefly
heavy rain over northern Indiana, western Ohio and Lower Michigan,
where some Kalamazoo streets were reported flooded, the National
Weather Service said.
   Elsewhere, showers and thunderstorms were scattered over
southern Texas, southeastern Louisiana, southern Georgia, eastern
sections of the Atlantic Coast states and sections of Kentucky.
   Widely scattered thunderstorms developed over the mountain and
desert regions of southern California and southern Nevada and
isolated rainshowers were over central Oklahoma.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 58
degrees at Arcata, Calif., to 109 at Gila Bend, Ariz. The low
Friday morning was 34 degrees at Gunnison, Colo.
   For Saturday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
over the Atlantic Coast states, the eastern Gulf Coast region,
Alabama and Florida. Numerous showers were forecast over
southeastern Maine. Scattered showers and thunderstorms also were
forecast over the mountains and desert regions of southern
California.
   High in the 70s were predicted over New England, the northern
and central Appalachians and eastern Ohio; in the 70s and low 80s
over northwestern Washington state and along the California coast;
in the 80s over the Great Lakes states, the Ohio and Tennessee
valleys, the middle Mississippi Valley, the southern Appalachians,
the southern and central Atlantic Coast states except Florida, and
Alabama; between 100 and 110 over the desert Southwest and sections
of the Great Basin; and in the 90s over the remainder of the nation.
</TEXT>
