<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PolygamistIndictments     07-22 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Polygamist Indictments,0491</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Members of Polygamist Sect Indicted, Accused Of Running Truck
Theft Ring</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM F. RAWSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least four alleged members of a violent
polygamist sect have been indicted on charges of running a truck
theft ring that shipped stolen pickups to Mexico, authorities said
Friday.
   Named in the indictment were Douglas Barlow, 28; Richard
LeBaron, 18; Tarsa LeBaron, 22; and Cynthia LeBaron, who gave
authorities various birth dates, said Sylvia Lopez, spokeswoman for
the Mariposa County attorney's office.
   ``The defendants are alleged to have conspired in the theft of
1986 and '87 Ford and Chevrolet pickup trucks,'' the spokeswoman
said.
   She said she could not elaborate on the alleged crimes since the
indictment remained sealed Friday ``because there are other
defendants.'' The indictment was handed up Tuesday.
   The four defendants whose names were made public Friday are each
charged with one count of conspiracy to control an illegal
enterprise, one count of controlling an illegal enterprise and 20
counts of felony theft, Ms. Lopez said. They are being held on
$274,000 bond pending arraignments, set for July 29, she said.
   They and a fifth person, Heber LeBaron, 27, were arrested July 1
at a Phoenix motel after police ran a routine check on a truck
parked there and learned that it had been stolen in Texas. Heber
also is being held on bond.
   All five are described as children or followers of late Ervil
LeBaron, founder of the Church of the Lamb of God. The sect has
been linked to 18 deaths and disappearances of former members or
critics over the past 22 years. The elder LeBaron died in a Utah
prison in 1981 while serving time in one of the killings.
   Among the deaths linked to the sect are the execution-style
killings of three former sect members, and the 8-year-old daughter
of one of those victims, in Texas on June 27. But no charges have
been filed against any sect members in those deaths.
   Texas authorities are attempting to extradite Heber LeBaron and
Barlow. LeBaron is wanted on a November 1986 aggravated-robbery
charge in Richardson, Texas, and Barlow is wanted in a vehicle
burglary in Houston.
   Earlier this week, police in Mesa, a Phoenix suburb, said that
the five sect members arrested July 1 may have been involved in a
major theft ring that stole dozens of pickup trucks and
four-wheel-drive vehicles.
   Fifty such vehicles have been stolen in Mesa alone since
January, police said, and there have been similar thefts in Phoenix
and Tempe. It is believed the missing trucks were transported to
Mexico, police said.
   Sgt. Mike Hayes, a Mesa police spokesman, said Wednesday that
officers found a notebook containing lists of locations where
vehicles were stolen, along with a drill and lock-picking tools, in
the Phoenix motel rooms where the five had been staying.
</TEXT>
