<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Drought-Indiana     07-22 0259</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Indiana,0265</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Agriculture Secretary Declares All Of Indiana Drought Disaster
Areas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRAN RICHARDSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All 92 Indiana counties were declared
drought disaster areas Friday by U.S. Agriculture Secretary Richard
Lyng, Lt. Gov. John M. Mutz announced.
   The designation means qualified Indiana farmers will be able to
receive low-interest Farmer's Home Administration emergency loans.
The loans can be for up to 80 percent of the farmer's loss at an
interest rate of 4{ percent. The loans must be paid back in five to
seven years, Mutz said.
   In spite of rain this week, Purdue University specialists
caution that nearly 90 percent of the state's corn crop remains
rated poor or very poor. ``We're not out of the woods yet,'' said
agronomist Cliff Spies.
   Nevertheless, agriculture experts staffing the university's
drought hotline say the number of calls dropped dramatically, and
the spirits of the callers seemed improved.
   U.S. Rep James Jontz, D-Ind., a member of the House Agriculture
Committee, said earlier Friday that fewer than 10 percent of
Indiana's farmers will benefit from the disaster declaration unless
the government waives a crop insurance requirement attached to the
loans.
   Provisions to waive that rule for a year have been added to the
House version of the measure, Jontz said during a Statehouse news
conference.
   Mutz said the disaster declaration and related loans would be
valuable tools for some farmers. However, he said, ``The real fact
is that ... the thing farmers need more than this is not more loans
but better cash flow,'' Mutz said.
</TEXT>
