<1ST_LINE>r i AM-ShipAttack-Denmark     07-22 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ship Attack-Denmark,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Terrorist Ship Attack Was Clash Between Groups, Newspaper Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The attack aboard a Greek cruise ship
July 11 was in fact a clash between Abu Nidal terrorists and the
Israeli secret service set off by anger over an aborted hijacking
of the vessel, a newspaper said.
   The attack aboard the City of Poros killed nine people and
wounded 98.
   The Copenhagen B.T. paper reported in its Saturday edition that
two groups, an Abu Nidal terrorist group and Mossad, Israel's
secret service, opened fire on each other after Mossad stopped the
terrorists from hijacking the ship.
   Quoting Danish intelligence officers and unidentified diplomatic
sources, B.T. said the Abu Nidal group started shooting after
watching a television news report saying a car bomb detonated
outside the Greek port city of Piraeus.
   Greek police said the car bomb went off prematurely six hours
before the ship was due to dock, killing two people in the car.
   The newspaper report said the terrorists reportedly planned to
bring explosives from the car aboard the cruise ship when it
arrived in Piraeus with 471 passengers, to be used in a hijacking.
   Instead, the explosives were detonated by Mossad to avert the
hijacking, the B.T. version ran. Two of those killed in the attack
on the City of Poros are believed to be Abu Nidal terrorists, the
report said.
   It said Danish intelligence is working on the case because
Libyan passport holder Hejab Jaballa, identified by the Greek
government as the likely leader of the terrorist attack, arrived in
Greece on a flight from Copenhagen June 1.
   Jaballa has previously been identified as involved in the
assassination of an Egyptian newspaper editor, for which renegade
Palestinian terrorist Abu Nidal _ real name Sabry al-Banna _
claimed responsibility.
</TEXT>
