<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0681,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush: Dukakis Was `Very Good,' But What Was That Veep Point?
^EDs: To update SUBS last graf bgng ``The vice president ... ''
with 7 grafs on New Jersey campaign stop.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush praised Michael Dukakis's
acceptance speech as ``very good'' Friday, but said he was puzzled
by the Democratic nominee's pointed insistence that a vice
president shouldn't hesitate to tell the boss when things are awry.
   ``I don't know what that was all about, but I'm sure it wasn't
complimentary,'' Bush deadpanned to reporters.
   In his speech accepting the Democratic presidential nomination
in Atlanta Thursday night, Dukakis drew thunderous cheers when he
declared: ``We're going to have a vice president who won't sit
silently by when somebody at the National Security Council comes up
with the cockamamie idea that we should trade arms to the ayatollah
for hostages.
   ``We're going to have a vice president named Lloyd Bentsen who
will walk into the Oval Office and say, ``Mr. President, this is
outrageous and it's got to stop. That's the kind of vice president
we're going to have,'' Dukakis said.
   Bush, the certain Republican nominee, suggested that Dukakis
could benefit much from the advice of Bentsen, the senior senator
from Texas.
   ``If he's suggesting that Bentsen can change his views on gun
control, that's good. That would be an effective use for Lloyd
Bentsen,'' Bush said.
   The vice president sought to portray Dukakis as far more liberal
on most issues than Bentsen.
   Ask if he wanted to suggest that the Democratic party was
running against itself, Bush said: ``It'll be running against
itself by the time we get through.''
   The vice president spoke with reporters as he campaigned at a
lakefront Italian festival here.
   Asked his impression of Dukakis' speech, Bush said ``I thought
he gave a very good speech. He did a very good job.''
   Asked why he arrived at that assessment, Bush, balancing a plate
of scrambled eggs and sausage as he moved through the crowd,
quipped ``because he didn't say anything nasty about me.''
   Bush, as he has done in the past, defended his own access to
President Reagan. Democrats have long accused him of being silent
or contradictory about his role in the administration's
controversial decisions, including the aborted arms sale to Iran.
   ``I didn't take it as personal criticism,'' said Bush, ``because
I have a relationship with the president where I can walk in, tell
him anything I think. And then he knows I'm not going to go out and
talk to the press.''
   Bush said he was willing to ``take a shot'' from Democrats on
the arms-for-hostages deal, but said he would talk about the
accomplishments of the administration at the same time _ including
the current record peacetime economic recovery.
   The vice president declined anew to disclose what advise he gave
to President Reagan on the arms deal.
   Later, Bush told a news conference in the rain on the beach at
Point Pleasant, N.J., that he supports a ban on all ocean dumping
``the sooner the better.''
   ``Frankly, it's a national tragedy,'' Bush said, standing
alongside a display of medical wastes that had washed up on New
Jersey beaches.
   New Jersey Gov. Tom Kean, who stood alongside the vice
president, called Bush ``a candidate who really cares about the
ocean.'' Kean criticized Dukakis for not also advocating a ban on
ocean dumping.
   A small group of protesters stood on the beach as Bush held his
news conference, holding placards and chanting ``Where was George?''
   Bush, as he had done earlier in the day, praised Dukakis'
acceptance speech, although he said it struck him as superficial.
He said that Democrats had made an impressive show of unity, even
though he claimed it might be short-lived.
   But, Bush said, ``our (convention) will be much more postiive. I
won't be saying what's wrong with the country.''
   ``Jesse Jackson made him (Dukakis) look conservative. He's not,
he's a liberal,'' Bush said.
</TEXT>
