<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Italy-Fashion     07-22 0553</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-Fashion,0565</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Valentino Decrees The Return Of Chic</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto ROM4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIELA PETROFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Fashion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Valentino, the Caesar of Italian couture, exiled the
miniskirt and decreed the return of knee-length or midcalf hemlines
for a fashionable fall and winter.
   His new high fashion collection is young and elegant, with a
myriad of prim little sheaths, small spencer jackets and demure
chiffon gowns. It was presented in Rome's Grand Hotel Thursday
night to a star-studded audience that included actress Sophia Loren.
   The Valentino fall hemline harks back to the classic on the
knee-length, with a few exceptions rising a discreet two inches
above the knee, or dropping to midcalf.
   The tight derriere, characteristic of the 1980s mini, also
disappears, to be replaced by proper pleats even in the longer
skirts.
   While other designers, showing during the Italian high fashion
week which ended in Rome Friday, played heavily on the gilded and
ornate, Valentino insisted on simplicity throughout his collection.
   By day he used such classic fabrics as gray flannel and
houndstooth for his redingote pleated coats and town-and-country
suits with short spencer jackets enriched by a bell-shaped cuff and
long pleated skirt with high waistline, marked by a thin leather
belt.
   He also ennobled the most traditional of winter wear, the
cashmere twin set, by trimming the cuff in sable. For those who
can't afford the couture version, this idea is easily imitated in
the home, with a lesser wool and a humbler fur.
   To rejuvenate his classical elegance, Valentino used bold shades
of pastel pink, blue and green as well as his trademark red. Velvet
shawl collars and cuffs trimmed with lace enhance the youthful
spirit of the collection.
   The cocktail hour by Valentino is basic black with a new twist _
the mixture of fabrics and shades to bring the Manhattan look up to
date. An Empire-waisted black velvet dress, for example, has a
crisscross draped black chiffon bodice, while a simple, sleeveless
black velvet sheath is brightened up by a white, scalloped,
apron-like overslip.
   Nighttime a la Valentino is an ode to the artisan craftsmanship
which is the trademark of Italian high fashion. Embroidery is no
longer flatly stitched on, but comes alive in three-dimensional
sequined roses, or delicate dahlias formed out of satin ribbons.
   Favorite fabrics are chiffon and taffeta, shaped into unfussy
silhouettes, where the emphasis is always on the detail, such as a
draped bodice, flowered embroidery or a richly decorated
cummerbund. Colors are bold shades of yellow, green, purple and
pink.
   Valentino's newest evening shade is Madonna blue, perhaps in
deference to Pope John Paul II, who is celebrating 1988 as a
special year dedicated to the Virgin Mary.
   For the grande soiree, Valentino, the only Italian designer who
can vie with his French colleagues for ballroom fame, proposes
wide-skirted gowns in gray taffeta with an overlayer of tulle
dotted with white tufts for a three-dimensional polka dot effect,
or a sumptuous, brown satin gown whose wide hem trimmed in sable
gives it an Imperial Russian allure.
   As Valentino came down the runway, which was decorated with an
imposing sculpture of the head of a Roman centurion, to take a
final bow, a deeply tanned Miss Loren expressed her approval of the
entire collection, but said she particularly craved ``those
unbelievable ballgowns.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
