<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Pub     07-22 0203</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Pub,0211</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Missile Team Visits British Pub</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 20-member Soviet team, in Britain to inspect
U.S.-operated missile bases, stopped Friday to examine a local
phenomenon _ the English pub.
   The Soviets were en route to the Greenham Common air base where
U.S. medium-range nuclear missiles have been installed. Both U.S.
and Soviet medium-range missiles are to be eliminated under the
pact agreed to in December by the two superpowers.
   The Soviet delegation made a beer stop at the Coach and Horses
pub in Midgham, Berkshire.
   Pub owner Ann Holden said she had been told to expect foreign
visitors and suspected it might be the Soviets.
   ``All our locals were tickled when they walked in, it caused
quite a stir,'' she said. ``We all felt rather honored that our pub
had been chosen.''
   Mrs. Holden said the Soviets sipped their pints of beer and
talked to other customers through interpreters.
   ``They all had a pint of beer, only one each mind you, and they
all seemed to enjoy it,'' she said.
   The Soviets were given glass coasters and in turn handed out
souvenir badges, but ``I don't know what they said, it was all in
Russian,'' said Mrs. Holden.
</TEXT>
