<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pakistan-Bus     07-22 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan-Bus,0236</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Monsoons Blamed For Bus Accident; 71 Feared Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Torrential monsoon rains and
floodwaters swept a crowded bus off a bridge into a shallow ravine
in eastern Pakistan Friday and up to 71 people were killed, police
said.
   They said nine people survived and 18 bodies were recovered,
   The disaster occurred Thursday in eastern Punjab province, about
20 miles southeast of Islamabad. Police said the bus was so
crowded, passengers were riding on the roof.
   The police chief of the nearby village of Kahuta, Riaz Hussain
Shah, said the bus became trapped in floodwaters as it crossed the
bridge and was swept away by the current.
   Witnesses said passengers jumped in panic into the water and
were swept away.
   Shah said the army helped search for survivors, but darkness and
the strong current hampered rescue operations.
   The bus was believed to be ferrying about 80 people between
nearby Rawalpindi and Rawal Kot, about 60 miles east of Islamabad
in Kashmir province.
   The passengers were said to be Kashmiri residents heading home
for an Islamic holy festival.
   Also Friday, Pakistan's news agency reported that a landslide
killed two people near the village of Mansehra, about 50 miles
north of Islamabad.
   An Urdu-language daily, Jang, said before the bus accident that
the rains had killed four people and flooded hundreds of villages.
</TEXT>
