<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Duvalier     07-22 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Duvalier,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Throws Out Haitian Ex-Ruler's Appeal on Funds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An appeals court Friday rejected an attempt by
former Haitian dictator Jean-Claude Duvalier and his family to
block a probe into the whereabouts of $120 million the Duvaliers
allegedly stole from the state.
   Lord Justice Sir Christopher Staughton dismissed the Duvaliers'
claim that they were being persecuted, saying in that event, they
should cooperate in the international search for the missing
millions.
   ``This case demands international cooperation between all
nations,'' he said.
   A French court ruled in April that it had jurisdiction in the
case, which is to be heard in Grasse, the French Riviera town where
Duvalier and his wife, Michelle, now live.
   Duvalier was ousted in a coup in February 1986 and fled with his
family to France. Haiti's present rulers accuse the Duvaliers of
misappropriating the funds.
   Haitian government representatives began proceedings to seek
information on assets that may be hidden in Britain, and to have
them frozen if they turn up.
   Judicial sources in France have said a household budget sheet
seized by investigators shows Duvalier and his wife still live
comfortably. The sources said this could undermine their claim that
they left all their money in Haiti.
   Entries include such items as $5,600 for a dress and $83,000
spent on jewelry from July 1987 to January 1988.
   Duvalier, his wife and his mother, the widow of the notorious
dictator Francois ``Papa Doc'' Duvalier, have been staying in a
luxurious villa rented from Saudi businessman Adnan Kashoggi.
</TEXT>
