<HEAD>Pope Rules Out Stop In South Africa In Upcoming African Tour</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LORENZAGO, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II said Friday he would
like to visit South Africa some day but that he will not stop there
during his upcoming tour of five southern African countries.
   John Paul, talking to reporters at the end of a 10-day vacation
in the Dolomite Alpine town of Lorenzago, said that the Roman
Catholic bishops of South Africa do not believe the time is ripe
for such a visit.
   But he added that he hoped ``perhaps one day'' he could visit
there.
   From Sept. 10-20, the pope is scheduled to visit Botswana,
Lesotho, Mozambique, Swaziland and Zimbabwe.
   From Lorenzago, the pope was scheduled to return to Rome and go
immediately to his summer vacation palace in Castel Gandolfo, south
of the capital.
