<HEAD>Bank Robbers Hold Boy Hostage in 10-Hour Ordeal</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto RIO1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men surprised by police during
an attempted bank robbery took a 13-year-old boy hostage and led
police on a 60-mile chase before surrendering early Friday, state
police said.
   No one was injured in the incident.
   Law enforcement officials interrupted the attempted bank robbery
Thursday in the mountain resort town of Teresopolis, 60 miles
northeast of Rio de Janeiro, police said.
   Police said the two suspects fled to a nearby farmhouse and took
the boy, identified as Andre Luiz Santarrita, hostage. Live
television footage showed one of the robbers holding two pistols to
the child's head and pleading with police surrounding the house not
to invade.
   After 10 hours, the boy was released in exchange for five other
hostages, including a police chief and journalists.
   Early Friday, the two fled with the hostages in a car and were
chased by police along the winding mountain road to Rio. The
hostages were released in Rio, and the robbers were trapped by
police and surrendered.
   Rio de Janeiro state police said the two men, identified only as
Mauro and Rogerio, were in police custody in Rio Friday night.
