<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Tehran Radio Reports Demonstration By Pilgrims In Mecca</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 8th graf pvs `The Saudi interior minister ....' with 1
graf to CORRECT that press conference was last Saturday, sted
Saturday. PICKS up 9th graf pvs bgng, `Speaking in Jiddah ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tehran radio said hundreds of pilgrims carrying
placards condemning the deaths of 402 people in rioting in Mecca
last year demonstrated in that Saudi Arabian city Friday and that
some of them were attacked by police.
   The radio reported: ``Hundreds of Arab, Turk, Afghan, Pakistani
and American pilgrims demonstrated in Mecca today (Friday),
chanting slogans ... and carrying placards condemning the Al-Saud
regime in their killing of over 400 pilgrims of the holy sanctuary
last year in Mecca.''
   The report by the state-controlled radio, monitored in Britain,
added:
   ``According to received reports, the Saudi regime's police ...
subjected the demonstrators to severe control and surrounded them.
In some sections, they attacked the ranks of the marchers.''
   Parts of the Tehran radio report were indistinct but monitrs
heard no reference to any injuries.
   Saudi security forces were put on full alert earlier this month
as people began pouring in for the annual Moslem pilgrimage to
Mecca, Islam's holy city.
   Saudi authorities have blamed Iran for instigating the riots
there lat year. Iran has blamed violence by Saudi security forces
for the deaths during demonstrations by Iranian pilgrims against
Iran's enemies.
   The Saudi interior minister, Prince Nayef Bin Abdel Aziz, told a
news conference last Saturday: ``All precautions have been taken to
face any emergency whatsoever.''
   Speaking in Jiddah, the Saudi capital, Aziz said anyone
undermining security would be ``taught a lesson that will make
others not even think of any similar action.''
   He said Iranians would not be barred from making the pilgrimage
to Mecca this year. ``The door is always open for them,'' he
declared.
   But Saudi authorities announced earlier that the number of
pilgrims would be restricted this year to one for every 1,000
residents of each Moslem country and Aziz said Iran was included in
this restriction.
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency charged this month
that the Saudi royal family was not fit to supervise the holy
shrines at Mecca and Medina where the pilgrimage is centered
   Saudi authorities closed entry points to the kingdom on Monday.
This is a traditional measure necessary to organize transport to
the holy sites.
   More than 1 million pilgrims converge on the holy sites most
years.
