<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--Arrington 1stLd-Writethru a0776 07-22 0430</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Arrington, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0776,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Black Mayor Of Once-Embattled City Says Party Similarly Healed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 4th graf pvs to show that Arrington speech not used to
introduce Bradley, picks up 5th graf pvs, ``I am ...''; SUBS 10th
graf pvs to show Bradley comments included in prepared remarks,
picks up 11th graf pvs, ``As a pro ...''
^By KENDAL WEAVER</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Birmingham Mayor Richard Arrington, in an
emotional appeal to Jesse Jackson supporters, implored blacks and
whites on Thursday to unite behind Michael Dukakis in the same way
that they joined forces to reclaim Birmingham from the bastions of
segregation.
   ``If blacks and whites can work side by side to rebuild and
reclaim our city _ as we have done _ we can rebuild our party and
reclaim the White House,'' Arrington said.
   ``The enemy is not in this hall,'' he said.
   Arrington, who in 1979 became the first black to be elected
mayor of Birmingham, used the theme ````We Are Family'' in his
address to the Democratic delegates. Arrington had originally been
scheduled to introduce New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley, but party
officials changed the Thursday night agenda and Arrington's speech
was not an introductory one.
   ``I am _ do not forget _ from Birmingham,'' said the mayor. ``We
know about strife, discord, hurt feelings, shattered dreams, dashed
hopes.
   ``But we also know about healing, rebuilding, putting
differences behind us, about yesterday's enemy being today's ally.
About understanding, forgiveness, unity.''
   Arrington, a Jesse Jackson delegate who has pushed for a
harmonious convention, urged Jackson followers to put aside their
disappointment and work to get a Democrat in the White House.
   ``We need you, Jesse _ this party, this country _ we need your
ideas, your convictions, your empathy, your passion, your vision,
and that great gift from God: your powerful words ...
   ``We need your strong arms to lock with ours, marching into
battle, not against our own, but against the party of privilege.''
   In his prepared remarks, Arrington likened the role of Jackson
and his supporters in the fall campaign to Bradley's performance on
the basketball court.
   ``As a pro player, he was a winner, best known for moving
without the ball, helping to position his team for the win,'' he
said of the man he called ``my taller brother.''
   ``Likewise, in politics he knows that you don't always have to
have the ball to help your team win, that sometimes you have to
move without the ball or to pass to a teammate. He knows that
teamwork is what wins.''
</TEXT>
