<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-88 2310EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-HungarianLeader     07-22 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hungarian Leader,0448</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hungarian and Industrialist Armand Hammer Want More East-West
Trade</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LUIS TORRES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungarian leader Karoly Grosz said Friday he
hopes improved East-West relations fostered by President Reagan and
Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev will improve trade opportunities
between Hungary and the West.
   Grosz, newly elected general secretary of Hungary's Communist
Party, was welcomed to Los Angeles by Dr. Armand Hammer, chairman
and chief executive officer of Occidental Petroleum Corp. and a
longtime associate of Soviet and other Eastern European political
leaders.
   Hammer offered an official welcome to the city on behalf of
Mayor Tom Bradley who is in China on a trade mission.
   Grosz, 57, who replaced longtime Hungarian leader Janos Kadar in
May, is in the middle of a visit to the United States that will
include a meeting with Reagan on July 27.
   In addition to being general secretary, the top political post
in Hungary, Grosz also serves as prime minister.
   At a news conference at Occidental's headquarters where he was
flanked by Hammer and an interpreter, Grosz described his visit to
the United States as an effort to improve prospects of economic
cooperation between his country and America.
   ``I think the mere fact that we are here speaking in this room
right now is evidence'' of the potential for increased cooperation,
said Grosz through an interpreter. ``This is the result of the
constructive policies of President Reagan that the prime minister
of Hungary could lead a delegation to the U.S.''
   Asked what success he had achieved in increasing U.S.-Hungarian
trade, Grosz answered, ``Successes we have not, but hopes I do
have.''
   In general terms, Grosz said he had discussed business
opportunities with Hammer.
   ``We have had very constructive discussions with Dr. Hammer,''
said Grosz. ``But what we have discussed is still not reality, but
very hopeful (for) the future.''
   Hammer said some steps have been taken that could lead to mutual
economic ventures.
   ``We have had many good talks _ the prime minister and I,'' said
Hammer. ``Recently we signed letters of intent in Russia for a
joint venture, and Hungary has been working on this project, too,
for four years approximately,'' he said. ``And I think it very
likely that we and our partners will consider ... the possibility
of inviting Hungary to participate with us.''
   Throughout the news conference the Hungarian leader sat erect
with his hands in his lap. He continually fingered a small jade
disk.
   Grosz explained why he always keeps the small charm with him.
``It is for luck,'' he said. ``Politicians always are in need of
luck.''
</TEXT>
