<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Brites Sub a0773 07-22 0388</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites, Sub, a0773,0396</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 1st item to UPDATE with Opry allowing Stewart to sing.
Leads with 5 grafs, picks up 3rd graf pvs, deletes outdated 5th
graf pvs `Stewart hopes...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tired but triumphant man arrived in
town Friday after walking 1,500 miles for the past three months in
a successful effort to dramatize his desire to sing on the Grand
Ole Opry.
   David Stewart, 37, of Gillette, Wyo., said the general manager
of the 63-year-old Opry susprised him with a phone call Friday
evening saying he could sing on the live country music show
Saturday night. An Opry spokesman confirmed the invitation.
   ``I was sitting there in my motel room when Mr. (Hal) Durham
called me and asked me about the walk and so forth,'' Stewart said.
When Durham offered him a spot on the show, Stewart said, ``I just
about fell out of my chair.''
   Opry officials said before Stewart began his trip that Opry
singers normally are veteran performers or nationally known
recording artists. They suggested he audition for The Nashville
Network show, ``You Can Be a Star,'' which sponsors competition for
budding country music performers.
   Stewart reached the steps of the state Capitol on Friday to
climax a trek that covered seven states and wore out three pair of
athletic shoes.
   ``I feel great,'' he said. ``I'm very emotional now. But it was
a beautiful trip and I met some beautiful people.''
   Snicker, a brown and white 2{-year-old mixed cocker spaniel,
made the trip with him. ``People brought him dog bones and
things,'' said Stewart, on leave from his job as manager of a
fast-food restaurant.
   Stewart left Gillette on April 30 and walked across Wyoming,
Nebraska, Iowa, Missouri, Illinois, Kentucky and Tennessee. Weather
ranged from a May 1 snowstorm in Wyoming to high heat the past few
weeks.
   ``There were days when it was 105 or 106 degrees,'' he said. ``I
just kept thinking about getting to Nashville.''
   Stewart normally walked six days a week, taking Sundays off, and
averaged up to 30 miles each day. He stayed in hotels or in a motor
home that followed him with country music promoter Floyd Haynes
driving.
   ``This was a way for me to show my appreciation of country
music,'' Stewart said of the walk.
</TEXT>
