<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ForestFireRdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0766 07-22 0938</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Forest Fire Rdp, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0766,0958</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Forest Fires Burning In Northwest And Alaska</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with fire in Utah contained,
reduce size of fire east of San Francisco to 11,000 acres,
reflecting official change, picking up 4th graf pvs, `None of...'.
Subs 13th graf, ``Wind blowing,'' to update with wind diminishing.
Subs 18th grafs to end, bgng ``A fire...,'' with 8 grafs to UPDATE
size of Colo. fire, add later fires in California and reduce size
of Calaveras County fire.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Weary firefighters hoped for rain Friday to give them a hand on
52 forest fires burning in northern Alaska, and a Wyoming blaze
that had charred nearly 20,000 acres was within a mile of the
border of Yellowstone National Park.
   Arson was blamed for six fires in the mountains northeast of Los
Angeles and for a pair of fires that had burned nearly 11,000 acres
and six homes east of San Francisco. Gusty wind fanned an
out-of-control blaze in Washington, and wind in Colorado pushed a
fire in all directions.
   Fires also burned in Oregon, but in Utah, firefighters contained
a blaze that blackened 300 acres in a desolate scrubland area
northwest of Cedar City.
   None of the Alaska fires was much of a threat to life or
property, said Bill Rockwell of the Bureau of Land Management's
Alaska Fire Service office in Fairbanks.
   ``We've had several cabins threatened, but we've managed to put
a line around those,'' Rockwell said Friday. ``Seventeen fires have
manpower on them; the others are in limited suppression areas and
they're being monitored by air.
   ``We're getting rain in Fairbanks and some rain in and around
the fires. What we need is a good front to move in, but it doesn't
seem to be happening.''
   A half-dozen of the Alaska fires had charred large areas, but
mostly in remote terrain covered by trees of little commercial
value, officials said.
   The Waring Mountain fire had burned 138,000 acres about 35 miles
northwest of Ambler, Rockwell said. The Livengood fire had charred
300,000 acres, but was reported moving toward the sparsely
populated Yukon Flats refuge.
   Fire managers say it has been unusually dry in Alaska this year.
Lightning has caused most of the fires.
   The Mink Creek blaze in the Teton Wilderness in Wyoming grew by
almost 2,900 acres since Thursday to cover 19,960 acres Friday,
with most of that growth on the fire's northern end near
Yellowstone, said Pam Gardner, a fire information officer for the
Bridger-Teton National Forest.
   Although the fire was nearing the park's border, it was still
far away from any major attractions. Several fires were burning
within the park, but firefighters would go to work on them only if
they threatened structures or adjacent national forest lands, said
park spokeswoman Joan Anzelmo.
   Also in Wyoming, a 600-acre blaze in the Bridger Wilderness area
about 25 miles north of Pinedale was about 75 percent contained
Friday, said fire information officer Dave Olson.
   Wind blowing at 15 to 20 mph with gusts to 30 mph hampered some
300 firefighters battling an out-of-control fire that covered 120
acres of felled timber and logging debris near Washington's
Snoqualmie Pass. The wind diminished during the afternoon and
firefighters tried to stop the fire at the top of a ridge,
officials said.
   Department of Natural Resources spokesman Tim Boyd predicted it
would take several days to control the fire, which was burning or
threatening 1.5 million board feet of Douglas fir worth more than
$300,000.
   The fire, mostly on rugged private land, had destroyed a
bulldozer and logging tower.
   ``There's no precipitation in sight. This really has a lot of
potential to be a very tough fire,'' Boyd said.
   In northeastern Washington, a grass-and-timber fire had burned
about 1,500 acres on the Colville Indian Reservation, covering the
town of Omak with smoke, but it had been circled by a bulldozer
trail, said Pat Quill of the Bureau of Indian Affairs. A few
abandoned buildings were destroyed.
   A fire about eight miles north of Canon City, Colo., was
``moving in all four directions'' in brush and pinon juniper Friday
because of erratic wind and more than tripled in size to 1,100
acres by late afternoon, BLM fire officials said.
   ``Once the winds and weather turned on us, we didn't have a
chance,'' said associate fire manager Stuart Freer.
   Elsewhere in Colorado, firefighters were conducting final
mopping-up operations at a 3,130-acre fire near Dinosaur National
Monument and a 15,000-acre blaze near Maybell that was one of the
largest range fires in the state's history.
   An arsonist set six fires in the San Bernardino National Forest
about 50 miles northeast of Los Angeles, including one that
destroyed two storage buildings and a car, blackened 150 acres and
threatened about 10 homes, authorities said Friday.
   The fires that began Thursday were all contained by 6 a.m.
Friday, said Lindsay Maierhofer, spokeswoman for the Forest Service.
   But another fire, which authorities believe was started by
fireworks, had covered 400 acres and was burning out of control
Friday afternoon in the Spoor Canyon area of the national forest.
That fire briefly threatened several homes before the wind changed
direction.
   Another out-of-control brush fire burned over 140 acres near
Morgan Hill, Calif., southeast of San Jose.
   Hundreds of state prisoners battled two arson-linked fires that
had charred 11,000 acres of heavy timber and brush near the
Calaveras County town of Rail Road Flat, 150 miles east of San
Francisco. Firefighters were close to containing the blazes, which
have caused an estimated $3.8 million damage to the drought-parched
region since Tuesday.
</TEXT>
