<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--Bradley     07-22 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Bradley,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bradley Says President Must `Stay Awake'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS G. KATSARELAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Bill Bradley told the Democratic National
Convention on Thursday the next president ``must be a person who is
awake and will stay awake,'' and that Democratic nominee Michael
Dukakis is ``committed to excellence.''
   ``A president must engender trust because a president leads by
trust,'' the New Jersey senator told the convention's closing
session. ``Trust is a bond earned by honest words and honest
activities.''
   Bradley, considered by many a candidate for the national ticket
but who declined to run, paid homage to past leaders, lavished
praise on Dukakis, saying he is excited to lead, committed to
govern all the people and proud of the country.
   Dukakis is ``a person committed to excellence, who is calm under
pressure and has the capacity to know what's important,'' Bradley
said.
   Bradley aimed some barbs at the Reagan administration without
naming it, saying the next president ``must be a person who is
awake and will stay awake, because he can't rest while kids kill
kids in our cities and families sleep on the streets.''
   ``A good president doesn't define honesty as simply staying out
of jail,'' he said.
   ``Does it make a difference who's president of the United
States?'' Bradley asked. ``Did Lincoln make a difference? Did
Woodrow Wilson? Ask any child who stares in wonder at the Grand
Canyon if Teddy Roosevelt made a difference.''
   He said a president can offer inspirational leadership by
showing how the past is part of the present, and how both can lead
to a better future.
   ``He can give reassurance and understanding to those who have
never been reassured or understood; he can give guidance in a world
that technology changes every day. The words of a president, like
nature's returning seasons, can provide continuity in the midst of
change.''
   Courage, honor and truth are vital qualities of leadership and
the president must demonstrate self-sacrifice to encourage
unselfishness among others, Bradley said.
   ``He knows ... that the ultimate question posed to a citizen in
a democracy is to ask yourself what you owe another human being,''
said Bradley. ``Do you owe more than a contribution to charity or
taxes to the government? Do you owe a commitment of some part of
your life? Or do you believe you owe nothing at all?
   ``How we answer these questions will determine the kind of
society we become,'' he said.
   Asked before the speech if he were anxious, Bradley, a former
professional basketball player, responded that being nervous ``has
a tendency to get the adrenalin going.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
