<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-88 0237EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-US-Missiles     07-22 0476</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-US-Missiles,0489</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cruise Missiles Counted, Soviet Inspectors Turn Tourists</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. cruise missile counting done, Soviet
inspectors turned tourists Thursday, sightseeing in London and
joining royalty, school groups and thousands of families at a
military pageant, the Royal Tournament.
   The 20 inspectors, some after a sleepless night spent checking
two missile sites and writing reports, watched the display in the
packed Earls Court Exhibition Center in west London.
   Queen Elizabeth II's daughter, Princess Anne, seated 20 rows
above the Soviets in the royal box, did not notice the plainclothes
group arrive.
   But she glanced down, frowning slightly, as they slipped out,
escorted by five American officers, just before the national
anthem, ``God Save The Queen,'' was struck up at the end of the
three-hour afternoon performance.
   Meanwhile, 10 U.S. inspectors meanwhile arrived in
Czechoslovakia Thursday for the first inspection of a former base
for Soviet nuclear missiles in the Warsaw Pact country, the
official CTK news agency reported in Prague.
   CTK said earlier that permission was granted for the inspection
at the central Czechoslovak town of Hranice, 180 miles southeast of
Prague.
   Soviet troops stationed with the SS-12 missiles began pulling
the weapons out in February, even before the U.S. Congress ratified
the superpower treaty. The former missile base at Hranice now
houses a Czechoslovak army unit, CTK said.
   Thursday's show in the 13,000-capacity Earls Court Exhibition
Center was a near-sellout.
   Organizers said they gave the Soviets the best seats left, at
$21.25 each, paid for by the American hosts.
   The inspectors watched massed bands of British regiments
perform, equestrian events and hundreds of children in a gymnastic
display to pop music.
   Toting packed suppers, the Soviet inspectors _ 19 men and one
woman _ and the six-man crew of their Iluyshin IL-62 jet then
visited the Houses of Parliament, a tourist must-see, and took in
other sights from their bus.
   Their schedule called for them to return late Thursday to the
U.S. air base at Greenham Common, the main cruise missile site in
Britain, 50 miles west of London, and to fly home on Friday,
British officials said.
   The group arrived Tuesday on the first inspection in Britain
under the U.S.-Soviet treaty that provides for elimination of the
superpowers' land-based medium-range nuclear missiles in Europe by
1991.
   Under the treaty, inspectors are not allowed off missile sites.
But British and U.S. officers waived the rules when the Soviet
group asked to see some famed London landmarks.
   The inspections at Greenham Common and the other U.S. cruise
base in Britain, Molesworth, near Cambridge, are part of a 60-day
period of initial checks which started July 1.
   The Soviets are visiting 30 sites in the United States and five
Western European countries. U.S. experts are visiting 133 East bloc
sites. No violations have been reported so far.
</TEXT>
