<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ElvisTrust     07-22 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Elvis Trust,0386</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lisa Marie OKs Continuing Graceland Tours</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Elvis Alive?, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WOODY BAIRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Graceland lives!
   Elvis Presley's only child has cleared the way for her father's
former residence, Graceland, to remain a tourist attraction at
least 10 more years, lawyers said Thursday.
   ``She's not going to close it down. It's doing fabulously,''
said Blanchard Tual, a lawyer who was appointed to protect Lisa
Marie Presley's legal interests when she was a minor.
   Miss Presley, 20, would have taken sole control of his estate
when she turned 25, according to her father's will. But she agreed
to extend by five years the management structure of a trust set up
to handle her father's estate.
   The management agreement, approved Wednesday in Chancery Court
in Memphis, extends the conditions of the trust until 1998, said
Barry Ward, a lawyer for the Presley estate.
   ``Basically, this is a vote of confidence from Lisa Marie to the
management team to continue to handle the assets that she will
inherit from her father,'' Ward said.
   Tual said Graceland managers have encountered problems because
of speculation over Miss Presley's plans for Graceland.
   ``They found it harder and harder to deal with people on a
long-term basis when they said, `Look you've only got five years
left and how do we know what Lisa Marie will do in five years when
the trust terminates.' In order to do away with that uncertainty,
they just extended it five more years,'' Tual said.
   Tual no longer represents Miss Presley but was called in to
review the request for the management agreement.
   Presley was largely uninterested in business matters during his
career and he was worth $5 million to $7 million when he died,
estate officials say.
   Joseph Hanks, an accountant and trustee of the Presley estate,
said it is worth about $50 million now and its value is increasing.
   The estate, which has worked in recent years to secure legal
rights to the singer's name and image, includes Graceland, a
white-columned, three-story house that attracted more than 600,000
visitors last year.
   The Graceland complex, with a 36,000-square-foot shopping center
devoted almost entirely to Elvis souvenirs, generates some $9
million a year in tourist business.
</TEXT>
