<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Contras, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0722,0557</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sandinistas: New Contra Leadership Makes Peace Even More Difficult</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with report of Contra attacks.
PICKS up 4th graf pvs bgng, Bermudez, commander .... ADDS 5 grafs
at bottom with details.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ruling Sandinista party said
Thursday a new rebel leadership that includes a military commander
makes negotiating an end to the U.S.-supported war even more
difficult.
   Also Thursday, a military officer said the U.S.-backed rebels,
known as Contras, mounted several attacks this week to disrupt the
Sandinista government's celebration of its ninth anniversary. The
officer said 34 rebels were killed in fighting.
   An editorial in the Sandinista National Liberation Front's
newspaper Barricada said, ``It makes the possibility of negotiating
peace even more remote,'' referring to the election of Enrique
Bermudez to the seven-member Contra directorate.
   The paper said Bermudez's election at a meeting in the Dominican
Republic on Monday ``removes the civilian mask'' the Contras wore.
   Bermudez, commander of the main rebel army known as the
Nicaraguan Democratic Force, was a colonel in the national guard of
the Somoza dynasty that ruled Nicaragua for 42 years until it was
overthrown by the leftist Sandinistas in July 1979.
   He has long been a major point of friction in the Nicaraguan
Resistance coalition.
   Some members of the coalition are former Sandinistas, leery of a
return to a military-dominated government. At least five Southern
Front field commanders split away from the Resistance to protest
Bermudez's election.
   Claiming Bermudez's election was engineered by the CIA, the
Barricada editorial claimed that ``with the appointment of the new
directorate the CIA has ratified the Somoza leadership in the
movement, which years ago it made an effort to hide.''
   ``In order to ensure the survival of the Contras, the CIA has
been obliged to promote Bermudez to the highest level of
leadership,'' the newspaper said.
   A cease-fire has been in effect since March 21 in the 7-year-old
war between the Sandinista government and the Contras.
   On Tuesday, the ninth anniversary of the Sandinista guerrillas'
successful march into Managua, President Daniel Ortega announced a
unilateral extension of the cease-fire until Aug. 30. The Contras
have not yet said if they will do the same.
   No talks currently are scheduled for the attempt to reach a
lasting peace agreement. The last round broke off in June.
   Maj. Ramon Caldera, chief of the general staff for the Fifth
Military Region, reported on this week's Contra attacks at a
ceremony for the demobilization of 12,000 Sandinista army soldiers.
   Caldera said the attacks occurred in his command, which includes
central Chontales province and northern Boaco province. He gave no
details, except to say 34 rebels died in fighting.
   Caldera also claimed the Contras were secretly supplied with
weapons in four airdrops in northeastern Nueva Guinea province
during the first 15 days of July.
   A Defense Ministry statement said two rebels died Wednesday when
a Contra group attacked an army patrol in Buenos Aires, about 148
miles north of the capital. It said Contras kidnapped six civilians
in the northern part of the country on Sunday and Tuesday.
   The statement, which gave no details, also said 6 rebels
deserted to the Sandinista forces this week.
</TEXT>
