<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WildfiresRdp     07-22 0636</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wildfires Rdp,0657</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Firefighters Gaining Upper Hand on Wildfires in California,
Wyoming</HEAD>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Firefighters gained the upper hand Thursday on wildfires that
charred some 12,500 acres in California and more than 17,000 acres
in the Teton Wilderness of Wyoming, but officials remained cautious.
   Meantime, more than 100 firefighters rushed to the Umatilla
National Forest in Oregon, where a fire that destroyed logging
equipment burned out of control, and fires that posed no immediate
threat to property or people burned in Utah.
   At least six states had fires raging, but blazes in Colorado and
Alaska were being brought under control or burning out.
   California firefighters carved control lines around twin
wildfires, leaving flames to gnaw mostly at uninhabited timber
country in rugged Calaveras County.
   The blazes that began Tuesday have razed six houses, including a
$600,000 two-story structure with contents the owners valued at
more than $400,000.
   ``There will never be a house like this again. You spend 49
years collecting things you love and in less than an hour, they're
gone,'' Hazel Burt said as she picked through the ruins.
   Authorities estimated the total timber and property losses plus
the costs of fighting the Calaveras blazes at $4.3 million,
although they said the figure would likely increase.
   Investigators found an incendiary device that was used to set
one of the two arson-suspected fires.
   Authorities predicted full containment by Friday evening.
   ``Firefighters are getting the upper hand,'' said Dick Craig, a
California Department of Forestry spokesman at the fire camp in
Rail Road Flat, 150 miles east of San Francisco and a few miles
west of the fires.
   Still, the pronouncement was cautious. ``Some of the lines
aren't very secure,'' Craig said.
   In Wyoming, crews combatted a wildfire in the Bridger-Teton
National Forest and gained the advantage by fighting fire with fire.
   Forest officials began talking in guarded terms of containment
following an intentional ``back burn'' of some 2,000 acres of
tinder-dry trees on the southern edge of the fire in the Teton
Wilderness.
   ``If we can hold on to what he have secured on the south end the
rest of today and tomorrow, we have turned the corner. We are
making good progress,'' said fire official Dale Jarrell.
   Firefighters ignited the area, on the edge of the densest area
of 15,000 acres of trees blown down last summer by a rare,
high-altitude tornado, by dropping chemical-filled pingpong balls
from a helicopter.
   The controlled burn, which was intended to keep the flames from
spreading into that dense area of trees, has allowed crews to get
that part of the fire 50 percent contained, said Fire Information
Officer Ed Waldapfel.
   ``We're a long ways from being out of the woods, but we're going
in the right direction,'' he said.
   In Oregon, Kathy Campbell, a spokeswoman for the Umatilla
National Forest, said about 130 federal firefighters, including
five 20-person fire crews and a 30-member supervisory team, were
assigned to the fire that destroyed logging equipment shortly after
breaking out Thursday afternoon.
   Oregon Department of Forestry spokesman Doug Decker said the
fire quickly grew to 150 acres and stiff winds and steep canyons
were causing concern for the firefighters.
   In Colorado, all but two of the fires that have charred more
than 21,000 acres since Saturday have been declared under control.
   And in Alaska, where fires have burned 1,300 square miles _
larger than Rhode Island _ this season, the state Fire Service has
left most blazes to burn themselves out. It has been monitoring
about 50 wildfires, some of them weeks old.
   The biggest is a 225,000-acre blaze 60 miles north of Fairbanks
that approached the Alaska pipeline earlier this month but was
stopped about 12 miles from it. The pipeline is covered with
heavy-gauge metal and was not threatened, Alyeska Pipeline Service
Co. said.
</TEXT>
