<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CVN--VivaMike     07-22 0137</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CVN--Viva Mike,170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nominee's Spanish Phrases Draw Cheers _ In Spanish</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cries of ``Viva Mike'' reverberated through the
convention hall Thursday night as Michael Dukakis gave part of his
acceptance speech for the Democratic presidential nomination in
Spanish.
   Dukakis spoke of Willie Velasquez, longtime head of the
Southwest Voter Education Project, who died recently.
   Dukakis paid tribute to Velasquez, stating both in English and
in Spanish that when Velasquez ``can register tens of thousands of
his fellow citizens to vote, bringing new energy, new ideas, new
people to the local and state governments in the Southwest, we are
all enriched and enobled.''
   Led by the Texas and Puerto Rico delegations, the hall erupted
in cheers of ``Viva Viva'' and ``Viva Mike.''
   Dukakis speaks fluent Spanish, having studied in South America
many years ago.
</TEXT>
