<TEXT>
   A series of suspicious stock trades just before
Business Week's widely-read Wall Street column hit the streets has
prompted an investigation by the magazine's publisher that ``covers
the entire operation.''
   McGraw-Hill Inc. spokesman Mary McGeachy said Thursday the
company was investigating Business Week's editorial staff as well
as employees in its four printing plants to determine whether
market-sensitive information was being leaked in advance of
publication.
   McGeachy said that ``some time back'' the company's legal
counsel began tracking stocks mentioned in the ``Inside Wall
Street'' column after noticing unusual rises and heavy trading
volume in those stocks on the day Business Week was printed but
before it reached newsstands.
   She said no employees had been suspended or fired.
