<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   07-22 0530</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0561</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allegheny International Inc. says it will move
Sunbeam's headquarters from the Chicago area to the offices of its
Oster appliance unit in Milwaukee, where office rent is cheaper.
   Some jobs will be eliminated in the Chicago suburb of Downers
Grove, Ill., where Sunbeam is based, Edward M. Romanoff, spokesman
for the Pittsburgh-based parent, said Thursday.
   He said it was not immediately clear how many of the 150
employees at Downers Grove will lose their jobs as the move occurs
over the next several months.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission is
cracking down on television pirates who market illegal descrambling
devices for backyard satellite dishes.
   ``We will put them out of business and, if we can, put them in
jail,'' FCC Chairman Dennis Patrick said Thursday.
   Patrick said the FCC is sending warning letters to 19 companies
that the FCC believes sell the technology that enables a dish owner
to decode the scrambled signals used by premium program services
like Home Box Office and Showtime.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Publishing Co. and Mead Data Central
Inc. have settled their court battle for control of the
computer-assisted legal research marketplace.
   ``Both parties finally came to the realization that the
diversion of time and money would be better spent focused on the
market,'' West attorney Vance K. Opperman said Thursday.
   Two federal judges helped settle the three lawsuits between the
competitors, which dominate a rapidly growing market that generates
more than $200 million in annual sales.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Three major pharmaceutical producers, Pfizer Inc.,
Schering-Plough Corp. and Squibb Corp., reported higher earnings
for the second quarter.
   Pfizer said Thursday that its net income rose 21 percent to
$213.1 million, or $1.26 a share, from $175.8 million, or $1.03 a
share, a year earlier.
   Schering-Plough's earnings jumped 22.4 percent to $101.0
million, or 90 cents a share, from $82.5 million, or 71 cents a
share.
   Squibb's net income rose 20 percent to $114.1 million, or $1.16
a share, from $95.2 million, or 91 cents a share.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Savings banks hold deposits equal to $1,700 for
every man, woman and child in the Soviet Union, which reflects how
difficult it is for people to find anything worth spending their
money on.
   The per capita savings figure of 1,000 rubles, revealed Thursday
in a government report, represents half a year's salary for most
Soviet workers and the hoard could generate serious inflation when
more consumer goods reach the market.
   Soviet savings banks hold personal deposits of 280 billion
rubles, or about $451 billion, for the nation's 284 million
residents.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market fell broadly Thursday, faced with a weak dollar
and rising interest rates. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials
fell 24.01 points to 2,086.59.
   The dollar declined sharply, while a strong British pound took
center stage in worldwide currency trading. Gold prices fell after
advancing overseas.
   Bond prices fell on the heels of the lower dollar.
   Oil prices rose for a second straight day on technical factors.
   Wheat and corn futures advanced, oats mostly were lower and
soybeans were mixed.
</TEXT>
