<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     07-22 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Rise for Second Straight Day</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures have rallied for a second
consecutive day on technical factors in the absence of any news to
affect the market.
   The September contract for the benchmark U.S. crude oil, West
Texas Intermediate, rose 34 cents to close at $16.39 a barrel
Thursday on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, the contract for
August delivery of unleaded gasoline rose 1.25 cents to close at
52.10 cents a gallon, while August home heating oil rose 0.88 cent
to 45.53 cents a gallon.
   Prices had moved out of a prolonged slump on Wednesday amid
reports about the proposed cease-fire between Iran and Iraq and the
possibility of a meeting of OPEC's pricing committee.
   But there were no new developments to influence trading
Thursday, said Jim Fiedler, a vice president at E.D.&F. Man
International Futures Inc.
   ``You're having a technical correction to a bear market,''
Fiedler said.
   Most traders are bullish for the short-term because of the
prospect of peace in the Persian Gulf, Fiedler said. They believe
an end to the 8-year-old war will remove the threat of oil supplies
being interrupted by the hostilities.
   But in the long-term, Fiedler said, many traders are bearish
because both countries could step up oil production _ adding to the
glut on worldwide markets _ as they try to repair their economies
following the war.
   Fiedler described the market as nervous in advance of a possible
Aug. 3 meeting of officials of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries to discuss pricing and production levels.
</TEXT>
