<DOCNO> AP880722-0271 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-88 0611EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Macmillan Bjt   07-22 0626</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Macmillan, Bjt,0653</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Maxwell Offers $2.07 Billion for Macmillan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's Robert Maxwell has emerged as a bidder
to compete with hostile suitor Robert Bass for Macmillan Inc., but
apparently not as the ``white knight'' that many analysts have been
expecting to appear and rescue Macmillan.
   Maxwell Communications, the media company headed by the
flamboyant publisher, said Thursday it had offered to buy Macmillan
in a conditional bid that values the company at $2.07 billion.
   Maxwell stated he would pay $80 a share for the 25.9 million
outstanding shares of Macmillan, the publishing giant that already
faces a hostile $1.9 billion tender offer from Robert M. Bass Group.
   But Macmillan issued a brief statement saying the Maxwell offer
was unsolicited and would be considered ``in due course'' along
with the Bass bid.
   Macmillan stock closed up $4.25 at $82.87{ per share, reflecting
speculation that a higher bid yet would emerge.
   Bass, which already holds a 9.9 percent stake in Macmillan,
launched a $75-a-share tender offer Monday for the shares it does
not already own. The spokesman for Bass was said to be out of his
office and unavailable for comment Thursday.
   Edward P. Evans, Macmillan's chairman and chief executive
officer, stated that Macmillan ``vigorously'' was attempting to
overturn a ruling that prevents the company from proceeding with an
extensive restructuring program announced after Bass's initial
overtures.
   The restructuring, which includes paying shareholders a special
dividend and splitting the company into two separate public
entities, was blocked last week by the Delaware Chancery Court at
Bass's request. Macmillan is appealing to the Delaware Supreme
Court.
   Maxwell's offer was conditioned upon the termination of the
restructuring plan and Macmillan's ``poison pill'' takeover
defense, and approval by the Macmillan board and shareholders.
   In a letter to Evans, Maxwell also requested his company get the
same access to confidential corporate information as Macmillan's
investment bankers.
   Maxwell Communications' North American headquarters, based in
Greenwich, Conn., control printing, telecommunications, database
services and publishing operations with annual revenue approaching
$1 billion.
   Some of the operations compete against Macmillan's publishing
and information services units, a Macmillan spokesman said.
   Bert Boksen, an analyst at Raymond James Financial Corp. in St.
Petersburg, Fla., said the entry of Maxwell into the bidding
``further complicates the situation for the Macmillan board ... it
will probably force them to find a true `white knight.'''
   He predicted a third bidder would surface and an auction would
ensue that would send Macmillan to the highest bidder.
   ``I still think the company is worth $90 to $95 a share,''
Boksen said.
   Coniston Partners, an aggressive New York investment firm that
holds a 4.9 stake in Macmillan, has maintained the company is worth
at least $85 a share.
   Robert Maxwell's worldwide operations reported 1987 sales of 884
million pounds, or about $1.53 billion at current exchange rates.
   In his most recent annual report, Maxwell said the company was
``on the road to becoming a global information and communications
empire before the end of the decade, with annual revenues of 3 to 5
million pounds with profit to match.''
   Maxwell's company is the largest printer in Britain, owns the
Mirror group of newspapers in Britain and publishes scientific
journals.
   Maxwell recently encountered the Bass group when it acquired a
2.3 percent stake in Bell & Howell Co. Maxwell ultimately decided
against making a bid for the Illinois information services company,
which Bass acquired in May for $700 million.
   Earlier this year, Maxwell offered $2 billion for Harcourt Brace
Jovanovich Inc., a publishing, theme park and insurance concern,
but withdrew the offer after Harcourt undertook a $3 billion
recapitalization.
   Maxwell Communication still spent $1 billion making smaller
acquisitions in the United States this past year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
