<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-88 0728EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     07-22 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0368</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Steady In Moderate Late-Morning European Dealings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar held steady in moderate late-morning
trading in Europe today after rebounding slightly from lows hit
earlier in the session.
   Gold prices fell, and silver prices seesawed.
   Foreign exchange traders in Italy predicted the dollar would
remain weak.
   ``Things are pretty schizophrenic. Last week the dollar raced,''
one trader said. ``This week nobody seems to want it.''
   She said she expected the dollar to edge back up early next
week, where it could run into renewed central bank intervention.
   A trader in Milan said players were keeping a close eye on the
strong pound. But he said the pound possibly had reached the upper
end of its recent ascent, buoyed by a recent increase in British
interest rates.
   In London, the British pound was quoted at $1.7350, compared
with $1.7265 Thursday.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Thursday's
rates, included: 1.8268 West German marks, down from 1.8375; 1.5165
Swiss francs, down from 1.5275; 6.1620 French francs, down from
6.2000; 2.0600 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0765; 1,359.50 Italian
lire, down from 1,363.50; and 1.1958 Canadian dollars, down from
1.1968.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends before Europe's begins,
the dollar fell 1.42 yen to a closing 132.08. Later, in London, it
was quoted at 131.15 yen.
   Dealers said gold was sidelined this morning as silver's
volatile movements again dominated the market.
   Dealers said continued confusion about the state of a miners'
strike in Peru could send the metal in any direction.
   Silver bounced up to about $7.86 an ounce in Europe before
retreating to about $7.76.
   Later, silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $7.80 a
troy ounce, down from Thursday's $7.81.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $443 a troy ounce,
compared with late Thursday's $445.80. At midmorning today, the
city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of
$443.20.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $443.10, down from $445.50 late
Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 43 cents to close at a bid
$444.86.
</TEXT>
