<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-88 0934EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-ShearsonProbe     07-22 0219</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Shearson Probe,0227</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shearson Cooperating In Stock-Lending Investigation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. said Friday it is
cooperating with the U.S. attorney's office in a probe looking at
certain transactions completed by the investment firm's stock-loan
operation.
   Reading from a prepared statement, Shearson spokesman Michael
O'Neill said, ``We have not been advised of the nature of the
inquiry, but nothing in our discussion with the attorney's office
suggests that the firm or any of its employees are the target of an
investigation.''
   He confirmed that the firm had received subpoenas relating to
its stock-lending business, which is involved in lending and
borrowing large blocks of stocks to and from brokerages and
institutional clients.
   According to a report in Thursday editions of The Washington
Post, the focus of the investigation is Dennis Palmeri, who
supervises Shearson's stock-lending operation.
   The Post said the subpoenas seek information about transactions
conducted over the last few years that involved Palmeri, two of his
relatives and several of his business entities.
   The stock-lending business has been under investigation by
federal prosecutors for several years, the paper reported.
   Citing unidentified sources, the New York Times reported in
Friday editions that the inquiry is believed to encompass one or
more employees of Seemala Corp., a securities firm controlled by
convicted felon Ivan Boesky.
</TEXT>
