<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-88 1011EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-FDIC-Continental     07-22 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-FDIC-Continental,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FDIC In Talks On Sale Of Its Continental Illinois Stock</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. is talking
with prospective buyers for the 70 percent stake in Continental
Illinois Corp. it acquired in bailing out the banking firm four
years ago, the agency's chairman said.
   While revealing the talks on the Continental Illinois shares, L.
William Seidman refused to say Thursday who has expressed an
interesting in purchasing the shares.
   He also said he couldn't predict when a sale might be completed.
   ``I'd love to come to a conclusion soon,'' he said after
speaking at a luncheon sponsored by the Chicago Association of
Commerce and Industry.
   ``We would be happy to talk to anybody who wants to acquire an
interest and who is a qualified buyer,'' he said.
   Seidman refused to say what price the FDIC would want for its
Continental shares, but said the ages stake at a ``reasonable''
price.
   Continental stock was up 37{ cents a share to $5.50 in early New
York Stock Exchange trading today.
   The FDIC sold about 10 percent of its Continental stock in
November 1986, receiving $5.25 a share.
   Continental nearly collapsed four years ago, but since its
bailout the bank's financial condition has improved and it is
restructuring its operations to concentrate on commercial banking.
   Seidman described Continental as ``a great bank with a strong
management and well-capitalized.''
   The FDIC is apparently seeking to reduce its investment in the
Chicago bank at a time when it is facing growing losses from bank
failures in Texas.
   Seidman said he expects the fund, which had a total net worth of
$18.3 billion at the end of 1987, to lose about 10 percent this
year as a result of payouts in bank failures and assistance to
threatened banks.
   This would be the first loss in the net worth of its deposit
insurance fund since the agency was founded in 1933.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
