<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0342</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crop futures opened mixed this morning as bearish
concerns about weekend showers in the thirsty Midwest offset
export-related buying, analysts said. Wheat and soybeans were
higher while corn was nearly unchanged.
   Although forecasters generally expected the weather in most
crop-growing states to turn warmer and drier over the weekend, some
predicted that scattered showers would sweep across the northern
Plains into the upper Midwest early next week.
   ``That's got everybody a little gun-shy because the last time we
were supposed to just get showers we got some good rains,'' said
John Frazier, grains analyst with Balfour Maclaine Corp. in Chicago.
   Despite the uncertainty about the weather, wheat prices rose on
the Agriculture Department's announcement of some new sales to
China, India and Iraq. Rumors that the Soviet Union was in the
market for soybean meal supported the soybean market, Frazier said.
   Corn opened lower on conjecture that recent rains had helped
some drought-stressed corn fields to recover, he said.
   In early trading, wheat was 3 cents to 4\ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.89 a bushel; corn was }
cent lower to { cent higher with September unchanged at $3.17 a
bushel; oats were 2 cents to 6 cents higher with September at
$2.69{ a bushel; soybeans were 4 cents to 7{ cents higher with
August at $8.49 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were higher and pork futures were sharply higher
in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle .08 cent to .48 cent higher with August at 66.10
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent to .75 cent higher with
August at 76.85 cents a pound; hogs were .13 cent to 1.28 cents
higher with August at 45.90 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.30 cent to the limit 2 cents higher with July at 39.75 cents a
pound.
   Livestock and meat futres settled sharply higher on Thursday.
</TEXT>
