<DOCNO> AP880722-0292 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-88 1436EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Eastern     07-22 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Eastern,0479</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eastern Announces Plan To Cut 4,000 Jobs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By A.J. DICKERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines said today it will eliminate
4,000 jobs and cut service to 14 cities on Aug. 31 and leave its
Western hub in a cost-cutting move one union immediately called a
``slap in the face.''
   ``We are preserving the airline. We're strengthening the
airline. I don't care to place the blame anywhere,'' Eastern
president Phil Bakes said, citing high operating costs and
competition for a $182 million loss in 1987.
   Personnel cuts through layoff and early retirement will affect
union and non-union employees and management, Bakes said. They will
include some 520 jobs in Miami, 300 in Atlanta and 350 in Kansas
City, Mo., which no longer will be the carrier's Western hub.
   Eastern's operations in Boston, New York, Washington, Atlanta
and Miami will be the core of the carrier's service, he said.
   The 12 percent reduction in workforce will free a proportional
percentage Eastern's fleet, which will be sold, he said.
   Eastern said service will be suspended in the following cities
beginning Aug. 31: Albuquerque, N.M.; Fort de France, Martinique;
Las Vegas, Nev.; Minneapolis-St. Paul, Minn.; Oklahoma City, Okla.;
Omaha, Neb.; Dallas; Pointe-a-Pitre, Guadeloupe; Reno-Lake Tahoe,
Nev.; San Antonio, Texas; San Diego, Calif.; St. Lucia, West
Indies; Tuscon, Ariz.; and Tulsa, Okla.
   Eastern is locked in bitter contract talks with its machinists
union. The union is seeking raises for the 10,000 workers it
represents, while the carrier is pressing for $161 million in such
cost concessions as pay cuts.
   The carrier seeks another $69 million in concessions from its
pilots union, which began formal contract talks with the company
Friday.
   ``We feel this is a very cavalier action by Texas Air and a real
slap in the face to the loyal Eastern employees of Kansas City, who
made the hub a success,'' said Ron Cole, spokesman for the Air Line
Pilot's Association.
   The unions contend that Frank Lorenzo's Texas Air Corp. is
trying to dismantle Eastern, selling off profitable assets and then
folding it into a sister subsidiary. Since Texas Air bought Eastern
for $676 million in November 1986, a sale the carriers' three major
unions unsuccessfully tried to block in court, Eastern has been
trimmed considerably.
   Eastern's parent firm Texas Air ended last year $466 million in
the red.
   Miami civic and business leaders are lobbying for federal
mediators to declare an impasse in the 7-month-old talks with
machinists. An impasse would trigger a 30-day ``cooling off''
period under federal law. The union would be free after that to
strike and the company to impose its latest proposal.
   The IAM is seeking a two-year contract with raises of 1.5
percent and 5 percent, which Eastern says will cost $50 million
yearly.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
