<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Close Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crop futures closed mostly lower Friday on the
Chicago Board of Trade in a lackluster session marked by
uncertainty about the Farm Belt weather outlook for the weekend and
beyond.
   Grain and soybean prices had fallen sharply earlier in the week
as showers swept across the dusty Midwest and the market has been
unable to sustain a rally since then because of speculation that
the drought pattern has weakened, analysts said.
   ``The bulls are really grasping here, trying to get things
recovered,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter
Reynolds Inc. in Chicago. ``What we need (to make prices rise) is a
return to hot, dry weather.''
   Forecasters generally expected temperatures in the Midwest to
turn warmer over the weekend but some also predicted scattered
showers, and traders were hesitant to establish new positions.
   ``Everybody's a little gun-shy because the last time we were
supposed to just get showers we got some good rains,'' said John
Frazier, grain specialist with Balfour Maclaine Corp. in Chicago.
   At the close, wheat was 2 cents lower to 2 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.84{ a bushel; corn was 2
cents to 5 cents lower with September at $3.12 a bushel; corn was
9{ cents lower to 2 cents higher with September at $2.60 a bushel;
soybeans were 10{ cents lower to 20 cents higher with August at
$8.32 a bushel.
</TEXT>
