<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Chips,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strong Semiconductor Market Boosts Texas Instruments Earnings 39
Percent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas Instruments Inc., citing the strongest semiconductor
market growth in four years, Friday announced a profit of $92
million for the second quarter, an increase of 39 percent over
earnings of $66 million for the same period in 1987.
   The strong quarter lifted earnings of the Dallas-based company
for the first half of the year to $177 million, compared with $156
million for the first six months of 1987.
   Earnings per common share for the second quarter were $1.02,
compared with 78 cents in 1987. That increased earnings per common
share to $1.97 for the first half of 1988 from $1.90 last year.
   Revenue for the quarter that ended June 30, measured as net
sales billed, climbed to $1.56 billion from $1.37 billion, said the
company, whose products include semiconductors, computer systems
and defense electronics systems.
   For the first six months of the year, revenue rose to $3.03
billion from $2.64 billion.
   Jerry R. Junkins, the chief executive, said an expanding U.S.
economy coupled with strong industrial markets in the Asia-Pacific
and European regions resulted in double-digit growth in electronic
equipment shipments.
   Net sales billed in semiconductors reached an all-time high in
the second quarter through a combination of greater production and
higher prices, the company said.
</TEXT>
