<1ST_LINE>r f AM-BankBid     07-22 0500</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bank Bid,0516</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Irving Urges End To Hostile Takeover Fight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Irving Bank Corp. on Friday urged Bank of New
York Co. to abandon its protracted takeover attempt, saying the
battle was ``effectively at an end'' since the hostile suitor gave
no indication that it planned to wage another proxy battle.
   But Bank of New York spokesman Owen Brady said the company had
no intention of ending its merger plans, which began last
September. He said Bank of New York could, based on a court ruling,
seek another proxy vote on its nominees to Irving's board of
directors.
   ``We have no present intention of waging another proxy battle
... but we're not going to reveal our business strategies,'' he
said.
   The New York Supreme Court, overturning the result of a previous
proxy vote, recently ruled that holders of 10 percent of Irving's
stock had the right to call special meetings. However, the court
confirmed the re-election of Irving's board of directors, which had
been contested by Bank of New York.
   The state court also struck down a provision of Irving's
anti-takeover ``poison pill,'' intended to make unsolicited
takeover bids prohibitively expensive, although Irving has appealed
that ruling.
   The provision would have allowed all shareholders, except a
hostile acquirer, to buy $400 worth of Irving shares for $200 if
any suitor bought more than 20 percent of Irving stock without the
support of Irving's management.
   ``With this favorable court ruling (regarding the board's
re-election) ... we believe that this hostile takeover attempt is
effectively at an end,'' Irving said in a statment. ``... We urge
Bank of New York's board to step in and direct its management to
cease its hostile activities, which have been disruptive and costly
to both banking companies.''
   Irving's board favors a friendly merger with the state-run Banca
Commerciale Italiana SpA, Italy's second largest bank.
   Banca Commerciale offered $80 a share for 51 percent of Irving's
18.5 million common shares outstanding, plus warrants entitling
shareholders to buy newly issued Irving stock at $65 a share over
the next seven years. Stockholders would receive one warrant for
every four shares they currently owned. The blended value was as
much as $76.50 per share.
   The merger proposal is part of a complex defensive restructuring
plan that includes, among other things, sale of Irving assets,
cost-cutting measures and a special cash dividend.
   Bank of New York, which owns a 4.9 percent stake in Irving, is
offering $15 in cash and 1.575 shares of its own stock for each of
Irving's common shares outstanding. The offer is valued at around
$68 a share or $1.2 billion.
   Bank of New York and many private banking analysts have
maintained that Bank of New York's hostile offer was superior to
that of Banca Commerciale largely because the New York bank already
had received conditional regulatory approval. That approval expires
Sept. 7.
   The takeover battle has attracted widespread interest in the
banking industry because hostile bank takeover efforts are
relatively rare.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880722-0301 </DOCNO>
