<HEAD>Cap Cities-ABC Earnings up 14 Percent in Second Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Capital Cities-ABC Inc. said its second-quarter
earnings rose more than 14 percent as the broadcast and publishing
company benefitted from lower tax rates.
   Capital Cities-ABC said it earned $113.9 million, or $6.78 a
share, up from $99.7 million, or $5.88 a share, in the same period
of 1987.
   Revenue increased during the quarter to $1.16 billion from $1.13
billion in the second three months of last year.
   The company said weakness in the national advertising market led
to only modest growth in broadcasting and publishing revenue.
   It said the increase in second-quarter earnings was attributable
primarily to lower income tax rates.
   For the first half, Capital Cities-ABC said it earned $184.2
million, or $10.93 a share, up nearly 49 percent from $123.7
million, or $7.35 a share, for the first six months of 1987.
   First-half revenue increased to $2.45 billion from $2.09 billion.
   Capital Cities-ABC operates ABC's television and radio networks
and stations, 21 other radio stations and provides cable television
programming. It also publishes nine daily newspapers, weekly
newpapers and other publications and distributes information from
electronic databases.
</TEXT>
