<2ND_LINE>AM-Burger King-Management,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Burger King Announces Management Changes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burger King Corp. has made three key managerial
changes in an effort to strengthen the fast-food chain's top
management, company president Charles S. Olcott announced Friday.
   Olcott, president and chief operating officer of Burger King
Corp., said in a release Friday that the changes are effective
immediately.
   The nation's second-biggest fast food chain, behind industry
leader McDonald's Corp., Burger King has reported sluggish sales
growth over the past two years.
   Ronald Petty, 44, president of Burger King International, has
been named president of Burger King USA. Petty joined Burger King
operations in 1978 as vice president of real estate.
   Richard Snead, 36, executive vice president for development and
for the North Central Division, has been named president of Burger
King International. Snead joined Burger King in 1978 as a senior
site engineer for the San Francisco region.
   Kevin Moriarty, 40, region vice president and general manager of
the Chicago region, has been named executive vice president and
division manager for the North Central Division, with
responsibility for the Chicago, Detroit and Minneapolis regions. He
joined Burger King in 1974 as an assistant restaurant manager in
Long Island.
   ``The promotion of these three veteran Burger King Corporation
leaders will further strengthen our top management group and better
enable us to provide increased service to our customers and
franchisees as we move into the new fiscal year,'' said Olcott.
   Burger King Corp. and its franchisees operate more than 5,500
restaurants worldwide. A wholly-owned subsidiary of The Pillsbury
Co., Burger King Corp. and its franchises have systemwide sales in
excess of $5 billion.
</TEXT>
