<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-88 2106EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-American-Hub     07-22 0443</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-American-Hub,0458</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Airlines Gives Up Plan to Operate European Hub</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Discovering more competition than
expected, American Airlines told the State Department it will not
accept the authorization to fly between West Berlin and three
cities in West Germany.
   Officials at the airline made the notification Thursday because
of the ``excessive capacity levels authorized on these routes.''
Making a profit woul be almost impossible, American said.
   The airline was surprised that the three nations that govern
West Berlin _ the United States, France and Britain _ had granted
as much new service to the city as they did last month, American
spokesman Steve McGregor said.
   ``We've run the numbers several times over the last few weeks,
and they just don't work for us, in either a short- or a long-term
sense,'' he said. ``And this airline is just not prepared to enter
into any markets where we know we would have to lose money for a
long, long time.''
   American petitioned the three nations late last year for
permission to build a connecting hub complex in West Berlin.
   The airline's plan was to serve Hamburg, Dusseldorf,
Cologne-Bonn, Frankfurt and Munich in West Germany; Zurich,
Switzerland; and Vienna, Austria, from West Berlin. Three other
U.S. airlines followed with similar plans for West Berlin service.
   American pulled back after learning that the three nations
authorized nearly twice as many new flights between West Berlin and
cities in the West as there had been previously.
   American had been awarded four daily round trips to Frankfurt,
three to Munich and three to Cologne-Bonn. Trans World Airlines was
given four daily round trips to Frankfurt, two to Hamburg and two
to Stuttgart, West Germany.
   Pan American World Airways, which had been the only U.S. carrier
serving West Berlin, was granted three more round trips daily to
Dusseldorf.
   British Airways PLC, which already serves West Berlin, was given
28 new round trips a week between West Berlin and Frankfurt and a
total of 56 new flights each week to points in the West.
   Also, a new airline to be formed as a joint venture between Air
France, which already serves West Berlin, and West Germany's
Lufthansa was given 36 round trips a week to Frankfurt, 19 to
Cologne-Bonn, 25 to Munich and 25 to Stuttgart.
   The three countries created rights to 120 new round trips
between West Berlin and Frankfurt alone, in hopes of stimulating
price and service competition on what previously had been a tightly
protected and high-cost route.
   McGregor said four McDonnell Douglas MD-80 airplanes that
American would have used for West Berlin service will now be
employed on domestic routes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
