<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Kellogg,0179</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cereal Maker's Earnings Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATTLE CREEK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kellogg Co. said Friday its
second-quarter earnings climbed 26 percent as its sales rose 17.7
percent from a year ago.
   The world's cereal-maker said its profit rose to $112.7 million,
or 92 cents a share, for the three months ending June 30, from
$89.8 million or 72 cents a share for the second quarter of 1987.
   April-through-June sales rose to $1.09 billion from $920.7
million in the year-earlier period.
   Earnings for the period benefited both from the increased cereal
sales and from the lowered U.S. statutory income tax rate, the
company said.
   For the first six months of the year, Kellogg reported net
earnings of $233.8 million, or $1.90 a share on sales of $2.12
billion, up from $194.3 million, or $1.57 a share, on sales of
$1.82 billion in the first half of 1987.
   Kellogg sells 37 cereal products in the United States. It
manufactures cereals in 17 countries and sells them in 130
countries around the world.
</TEXT>
