<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Polaroid     07-22 0430</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Polaroid,0446</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Polaroid Stock Jumps on Second Bid Speculation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polaroid Corp.'s stock jumped in heavy trading
Friday amid speculation that a ``white knight'' may emerge to
compete with a bid that values the instant camera company at more
than $2 billion.
   Polaroid rose 87{ cents a share to finish at $40.75 in composite
New York Stock Exchange trading, which was slightly above the
$40-a-share Roy E. Disney offered on Wednesday through Shamrock
Holdings Inc.
   Nearly 2.6 million shares traded hands, more than three times
Polaroid's normal daily volume.
   Polaroid, which jumped $7.75 on the week, has hinted that it
would reject the bid from Disney, nephew of the late Walt Disney.
The company said it had no comment on Friday's stock movement.
   Among a number of rumors circulating in the finanical markets
were hints that Goldman, Sachs & Co. had placed Polaroid on its
restricted list, indicating it might be representing a bidder for
the Cambridge, Mass.-based company.
   A Goldman spokesman could not confirm or deny the rumor, but
Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. analyst Eugene Glazer said Goldman
typically did not represent unwanted suitors. ``By that firm's
nature they would not represent a hostile bidder,'' he said.
   It also was rumored that Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. had agreed
to finance Shamrock's bid.
   Among the speculative list of potential ``white knights'' is
Fuji Photo Film Co. of Tokyo, said B. Alex Henderson, a vice
president and senior securities analyst at Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc.
   Among other companies that might be interested in Polaroid from
a strictly financial perspective were a handful of Japanese
consumer electronics companies, including Sony Corp., Toshiba Corp.
and Hitachi Ltd., analysts said.
   Henderson noted that imaging ``is a very hot area right now, and
current developments in the computer arena make imaging-related
products much more important to the mainstream computing world.''
   Shamrock's offer values Polaroid at about $2.88 billion based on
71.9 million shares outstanding. But Shamrock has indicated it
might not proceed unless it manages to get the recent issue of 10
million shares rescinded. That would lower the value of the bid to
$2.48 billion.
   Polaroid unveiled a retrenchment plan earlier this month calling
for layoffs and cost-cutting.
   After Disney unveiled his proposal, Polaroid management issued a
statement reiterating its support for the restructuring. ``We
firmly believe that this is, without doubt, the right course for
Polaroid and for all of its shareholders, employees, customers and
communities,'' it said.
   Henderson said the plan gives ``a strong indication ... that
they are going to protect themselves.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
