<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-88 2115EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ContinentalAdFlap     07-22 0300</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Continental Ad Flap,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Better Business Bureau Says No Way to Continental Ad</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If you mean Newark, N.J., why say Pittsburgh?
asks the Better Business Bureau of New York.
   Because Pittsburgh isn't the issue, says Continental Airlines.
   Confused?
   So are many readers of a Continental advertisement that appears
to suggest the airline can get you to Pittsburgh from Manhattan's
Penn Station in 42 minutes, says the Better Business Bureau of
Metropolitan New York.
   The BBB said Friday that the ad is deceptive and should be
discontinued.
   But the airline defended the ad as being no more dishonest than
ads featuring raisins that sing or cats that talk and said it would
continue to appear in local newspapers.
   ``Advertising hyperbole is a well-established, longstanding,
absolutely straightforward methodology to inform readers, viewers,
listeners. That's exactly what this ad does,'' Bruce Hicks, a
Continental spokesman, said from the company headquarters in
Houston.
   In a bold headline the ad promises: ``Penn Station to
Pittsburgh. 42 min.''
   Following the headline, in much smaller type, the ad explains
that 42 minutes is the average travel time from Penn Station to
Newark Airport during rush hours.
   ``The issue isn't Pittsburgh,'' Hicks said, ``it's how close
Newark Airport is to much of Manhattan.''
   Still, the BBB's president, Barbara Berger Opotowsky, is not
mollified and said the ad ``creates a misconception to the reader''
and ``an impression with no basis in reality.''
   Ms. Opotowsky said she has referred the matter to the state
attorney general and New York City's Department of Consumer Affairs.
   So, how long does it take to get to Pittsburgh from Penn Station?
   Assuming that after 42 minutes travel time you arrive at the
Newark terminal 30 minutes before the 8:40 a.m. flight, the entire
journey should take you 171 minutes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
