<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Holiday,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reports Profit Gain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Holiday Corp. said Thursday its
second-quarter profit rose 33 percent despite a 3 percent decline
in revenue.
   The lodging and gaming company said its earnings rose to $99.8
million, or $4 a share, for the three months ended July 1 compared
with a profit of $74.9 million, or $3.12 a share, a year earlier.
   Second-quarter revenue slipped to $410.4 million from $423.3
million a year earlier.
   The company said operating income for its gaming operations
increased 31.8 percent, largely because of a 73.2 percent
improvement in operating income at Harrah's Marina In Atlantic City.
   Operating income for hotels declined by 7.7 percent due to the
sale of 40 hotels over the past year, the company said.
   The company said results for the quarter reflected gains of
$154.1 million on the sale of 23 hotels and other assets. The
results also included an extraordinary charge of $6 million
associated with early retirement of debt.
   The company reported a total debt at the end of the quarter of
$2.2 billion, compared with $2.8 billion at the end of the same
period last year.
   For the first six months, Holiday said its earnings fell 27
percent to $81.1 million, or $3.26 a share, from $111.4 million, or
$4.65 a share, a year earlier.
   Revenues for the first half fell 1.9 percent to $806.7 million
from $822.7 million a year earlier.
   The results included a charge of $24.8 million for early debt
retirement in the latest quarter, compared with a charge of $3.5
million a year earlier.
   Holiday Corp. is the parent company of Holiday Inn, Embassy
Suites, Hampton Inn, Homewood Suites and Harrah's.
</TEXT>
