<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Knight-Ridder,0246</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Posts Profit Gain for 2nd-Qtr</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Knight-Ridder Inc. said Friday its second-quarter
profit rose 4.7 percent as a lower tax rate helped offset a weak
advertising market and higher newsprint prices.
   The media concern said it earned $45 million, or 78 cents a
share, in the three months ended June 30, compared with $43
million, or 73 cents a share, a year earlier.
   Operating revenue rose 3.4 percent to $544.6 million from $526.9
million in the second quarter of 1987.
   But operating income slipped 9.9 percent to $79.3 million for
the quarter from $88.1 million a year earlier.
   ``Weak retail and general advertising revenues, high newsprint
prices in our newspaper division and soft national television
advertising revenues contributed to a drop in operating profit,''
said Knight-Ridder's chief financial officer, Robert Singleton.
   ``But the benefits of a tax cut and other non-operating items,
including the purchase of over 2 million shares of our stock in the
past 12 months, resulted in gains in net income and earnings per
share,'' Singleton said.
   For the first six months of 1988, Knight-Ridder posted a profit
of $78.8 million, or $1.37 a share, up 10.1 percent from $71.6
million, or $1.22 a share, a year earlier.
   Six-month operating revenue rose 3.9 percent to $1.06 billion
from $1.02 billion a year earlier.
   Knight-Ridder owns 30 newspapers and eight television stations
and has interests in cable television.
</TEXT>
