<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-ConsumerProducts 1stLd-Writethru   07-22 0747</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Consumer Products, 1st Ld-Writethru,0770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Brands, RJR Nabisco, Colgate, Kraft Post Profit Gains</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with RJR and Kraft results.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   American Brands Inc. said Thursday its second-quarter profit
climbed 44 percent, while another food and tobacco concern, RJR
Nabisco Inc., said its profit rose 18 percent for the quarter.
   Consumer products giant Kraft Inc. the sale of its Duracell
battery division helped spark a seven-fold increase in its
second-quarter earnings, and Colgate-Palmolive Co. said its profit
rose 17 percent from a year ago.
   American Brands, headquartered in Old Greenwich, Conn., said its
net income for the quarter ended June 30 soared 44 percent to
$154.6 million, or $1.57 a share, from $107.4 million, or 94 cents
a share, in the year-ago period.
   Revenue jumped 27 percent to $2.49 billion from $1.96 billion in
the second quarter of 1987. The figures include subsidiaries
purchased from E-II Holdings Inc. in February in a deal valued at
$2.7 billion.
   Among the company's core businesses, tobacco and distilled
spirits put in a strong performance. Sales in the hardware, home
and office products unit more than doubled, partly because of
acquisitions.
   For the year's first half, the company reported net income of
$305 million, or $2.97 a share, up 28 percent from $238.2 million,
or $2.09 a share, in the year-ago period. Revenue totaled $5.40
billion, up 29 percent from $4.18 billion in the first half of 1987.
   American Brands' main brands are Lucky Strike and Pall Mall
cigarettes, Jim Beam bourbon and Gilbey's gin.
   RJR Nabisco, based in Atlanta, reported its second-quarter
profit rose to $354 million, or $1.50 a share, from $299 million,
or $1.16 a share, in 1987.
   The company said its sales rose 6.5 percent to $4.3 billion from
$4 billion in the second quarter of 1987.
   RJR Nabisco businesses include R.J. Reynolds Tobacco, Nabisco
Brands, Del Monte Foods and Planters LifeSavers.
   The company's tobacco sales for the second quarter were $1.8
billion, up 7.5 percent from $1.7 billion in 1987. Income from
operations rose to $496 million, a 7.6 percent increase from $461
miullion the prior year.
   The company's food business division achieved second quarter
sales of $2.5 billion, an increase of 5.9 percent from $2.3 billion
in 1987. Income from operations rose to $271 million, up 14 percent
from $238 million.
   For the first six months of the year, RJR said it earned $627
million, or $2.59 a share, on revenue of $8.08 billion, compared
with a profit of $519 million, or $2 a share, on revenue of $7.51
billion, a year earlier.
   Kraft, based in Glenview, Ill., reported net income of $785
million, or $6.10 per share, in the second quarter, compared with
$113 million, or 83 cents a share, for the same period a year ago.
   Sales increased 13 percent to $2.8 billion from $2.4 billion in
the second quarter of 1987, Kraft said.
   The results include a $686 million after-tax gain from the June
24 sale of Duracell to a group led by Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co.
Excluding a total gain of $658 from that transaction and other
discontinued operations, Kraft's net income for the quarter totaled
$127.3 million.
   Kraft's largest division, U.S. consumer foods, had sales of $1.2
billion to lead all units in revenue production, while the U.S.
commercial foods division showed the greatest improvement with a 21
percent increase in sales to nearly $882 million.
   For the first half of 1988, Kraft had net income of $903.5
million, or $7 per share, compared with $265 million, or $1.94 per
share, for the first half of 1987.
   First-half revenues increased 14.5 percent, to $5.4 billion from
$4.7 billion.
   Colgate-Palmolive, maker of soaps, toilet and health care
products and pet food, reported net income of $65.5 million, or 96
cents a share, up 17 percent from $56.1 million, or 82 cents a
share, in the second quarter of 1987.
   Sales for the New York-based Colgate totaled $1.19 billion, up 9
percent from $1.09 billion a year ago.
   The company noted that profits from its household and personal
care operations showed strong gains overseas. Specialty marketing
sales were boosted by increased sales at Hill's Pet Products, which
recently began advertising nationally.
   For the first six months, net income rose 16 percent to $130.9
million, or $1.91 a share, from $112.5 million, or $1.62 a share in
the year-ago period. Revenue totaled $2.33 billion, up 12 percent
from $2.08 billion in the first half of 1987.
</TEXT>
