<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-88 2131EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Peru-Silver     07-22 0562</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru-Silver,0580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Peru Orders State Mines to Sell Their Silver to Central Bank</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT SEAVEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Friday ordered state mines
to sell their silver to the Central Bank and offered private miners
more money for the metal in an effort to boost Peru's faltering
economy.
   Agriculture Minister Remigio Morales Bermudez said the
government may use the silver to build up a $750 million reserve to
import food.
   Current silver sales contracts will be respected and private
mine companies can still sell their silver abroad independently,
according to a decree published Friday in the official gazette El
Peruano.
   Analysts said it was unclear if the government would negotiate
new sales contracts with the silver it controls.
   The decree said the silver is earmarked to boost Peru's foreign
reserves, which have declined dramatically.
   A lack of dollar reserves to purchase imports needed for
economic growth has sparked widespread shortages of basic consumer
and industrial items and contributed to Peru's rocketing inflation,
estimated to reach 400 percent this year.
   The action comes with the nation's important mineral industry
slowed due to an indefinite nationwide mining strike, which began
Monday.
   The strike and the government new silver measures have created
uncertainty in international metal markets, causing some commodity
prices to fluctuate, news reports said.
   Silver futures posted sharp gains on New York's Commodity
Exchange in reaction to the continuing miners' strike in Peru. If
the government's plan to buy the metal continues, analysts said it
would likely prove bullish for silver prices.
   Peru is the world's second leading supplier of the metal behind
Mexico and a major source of copper, lead, zinc and gold.
   Private producers account for 58 percent of Peru's annual silver
output, estimated at 60 million ounces last year. Silver exports in
1987 reached $300 million. Total mineral exports were $1.2 billion,
slightly less than half of all sales abroad.
   The decree included an offer for private silver producers to
sell their production to the state in contracts lasting up to three
years.
   Both state and private silver producers would be paid 15 percent
more for their output than the international silver price. The
decree said payment would be in local currency at a floating bank
exchange rate. The rate is slightly less that the free market
exchange rate, which was 202 intis to the dollar Thursday.
   The government currently requires private and state mining firms
to exchange the dollars they receive from foreign mineral sales at
a fixed exchange rate of 101 intis to the dollar.
   Despite the higher price offered in the decree, industry
analysts said it was unclear how private miners would react. They
said the government has frequently altered its exchange rates and
if the floating bank rate were frozen, Peru's high inflation could
erode any gains the measure holds for mine companies.
   The nation's largest silver mines have continued to work despite
the strike, industry officials said. But silver mining operations
at Centromin, the largest state-owned silver producer, have been
cut by at least 50 percent, according to company and federation
officials.
   The strike organizer, the National Federation of Mine, Metal and
Steel Workers, which claims to represent 75 percent of the nation's
mine workers, is demanding unified labor contracts among all
unionized miners and quarterly cost of living salary increases. The
government has rejected the demands.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
