<FILEID>AP-NR-07-22-88 1849EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp 1stLd-Writethru   07-22 0878</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru,0905</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Retreat On Weather Jitters</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS grafs 11-12 to CORRECT that silver futures fell sted
rose; picks up 13th graf pvs bg'ng, ``If in ...; SUBS 15th graf to
CORRECT that silver lower; picks up 16th graf pvs bg'ng, Near-month
pork ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Most crop futures prices moved lower Friday on the Chicago Board
of Trade in a lackluster session featuring profit-taking and
uncertainty about the Farm Belt weather outlook for the weekend and
beyond.
   On other markets, silver futures were sharply higher; livestock
and meat were mostly higher; energy futures were lower; and
stock-index futures retreated.
   Soybean prices for near-term delivery fell for the fifth
straight day, bringing the August contract to just over $8.30 a
bushel, the lowest price for near-month delivery since June 2.
   Grain and soybean prices fell sharply earlier in the week as
showers swept across the dusty Midwest. The market has been unable
to sustain a rally since then because of speculation that the
drought pattern that drove soybeans to a 15-year high of nearly $11
a bushel on June 23 has weakened, analysts said.
   ``The bulls are really grasping here, trying to get things
recovered,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter
Reynolds Inc. in Chicago. ``What we need (to make prices rise) is a
return to hot, dry weather.''
   Forecasters generally expected temperatures in the Midwest to
turn warmer over the weekend but some also predicted scattered
showers, and traders were hesitant to establish new positions.
   ``Everybody's a little gun-shy because the last time we were
supposed to just get showers we got some good rains,'' said John
Frazier, grain specialist with Balfour Maclaine Corp. in Chicago.
   After the close, the National Weather Service issued a
6-to-10-day forecast calling for hot and mostly dry conditions to
prevail in the Farm Belt during the latter part of next week.
   Losses in the wheat market were limited by Agriculture
Department reports of new export deals with China, India and Iraq,
analysts said.
   Wheat settled 2 cents lower to 1 cent higher with the contract
for delivery in September at $3.84{ a bushel; corn was \ cent to 4{
cents lower with September at $3.12{ a bushel; oats were 9{ cents
lower to 2{ cents higher with September at $2.60 a bushel; soybeans
were 12 cents lower to 20 cents higher with August at $8.30{ a
bushel.
   Silver futures fell on New York's Commodity Exchange.
   The market reacted with skepticism to potentially bullish
reports that the Peruvian central bank planned to acquire all of
the nation's silver output _ accounting for 20-35 percent of world
production _ instead of allowing it to be sold on the international
market.
   ``If in fact they do hold it back for a long period of time,
it's very bullish for silver,'' said Jack Barbanel, director of
futures trading for Gruntal & Co. in New York.
   But, he said, ``the information is really mixed on whether
they're going to hold it back. And the market just cannot gauge
what is going to be the final outcome of this.''
   Gold settled unchanged to 20 cents higher with August at $442.90
a troy ounce; silver was 13.1 cents to 14.8 cents lower with July
at $7.606 a troy ounce.
   Near-month pork futures advanced their permitted limits on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange for the second consecutive session in
response to strong cash markets and anticipation of a seasonal
upswing in retail demand.
   Cattle futures advanced in cautious trading ahead of the USDA's
quarterly 13-state and monthly 7-state cattle-on-feed reports.
   The reports showed slightly more cattle being fattened for
slaughter than the trade had expected and analysts pronounced it
slightly bearish for near-term contracts.
   More startling was the USDA's projected third-quarter marketings
figure of 6.2 million head, which would make the number of cattle
sold for slaughter during the current quarter the largest in U.S.
history, said Chuck Levitt, livestock analyst in Chicago for
Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   The USDA also issued a monthly cold storage report showing 104.7
million pounds of frozen pork bellies in storage on June 30, a 220
percent increase over a year ago and the third-largest June 30
figure in history.
   Live cattle settled unchanged to .55 cent higher with August at
66.12 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent to .97 cent higher
with August at 77.37 cents a pound; hogs were .42 cent lower to the
limit 1.50 cents higher with ugust at 46.12 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were 1.45 cents lower to 2 cents higher with July at
39.75 cents a pound.
   Energy futures prices were slightly lower on the New York
Mercantile Exchange after Persian Gulf developments cast a pall on
early trading and technical factors brought the market back.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 1 cent to 16 cents
lower with September at $16.38 a barrel; heating oil was .53 cent
to .73 cent lower with August at 44.95 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was unchanged to .18 cent lower with August at 52.07 cents
a gallon.
   Stock-index futures retreated on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, where the contract for September delivery of the Standard
& Poor's 500 index settled 3.60 points lower at 263.55.
</TEXT>
